var e=`Subjective Evolution of Consciousness`,t=`en-SubjectiveEvolutionofConsciousness`,n=[{title:`The Play of the Sweet Absolute`,paragraphs:[{class:`b34`,text:`\r`},{class:`b35`,text:` All glory to ≈örƒ´ Guru and ≈örƒ´ GaurƒÅ·πÖga`},{class:`b36`,text:` Subjective Evolution of Consciousness`},{class:`b75`,text:` The Play of the Sweet Absolute`},{class:`b37`,text:` His Divine Grace`},{class:`b38`,text:` ≈örƒ´la Bhakti Rak·π£ak ≈örƒ´dhar Dev-GoswƒÅmƒ´ MahƒÅrƒÅj`},{class:`b76`,text:` ¬© 1989 Sri Chaitanya Saraswat Math`},{class:`b39`,text:` All rights reserved by:`},{class:`b40`,text:` The Successor President-Acharya<br />Sri Chaitanya Saraswat Math, Nabadwip`},{class:`b39`,text:` First Printing in 1989: 3,000 copies`},{class:`b40`,text:` Guardian of Devotion Press`},{class:`b39`,text:` Second Printing 1998: 2,500 copies`},{class:`b40`,text:` Ananta Printing and Publishing`},{class:`b39`,text:` Editors:`},{class:`b40`,text:` Bhakti Sudhir Goswami<br />Bhakti Vidhan Mahayogi`},{class:`b39`,text:` Assistants:`},{class:`b40`,text:` Alwarnatha Prabhu, Vidagdha Madhava Prabhu, Bhakta Priya Devi, Ananga Manjari Devi, Ramananda Prabhu, Jayananda Prabhu, and Mukunda Prabhu`},{class:`b39`,text:` Contributors:`},{class:`b40`,text:` Sripad Tripurari Swami Maharaj, Yudhamanyu Prabhu Seva Vikram, Sri Balaram Prabhu, and Divya Sari Devi`},{class:`b39`,text:` Special thanks to the following devotees for their help with the second edition:`},{class:`b41`,text:` Swami B.P. Janardan, Swami B. C. Parvat, Nabadwip Prabhu, Sarvabhavana Prabhu, Ananta Krishna Prabhu, Tilak Devi Dasi`}]},{title:`Contents`,paragraphs:[{class:`b46`,text:`\r`},{class:`b47`,text:` Contents`},{class:`b48`,text:` <span class="e1">Preface</span>`},{class:`b48`,text:` <span class="e1">Fossilism, Hypnotism, & The Cosmos</span>`},{class:`b48`,text:` <span class="e1">The Creation</span>`},{class:`b48`,text:` <span class="e1">Consciousness & Evolution</span>`},{class:`b48`,text:` <span class="e1">The Plane of Misconception</span>`},{class:`b48`,text:` <span class="e1">A Floating World of Experience</span>`},{class:`b48`,text:` <span class="e1">Thesis, Antithesis, & Synthesis</span>`},{class:`b48`,text:` <span class="e1">The Supersubject</span>`},{class:`b48`,text:` <span class="e1">Science vs. Nescience</span>`},{class:`b48`,text:` <span class="e1">Spiritual Evolution</span>`},{class:`b48`,text:` <span class="e1">Pure Devotion</span>`},{class:`b48`,text:` <span class="e1">The Subjective Bhagavad-gƒ´tƒÅ</span>`},{class:`b48`,text:` <span class="e1">The GƒÅyatrƒ´ Mantra</span>`},{class:`b49`,text:` <span class="e1">About The Author</span>`}]},{title:`Preface`,paragraphs:[{class:`b46`,text:`\r`},{class:`b47`,text:` Preface`},{class:`b43`,text:` Evolution is generally thought of as something objective. But objective evolution is a misperception of reality. Evolution is actually based on consciousness, which is subjective. Subjective evolution, however, seems to be objective evolution to the ignorant.`},{class:`b44`,text:` In ignorance, we think of ourselves as subjects, although in reality the Lord is the subject and we are His objects. We think of ourselves as proprietors although we are His property.`},{class:`b44`,text:` It is said that all things happen by the will of the Vai·π£·πáavas, the devotees of the Lord. A Vai·π£·πáava is like a faithful employee who speaks the will of the employer; he has no will of his own: the will of the pure Vai·π£·πáava is nothing but the will of God. In ignorance, however, we try to make the Lord our servant, but this is like using a ≈öƒÅlagrƒÅm-≈õilƒÅ to crack nuts. The Lord is not an object. He is the seer, the doer, and the knower‚Äîthe Supreme Subject‚Äîbut we foolishly think of ourselves as such.`},{class:`b51`,text:` The concept of subjective evolution is explained in <span class="e3">≈örƒ´mad BhƒÅgavatam</span> (10.14.22):`},{class:`b60`,text:` tasmƒÅd ida·πÅ jagad a≈õe·π£am asat-svar≈´pa·πÅ<br />svapnƒÅbham asta-dhi·π£a·πáa·πÅ puru-du·∏•kha-du·∏•kham`},{class:`b43`,text:` ‚ÄúBy an illusion created by the Lord, the universe appears to be real, although it is not, just as miseries we suffer in a dream are only imaginary.‚Äù`},{class:`b51`,text:` Unintelligent people take the subject as an object. It is ignorance to confuse the eye with the seer, or the brain with the knower. This is described in <span class="e3">≈örƒ´mad BhƒÅgavatam</span> (1.3.31):`},{class:`b60`,text:` yathƒÅ nabhasi meghaugho re·πáur vƒÅ pƒÅrthivo ‚Äônile<br />eva·πÅ dra·π£·π≠ari d·πõ≈õyatvam ƒÅropitam abuddhibhi·∏•`},{class:`b43`,text:` ‚ÄúThe unintelligent equate the sky with the clouds, the air with the dust particles floating in it, and think that the sky is cloudy or that the air is dirty.‚Äô‚Äô`},{class:`b44`,text:` Consciousness is not a product of the world; the world is a product of consciousness. This world is a perverted reflection of the spiritual world. In the material world, the world of exploitation, as Darwin says, it is a question of survival of the fittest. We must exploit to survive: <span class="e3">jƒ´vo jƒ´vasya jƒ´vanam</span>. But in the spiritual world, the land of dedication, everyone is a serving unit. There we will find a happy life through dedication.`},{class:`b52`,text:` In that supersubjective realm, ≈örƒ´ K·πõ·π£·πáa is eternally engaged in His divine play with His most intimate servitors. And as our consciousness evolves through dedication, we will find our highest prospect there, where we have a part to play in the Pastimes of the Sweet Absolute.`}]},{title:`Fossilism, Hypnotism, & The Cosmos`,paragraphs:[{class:`b46`,text:`\r`},{class:`b47`,text:` Fossilism, Hypnotism, & The Cosmos`},{class:`b99`,text:` This chapter is an excerpt from a conversation between ≈örƒ´la ≈örƒ´dhar MahƒÅrƒÅj, neurophysiologist Dr. Daniel Murphey, and physical organic chemist Dr. Thoudam Singh.`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Dr. Singh:</span> When scientists speak of evolution, they mean that life has evolved from matter. I have heard you speak of evolution with quite a different concept. You say that everything is evolving from consciousness.`},{class:`b43`,text:` <span class="e2">≈örƒ´la ≈örƒ´dhar MahƒÅrƒÅj:</span> Yes, consciousness comes first and then matter. The basis of all things material is consciousness, which is spiritual. Consciousness can contact consciousness directly. When consciousness comes into the stage of matter, material conception, we experience a kind of vague consciousness; first there is hazy consciousness and then material consciousness. But everything has its spiritual side. And as eternal souls, our direct connection is really only with the conscious aspect of existence. For example, the earth is conceived of as a woman. According to the Vedas, the presiding deity of the earth is a woman. And the sun is conceived of as a devatƒÅ, a male god.`},{class:`b51`,text:` The soul, coming into material consciousness, must come through some hazy reflection of consciousness, chidƒÅbhƒÅs. Only then can the soul experience material consciousness. Before pure consciousness evolves to material consciousness, it will pass through a hazy stage of consciousness or chidƒÅbhƒÅs. So, in the background of every material thing, there is a spiritual conception. This cannot but be true.`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Dr. Singh:</span> What is chidƒÅbhƒÅs?`},{class:`b43`,text:` <span class="e2">≈örƒ´la ≈örƒ´dhar MahƒÅrƒÅj:</span> Something like mind. Suppose consciousness comes to feel matter. When consciousness is coming to the material world to know the material world, it has to first pass through material consciousness, and then it can feel what is matter. According to Darwin‚Äôs theory, matter gradually produces consciousness, but before producing consciousness it must produce some hazy consciousness; then mind and then the soul. But in reality, it is just the opposite. So, subjective evolution parallels objective or material evolution. But in the evolution of consciousness, the supersubject is first, then the individual soul or jƒ´va-subject is next. Then, from the subjective consciousness of the jƒ´vas, matter is produced. But consciousness must penetrate hazy consciousness to perceive matter.`},{class:`b44`,text:` I say that the process of evolution moves from the top downward. The Absolute Reality‚Äîif we at all assert that there is anything which is the absolute reality‚Äîmust possess two qualifications. What is that? First, in the words of Hegel, He must be by Himself: He is His own cause. Second‚Äîand more important to us‚ÄîHe is for Himself: He exists to fulfil His own purpose. He is not subservient to any other entity for then His position would be secondary. Reality the Absolute is full in Himself. All other things are coming from Him. The perfect substance already exists. What appears to us as imperfect comes down according to our own defective senses.`},{class:`b51`,text:` The imperfect must be dependent upon the perfect, the ultimate reality. And the imperfect may be so arranged by Him in order to prove His perfection. To prove the perfection of the Absolute, there is conditioned and unconditioned, finite and infinite reality. The defective world, therefore, has an indirect relation to the truth. However, consciousness cannot jump at once into the conception of matter; it must pass through a process to come to material consciousness. From the marginal position, from the verge of the higher eternal potency, evolution and dissolution of this material world begins. This takes place only on the outskirts of svar≈´p-≈õakti, which is the system responsible for the evolution of the spiritual plane and is an eternally evolving dynamic whole. It is not that nondifferentiation is the origin of differentiation. An eternally differentiated substance exists. That plane is filled with lƒ´lƒÅ, dynamic Pastimes. If a static thing can be conceived of as eternal, then why can‚Äôt a dynamic thing be conceived of as eternal? That plane of svar≈´p-≈õakti is fully evolved within. It is eternal. Evolution and dissolution concern only the degradation of the subtle spirit to the gross material platform and his evolution towards perfection. Here, there is evolution and dissolution, but these things do not exist in the eternal abode of svar≈´p-≈õakti.`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Dr. Singh:</span> Objective evolution is what modern science calls Darwinian evolution, but how does subjective evolution unfold in K·πõ·π£·πáa conscious science?`},{class:`b43`,text:` <span class="e2">≈örƒ´la ≈örƒ´dhar MahƒÅrƒÅj:</span> You have to take the example of hypnotism. Through a form of mystic ‚Äòhypnotism‚Äô, the supersubject controls the subject to see a particular thing, and he is bound to see that. One may think that as we see a stone, the stone compels us to see it as stone, but it is just the opposite: we are compelled to see it as stone being under the influence of the supersubject who displays everything as He likes. When He commands, ‚ÄúSee stone‚Äù, then we shall see stone. Full control over whatever we see rests in His hands. No power to control what we see rests in the objective world. The objective world is fully controlled by the subjective. This is confirmed in <span class="e3">Bhagavad-gƒ´tƒÅ</span>, where K·πõ·π£·πáa says, ‚Äú<span class="e3">Pa≈õya Me yogam ai≈õvaram</span>: if I say, ‚ÄòBehold my mystic power‚Äô, you are bound to see it. You have no other choice.‚Äù`},{class:`b44`,text:` K·πõ·π£·πáa says <span class="e3">matta·∏• sm·πõtir j√±ƒÅnam apohana√± cha</span>: He is the prime cause of remembrance, forgetfulness, and intelligence. He is the controller. For His own pleasure, His lƒ´lƒÅ, He can do anything. This is true not only in the material world, but also in His own domain. What is meant by this statement of the <span class="e3">Gƒ´tƒÅ</span> concerns this brahmƒÅ·πá·∏ça, this material world. The gist of this statement is that from the lower planetary systems up to the highest‚Äîthis entire area of evolution and dissolution‚Äîeverything is manipulated by Him. No credit can be attached to any external thing. All credit should go to the Centre who controls everything.`},{class:`b44`,text:` And reality is subjective. It is based on consciousness. Colour is perceived through the eye. It is not that the colour is there and the eye can catch it. But the seer sees through the eye and perceives colour. So colour is a perception. Its position as actual substance should be traced to the subtle plane of existence. This is the nature of reality: the gross is coming from the subtle. In sƒÅ·πÖkhya philosophy, of course, that is described as a bifurcated thing. According to sƒÅ·πÖkhya philosophy, there are three branches of reality: the sense, the senses, and the sense objects. Sound is created by the ear, colour is produced by the eye, and so on.`},{class:`b44`,text:` The objects of the senses are in the mode of ignorance, tama-gu·πáa, the sensual instruments are in the mode of passion, raja-gu·πáa, and the power of sensation is in the mode of goodness, sattva-gu·πáa. From these proceed light, the eye, and colour; sky, the ear, and sound. In this way, mundane reality branches in three ways: tama, raja, and sattva. So the gross world is coming from the subtle through the channel of consciousness. The feeler, the instrument of perception, is creating the object of his perception.`},{class:`b51`,text:` Try to understand this principle of hypnotism. The whole thing is hypnotism‚Äîthis whole creation‚Äîand it is completely in the hand of the Supreme Subject. All material laws have no meaning: the laws and the sublaws are all pertaining to the subjective world.`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Dr. Murphey:</span> But how can one perceive this sort of hypnotism?`},{class:`b43`,text:` <span class="e2">≈örƒ´la ≈örƒ´dhar MahƒÅrƒÅj:</span> How can we know beforehand that in a laboratory, combining hydrogen and oxygen‚Äîtwo gases‚Äîwill produce water? Only when one comes to a particular stage of scientific knowledge can he know that a more subtle thing like gas can produce a tangible material thing like water. In that way, when you have an idea of the higher substance, then you can understand how from the subtle, the gross has originated.`},{class:`b44`,text:` The relative world is a perverted reflection of the Absolute Reality. Highly qualified things must be given the position of causal importance. It is not that a lower thing can produce a higher thing, but it is easy for a higher thing to produce something lower. This is not difficult to understand.`},{class:`b51`,text:` The modern scientific position is saying basically that stone can produce soul; but why not consider that soul can produce stone? We have to enquire about that process‚Äîhow the soul can produce stone. But we have done away with that and instead we say that stone is gradually producing soul. We are very fond of investigating in that line. Why? The subtle should be given more importance than the gross. Why should we think that man has created God, and not that God has created man?`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Dr. Singh:</span> Then God is the magician and we are His subjects?`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">≈örƒ´la ≈örƒ´dhar MahƒÅrƒÅj:</span> Not only is He a magician, but the Super-magician. He is not merely the kind of magician that is within our experience.`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Dr. Murphey:</span> What is the role of yogamƒÅyƒÅ, the Lord‚Äôs internal potency?`},{class:`b43`,text:` <span class="e2">≈örƒ´la ≈örƒ´dhar MahƒÅrƒÅj:</span> She is found in the eternal company of K·πõ·π£·πáa. In our conception of divinity, puru·π£a/prak·πõti, the masculine/feminine, are existing together. Potent and potency, substance and potency, are inconceivably interconnected. Otherwise, if we conceive of the Supreme Soul as existing independent of any potency, that will be the Brahma conception of ≈öa·πÖkar ƒÄchƒÅrya: ultimate consciousness as non-differentiated oneness. So, the Absolute Truth includes both potent and potency‚Äîpuru·π£a/prak·πõti‚Äîconsciousness with energy.`},{class:`b44`,text:` Actually, there are three main elements to be traced within divinity: j√±ƒÅn, bala, and kriyƒÅ. The eternal aspect of the absolute whole is divided in three ways: energy, consciousness, and ecstasy. Thinking, willing, and feeling. Sat, chit, ƒÅnanda. Sat, the potency for maintaining existence, is the potency of Baladev (bala). Chit, the aspect of consciousness, is VƒÅsudev (j√±ƒÅn). And ƒÅnanda, ecstatic feeling, is RƒÅdhikƒÅ (kriyƒÅ). J√±ƒÅn, bala, kriyƒÅ (knowledge, strength, feeling); sat, chit, ƒÅnanda (eternity, cognition, bliss); sandhinƒ´, samvit, hlƒÅdinƒ´ (existence, realisation, ecstasy): Baladev, K·πõ·π£·πáa, RƒÅdhƒÅrƒÅ·πáƒ´. These are the three phases of Advaya-j√±ƒÅn, or the one whole. The one whole can be thought of in its primary, evolved stage in three ways: main consciousness, main energy, and main satisfaction. In three phases, we are to conceive of that ultimate reality. It is there: <span class="e3">j√±ƒÅna-bala-kriyƒÅ cha</span>. Thinking, feeling, willing. Sat, chit, ƒÅnanda. Satyam, ≈õivam, sundaram (eternity, auspiciousness, beauty). And these three principles are expressed through evolution and dissolution in the eternal and non-eternal.`},{class:`b44`,text:` These aspects of theism have been dealt with in a very scientific way in the <span class="e3">≈örƒ´ K·πõ·π£·πáa-sa·πÅhitƒÅ</span> of Bhakti Vinod ·π¨hƒÅkur. Once, I considered from this point of view the question of the planets in Vedic cosmology. We see that by the movement of the different planets a solar eclipse is caused by the moon‚Äôs shadow falling upon the Earth. And yet in the scriptures it has been described that, during an eclipse, the planet RƒÅhu is devouring the sun or the moon. When ≈örƒ´la Bhakti SiddhƒÅnta Saraswatƒ´ ·π¨hƒÅkur was in Purƒ´ during his last days and an eclipse came, one devotee who was supposed to know siddhƒÅnta, the conclusions of scripture, was sitting next to PrabhupƒÅd. He suddenly ridiculed the idea given in the <span class="e3">BhƒÅgavatam</span> that during a solar or lunar eclipse RƒÅhu devours the sun or moon.`},{class:`b44`,text:` I could not tolerate that such a remark should be passed in regard to the <span class="e3">BhƒÅgavatam</span> and argued that what <span class="e3">≈örƒ´mad BhƒÅgavatam</span> has stated is not to be taken lightly. I offered what seemed like some far-fetched support. I said that in his <span class="e3">Jaiva-dharma</span>, Bhakti Vinod ·π¨hƒÅkur has created so many characters, but I think that they are not imaginary. What he has written might have occurred during some other millennium (kalpa), or day of BrahmƒÅ, and that has now come to the surface. In this way I went on to support the cosmological position of the <span class="e3">BhƒÅgavatam</span> by arguing that what is necessary to prove reality must also have some real position. It cannot but be. In this way my argument went, and PrabhupƒÅd supported me.`},{class:`b44`,text:` In understanding the position of the planet RƒÅhu, what ≈öukadev and VyƒÅsadev have said is geographically impossible, but their statements are there in <span class="e3">≈örƒ´mad BhƒÅgavatam</span>, and the literal meaning of the scriptures is not to be taken lightly. Considering the importance of the literal meaning of scripture, BhaktivedƒÅnta SwƒÅmƒ´ MahƒÅrƒÅj presented <span class="e3">Bhagavad-gƒ´tƒÅ</span> <span class="e3">As It Is</span>. I thought, ‚ÄúHow am I to prove what the <span class="e3">BhƒÅgavatam</span> says? I don‚Äôt know. But what is said in <span class="e3">≈örƒ´mad BhƒÅgavatam</span> must be true. I have faith in that.‚Äù`},{class:`b44`,text:` There are so many statements on the cosmology of the universe in the scriptures. The Aryans, the spiritually developed men of former times, used to see everything as consciousness. They saw that the shadow is also conscious. The shadow, ƒÅbhƒÅs, is also considered to be a stage of consciousness. Only through that shadowy stage of consciousness can we come to the material conception of a thing. Before we reach the conception of a shadow, we must pass through some mental stage, and personification may be attached to that mental stage. The personification of the shadow may be referred to as ‚ÄòRƒÅhu‚Äô.`},{class:`b44`,text:` The soul approaches matter, the material world, but before that, he must pass through a shadowy stage of consciousness called chidƒÅbhƒÅs. Consciousness passes through the shadow level of consciousness into matter, non-consciousness. And that shadow stage of consciousness has its personality. It is also conscious, and may be known as ‚ÄòRƒÅhu‚Äô.`},{class:`b44`,text:` Every material conception presupposes a spiritual conception of that particular thing. The shadow through which consciousness must pass in order to perceive things as material has personality, and in the <span class="e3">BhƒÅgavatam</span>, the ·πõ·π£is, the seers of the truth, are addressing it as RƒÅhu. Because they are highly developed, they find the personal aspect of existence everywhere. What we perceive to be dead matter, they perceive to be conscious. Therefore, they always take the personal perspective.`},{class:`b44`,text:` The soul, when going to experience any material conception, will have to pass through a medium which influences his consciousness to see things as material. What is concrete matter is unknown. It is a mere effect of consciousness. As everything material must have some conscious origin, or origin in personal consciousness, there must be a personal conception of the sun, the moon, the earth, and all the planets. Before we reach the conception of a shadow or any other object, the soul has to pass through a conscious stage. That stage has some spiritual existence as a person. Therefore, the <span class="e3">BhƒÅgavatam</span> refers to the sun, the moon, and the planet RƒÅhu, as persons. Everything‚Äîthe earth, the moon , the stars, the planets‚Äîhas a personal conception. In the background of what we can perceive with our dull senses, everything that is said to be matter, there must be a personal conception. Without the influence of a personal conception, consciousness cannot reach the stage of gross matter.`},{class:`b51`,text:` Therefore, in the ancient scriptures we find that the great sages and ·πõ·π£is are always addressing everything within this world as a person. Although to us it is dead matter, they have considered them as persons. Why? The matter is rather the shadow of the personal entity. The personal, conscious entity is more real, and the matter we perceive through dimmed consciousness is less real.`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Dr. Murphey:</span> So, that shadow is RƒÅhu?`},{class:`b43`,text:` <span class="e2">≈örƒ´la ≈örƒ´dhar MahƒÅrƒÅj:</span> When we conceive of the personal representation of that shadow, it will be known as RƒÅhu. Everything is conscious. The shadow, its effect‚Äîeverything.`},{class:`b44`,text:` When the moon is between the sun and the earth, the shadow of the moon is coming here, and what is coming is also conscious. Everything is conscious first‚Äîthen there is matter. From the personal conception things evolve to gross consciousness. It is all personal. So, the ·πõ·π£is with such a vision of reality used to address everything as a person: the trees, the mountains, the sun, the moon, the ocean. When pure consciousness is coming to experience pure matter, then there must first be some mixed stage, and that is a person suffering in karma. Person means they are not a fully developed spiritual person at present, but in a mixed condition. So, what the ·πõ·π£is are saying‚Äîthat everything is a person‚Äîis real; it is not a concoction.`},{class:`b51`,text:` Everything is conscious. As the present scientists say everything is matter, we have real cause to think that everything is conscious. Whatever you see does not matter; we can directly feel what is in our nature. That is conscious. Our consciousness may be in a developed or degraded position, but consciousness is nearer to us. We feel our mental energy only.`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Dr. Murphey:</span> This is a bit difficult for us to fully grasp. When we see colour, what are we actually seeing?`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">≈örƒ´la ≈örƒ´dhar MahƒÅrƒÅj:</span> That is a mental stage.`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Dr. Singh:</span> What is the reality of that object?`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">≈örƒ´la ≈örƒ´dhar MahƒÅrƒÅj:</span> Reality‚Äîthat is in the soul. Only the soul is real; the seer is reality. The subject is real. And whatever the subject feels also emanates from the subject.`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Dr. Singh:</span> But are the objects the subject perceives also persons? When we are seeing the colour red, now is red also a personality?`},{class:`b43`,text:` <span class="e2">≈örƒ´la ≈örƒ´dhar MahƒÅrƒÅj:</span> Everything has its representation in the original, personal, conscious, spiritual reality. Otherwise, there is no possibility of its being reflected into this plane as matter. First, there is consciousness, and then when it is in a more gross condition, it appears to be matter. In the study of ontology, it is taught that when studying a particular thing, although we can know that it has certain attributes to the eye and that it appears to the ear in a particular way, these are all appearances. Independent of appearances, the ontological aspect of a thing‚Äîwhat it is, the reality of a thing‚Äîis unknown and unknowable. My contention is that when consciousness is going to feel non-conscious matter, it will have to pass through a conscious area to meet the material object. So, the full perception of that material thing cannot but be conscious, and consciousness always indicates person. First, there is conception and then the material idea.`},{class:`b51`,text:` The conscious world is very near and the material world is very far off. Therefore, the great ·πõ·π£is, whose thinking is highly developed, address whatever they find within the environment as if they are all persons. In the Vedas, the ancient scriptural literature of India, we find that the saints and sages are always in the midst of so many persons. In the background everything is a person.`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Dr. Murphey:</span> And person means thinking, feeling, willing.`},{class:`b43`,text:` <span class="e2">≈örƒ´la ≈örƒ´dhar MahƒÅrƒÅj:</span> Thinking, feeling, willing‚Äîa living entity has three phases. And it is also the same with God and His potency. There is a subject existing first, and then his experiences. And experiences of the subtlemost character come first and are given the most importance. And when the subject is coming to the more distant area to conceive of matter, that will be the farthest point from him. He will address everything by which he is surrounded with personal conceptions.`},{class:`b44`,text:` A personal conception cannot but assert that matter is far off. The direct connection of consciousness is with the shadow, the reflection of the material into the conscious world. The soul can understand that only. If matter can exist independently, then also matter has a shadow in the conscious world, and the soul is concerned with that shadow.`},{class:`b44`,text:` In other words, there is the person and then the body. Just as the body is the after-effect of the conscious living agent, matter is the after-effect of spirit. Irrespective of all material consciousness, that which is in direct contact with soul is all personal. ChidƒÅbhƒÅs is something like the mental substance we have within.`},{class:`b51`,text:` There are two kinds of persons, k·π£ara and ak·π£ara: the pure liberated soul and the soul who is struggling in matter. When liberated and non-liberated persons are mixed within the world of material transactions, whether as moving or non-moving entities, or whatever their position might be, still they should be considered persons. Since everything is a unit of consciousness, everything has personal existence.`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Dr. Murphey:</span> So, externally we see the Ganges as water, but in reality she is a person.`},{class:`b43`,text:` <span class="e2">≈örƒ´la ≈örƒ´dhar MahƒÅrƒÅj:</span> Everything is a person. Before we go to the material conception, we must pass through the personal conception or aspect of that thing. In V·πõndƒÅvan, everything is conscious, but some things are posing in a passive way. But they are all conscious: the YamunƒÅ river, the cows, the trees, the fruit‚Äîeverything is conscious, spiritual, but they pose in different ways. Being able to detect the conscious characteristic in everything, the Aryans saw all of nature as conscious and personal and addressed everything as conscious.`},{class:`b51`,text:` Consciousness and personality are the universal basis of reality. Whatever we may experience is conscious. The reflection of a material object is within me, and the plane within me is conscious. The subject is consciousness, and whatever kind of thing the object may be, it casts its reflection into the plane of consciousness. The observer of any objective reality is involved only with consciousness from beginning to end and can have no conception of matter apart from consciousness.`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Dr. Murphey:</span> How can we differentiate consciousness from mind?`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">≈örƒ´la ≈örƒ´dhar MahƒÅrƒÅj:</span> In <span class="e3">Bhagavad-gƒ´tƒÅ</span>, the path of differentiation between consciousness and mind is suggested: <span class="e3">indriyƒÅ·πái parƒÅ·πáy ƒÅhur</span>. What is ƒÅtmƒÅ, the soul, the spiritual conception? We have come to the world conception by a particular process. By the process of elimination we can trace out what the mind is. It is said that the basis of the mind is acceptance and rejection: sa·πÖkalpa-vikalpa‚Äî‚ÄúI want this, I don‚Äôt want that.‚Äô‚Äô What is the mind? A thing that contains apathy and sympathy for the external world. That is the mind. We have to trace within us what that thing is. It is within us, and one has to enter into his own self and try to have some personal experience of what the mind is. Then by internal analysis one can try to come directly in touch with the faculty of judgment, reason, intelligence, by asking, ‚ÄúWhat is intelligence? Where is it within me?‚Äù We should try to find that out and come in touch with that directly. We should enquire, ‚ÄúWhat is the mind? It is already within me. But what is it? And what is reason within me? What is the source of the mind and intelligence? And crossing the stage of the decisive faculty, what is the soul?‚Äù We must try, as a yogi does, to come in direct touch with the elements within us. Mind and intelligence are within each of us. Why should we not be able to trace out exactly what they are, to see internally what they are?`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Dr. Murphey:</span> When our faith is growing in a particular direction, how can we know that our realisations are coming from our own internal self, from our inner consciousness, and not from the influence of the environment, the circumstances that surround us?`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">≈örƒ´la ≈örƒ´dhar MahƒÅrƒÅj:</span> The self is in a dormant state, but by some external help it may be reawakened, just as when one is sleeping, by external interference a man can be roused. It is something like that. Someone is dormant, but when, by external help, he awakes from his slumber, he again becomes aware of himself. Once he is awakened and his self-awareness has returned, he immediately knows, ‚ÄúI was such and such; I am such and such.‚Äù By the help of our friends, we may recover our health. In the same way, if we continue to apply the process of bhakti, we shall become more and more conscious of our self and of reality. We are our own guarantee.`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Dr. Murphey:</span> I wanted to clarify one point. In Kapila‚Äôs system of analysis, sƒÅ·πÖkhya, he says that pradhƒÅn is ‚Äúthat unmanifested matter which is eternal.‚Äù You say that everything is consciousness. Is pradhƒÅn also composed of consciousness?`},{class:`b43`,text:` <span class="e2">≈örƒ´la ≈örƒ´dhar MahƒÅrƒÅj:</span> Yes. What is material is only the misconception which is the cause of all this material existence. But it also has personality‚ÄîDevƒ´, the goddess.`},{class:`b51`,text:` The world begins within misconception. When you have the proper conception, then you can read K·πõ·π£·πáa-lƒ´lƒÅ everywhere. Everything will excite you about V·πõndƒÅvan. You won‚Äôt see the outward thing if you are relieved from misconception. A madman has a maladjusted brain. He may be in the midst of friends, but he is lost in his madness, his paranoia. When he goes back to his normal position, he finds the same thing‚Äîall friends. In the same way, everything is all right‚Äîonly the disease, our misconception needs to be removed.`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Dr. Murphey:</span> The disease is our lack of K·πõ·π£·πáa consciousness.`},{class:`b43`,text:` <span class="e2">≈örƒ´la ≈örƒ´dhar MahƒÅrƒÅj:</span> Lack of consciousness means misconception, disease. This is described in <span class="e3">≈örƒ´mad BhƒÅgavatam</span>: <span class="e3">bhaya·πÅ dvitƒ´yƒÅbhinive≈õata·∏• syƒÅd</span>‚Äîthe disease is separate interest. The deviation from our normal spiritual condition, the development of misconception, is based on the charm‚Äîthe prospect‚Äîof separate interest. That is the root cause of all misunderstanding. The conception of local, provincial interest has caused the difference between a proper conception of reality and misconception. We have gone away from the central conception. From universal consciousness we have come to this provincial plane. And according to the gradation of consciousness in its development from provincial to universal, we may find ourselves in so many different planets or planes of existence: Bh≈´, Bhuva, Sva, Jana, Maha, Tapa, Satya; all these different stages of development are involved in this process of provincialism and universalism. But loss of consciousness of the Centre is the root of this entire material existence.`},{class:`b44`,text:` One who is conscious of the organic whole, on the other hand, is in the most healthy position. That is proper adjustment, and maladjustment is the cause of our present diseased condition. Adjustment is life; it is liberated life, and to be the prey of maladjustment is to approach pain and misery. Everything within the environment is all right. The only difficulty is found in the conception of selfish special interest. Our aversion to the universal interest is the cause of our detachment from the conception of the whole and from happiness and health. We have been deprived of the happiness of our healthy position, and the cause is selfish interest.`},{class:`b44`,text:` The Absolute Autocrat is absolute good. So, there is no room for complaint against Him. K·πõ·π£·πáa says, <span class="e3">suh·πõda·πÅ sarva-bh≈´tƒÅnƒÅm</span>. He is the owner of everything; in comparison, we are nothing. But still, He is our friend. We should not forget that. We are represented in Him. Our detachment from Him is the cause of all the miseries that we are suffering. We and others like us have lost faith in Him, but He is our friend. We are jealous of Him and are thinking, ‚ÄúI am not the master? Someone else is the master‚Äîthis is intolerable. No taxation without representation!‚Äù But our interests are well-represented in K·πõ·π£·πáa. He cares about us even more than we can conceive. Why do we forget that?`},{class:`b44`,text:` If we only reinstate ourselves in that faith, we will be all right. It is our fault that we are suffering; otherwise, there is no difference in vision from the universal standpoint. <span class="e3">ƒ™≈õƒÅd apetasya</span>: we have turned away from our master. But we should remember that He is our master, He is our well-wisher, He is our guardian. Deviation from that consciousness is misery of an infinite magnitude. Its cause is very subtle and very minute; it is our mentality of separate interest. And as a result, we have been captured by the enemy camp.`},{class:`b44`,text:` Pata√±jali has said we are moving towards evil in an intelligent, organised way. That is not only mad but wicked; it is worse than mad, according to Pata√±jali. What will be the relief of a soul in such a deplorable condition? A madman is in possession of everything‚Äîhe is only out of his mind. His consciousness has to be adjusted properly. Then he will find, ‚ÄúOh, everything is all right‚Äîlet me go back home.‚Äô‚Äô At present his consciousness is cast aside. He is not at home; his consciousness must be pushed homeward.`},{class:`b44`,text:` That is the problem. Our Guru MahƒÅrƒÅj used to say, ‚ÄúI don‚Äôt admit any famine in this world‚Äîonly that of a lack of K·πõ·π£·πáa consciousness: <span class="e3">jagate eka-mƒÅtra Hari-kathƒÅ-durbhik·π£a chƒÅ·∏çƒÅ ƒÅra kona durbhik·π£a nƒÅi</span>.‚Äù Whenever he became excited, he used to use this expression. He would say, ‚ÄúFrom door to door tell everyone, ‚ÄòK·πõ·π£·πáa is the Supreme; you are all servants of K·πõ·π£·πáa.‚Äô Remind everyone of this, from door to door. Then they will find, ‚ÄòOh, I have everything I need. I am K·πõ·π£·πáadƒÅs, a servant of K·πõ·π£·πáa. I must connect with K·πõ·π£·πáa.‚Äô That link must be supplied, and then everything will be all right. There is no dearth of anything else. There is no real misery, except that we have forgotten K·πõ·π£·πáa, our Lord. That is the only point we must push. This is the universal necessity. I don‚Äôt admit any necessity besides this.‚Äù`},{class:`b44`,text:` Within this world there is always a fire burning, but there is no necessity of extinguishing the fire because we have nothing to do with the world that will be burned into ashes by the fire. All our inner demands can be met only in connection with K·πõ·π£·πáa. All other things are unnecessary. They may be burned into ashes or devoured by flood. We have no real concern with any of those things. Rather, those material attachments are dragging us back towards the wrong thing. And as a result, we can‚Äôt allow our mind to be attracted to K·πõ·π£·πáa. The things of this world, or attachments, are all negative; these things are all our enemy. The whole universe may be burned to ashes, but we will not be affected in any way. The world may be devastated‚Äîthe earth, the sun, the moon, the stars‚Äîeverything may vanish, but still we remain. The soul is eternal. And if we can have a connection with K·πõ·π£·πáa, the things of this world are all unnecessary for us and for everyone else. Why should we come to live in the mortal world, erroneously identifying ourselves with flesh and blood? We only think that we are being born and dying. But it is a false notion.`},{class:`b51`,text:` Everything is conscious. And when we realise it fully, we shall be fixed in the svar≈´p-≈õakti domain in the spiritual world. There, the different living beings may pose as matter, as the YamunƒÅ, as water, as creepers, as trees, but they are all conscious units, simply posing in different ways.`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Dr. Murphey:</span> It is said that when K·πõ·π£·πáa goes to take bath in the YamunƒÅ, all the waves rush in to embrace K·πõ·π£·πáa.`},{class:`b43`,text:` <span class="e2">≈örƒ´la ≈örƒ´dhar MahƒÅrƒÅj:</span> Sometimes the stones melt feeling the imprint of K·πõ·π£·πáa‚Äôs lotus feet. Everything is conscious. So, it is also in the case of RƒÅhu and Ketu and other planets. Everywhere in the scriptures, the spiritually developed sages are found talking with nature as if they are talking with a person. And it is real. But our consciousness is deviated in ignorance.`},{class:`b52`,text:` So, as scientists, you must crush the philosophy of fossilism. BhaktivedƒÅnta SwƒÅmƒ´ MahƒÅrƒÅj has ordered you to take a strong position in the scientific community in the West and crush fossilism. Why should we accept fossilism? First there is consciousness. This is Berkeley‚Äôs theory. Not that mind is in the world, but world is in the mind. Everything is based on consciousness; no conception‚Äînothing remains‚Äîwithout consciousness. So ultimately, all undesirable things are only a mental concoction.`}]},{title:`The Creation`,paragraphs:[{class:`b46`,text:`\r`},{class:`b47`,text:` The Creation`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">≈örƒ´la ≈örƒ´dhar MahƒÅrƒÅj:</span> The <span class="e3">Manu-sa·πÅhitƒÅ</span> (1.5‚Äì6) begins describing the creation from this point:`},{class:`b60`,text:` ƒÅsƒ´d ida·πÅ tamo-bh≈´tam apraj√±ƒÅtam alak·π£a·πáam<br />apratarkyam avij√±eya·πÅ prasuptam iva sarvata·∏•<br />tata·∏• svayambh≈´r bhagavƒÅn avyakto vya√±jayann idam<br />mahƒÅbhutƒÅdi-v·πõttaujƒÅ·∏• prƒÅdur ƒÅsƒ´t tamo-nuda·∏•`},{class:`b43`,text:` Just before the creative movement began, the marginal potency of the Lord was in a state of equilibrium. <span class="e3">Ta·π≠asthƒÅ</span> means equilibrium: <span class="e3">ƒÅsƒ´d ida·πÅ tamo-bh≈´tam</span>. Everything was in darkness, fully enveloped by ignorance. <span class="e3">Alak·π£anam</span> means there was no possibility of any estimation; no symptoms of reality existed by which any conjecture or inference about the nature of reality would have been possible. And it was <span class="e3">apraj√±ƒÅtam</span>: science has no capacity for investigating the nature of that stage of existence. We can only say from here that it was completely immersed in deep sleep. The analogy of deep sleep may give us some conception of that period: <span class="e3">prasuptam iva sarvata·∏•</span>. Material existence was as if in a sound sleep.`},{class:`b44`,text:` At that time, movement began from within the spiritual plane and light came. Light was seen by the seers. That light was pre-existent, but at that time the seers received the vision to see light. They began to see. The first conception of this material world after light was water. The light revealed a substance like water.`},{class:`b44`,text:` That primal light is compared with personality. Light means consciousness, and consciousness means personality. That light, or personality, first gave birth to the onlookers to the feelers of material existence, and then to an objective substance like water. That water is known as VirajƒÅ, or causal substance. What is known in Vai·π£·πáava vocabulary as Brahmaloka‚Äîthe world of consciousness‚Äîis represented by light, and VirajƒÅ, or causal substance, is represented by water. The conscious world is represented by light, and the first objective reality is represented as water. Then, the seeds of consciousness are sown in the causal water which is the shadow of that light. Although the actual element of water was created long after this, the first conception of matter is compared to water because water is an accommodating, moving solution. The Sanskrit word for water, <span class="e3">apa</span>, means ‚Äúof lower conception‚Äù. In this way, the lower creation began.`},{class:`b44`,text:` Then, in connection with the seeds of consciousness and the primal water, the next production was known as mahat-tattva: the energy of consciousness represented by light mixed with matter as a mass. When the mass of matter is infused with the energy of light-consciousness, that is known as mahat-tattva.`},{class:`b44`,text:` After further development, that entity was divided into many units of aha·πÖkƒÅr, the element of ego. <span class="e3">Mahato aha·πÖkƒÅra·∏•</span>. First there is aha·πÖkƒÅr, mass ego as a whole. The element of conglomerate ego is called mahat-tattva. As objective substance evolves by the influence of consciousness, it expresses itself in five main ingredients: that which can be seen, smelled, heard, tasted, and touched. These five elements are the primitive principles of material existence.`},{class:`b44`,text:` And that fivefold principle evolved in three phases: sattva, raja, tamah: goodness, passion, and ignorance. Expressing itself as ether, sound, hearing, and the ear; air, mass, touch, and the skin; fire, colour, vision, and the eye; water, tastes, the sense of taste, and the tongue; and earth, aroma, the sense of smell, and the nose. There are twenty-four elements. The self, three subtle elements‚Äîprak·πõti, mahat-tattva, and aha·πÖkƒÅr, five gross elements, five senses, five sense objects, five sense-gathering instruments‚Äîin this way, the development of the material world has been described to have come down through a process of subtle to gross, from consciousness to matter. Again when this material existence is withdrawn by superior will, the gross dissolves into the subtle. Beginning with the most gross, gradually the whole of material existence becomes more and more subtle until it finally enters into the subtle expression of material existence known as prak·πõti‚Äîthe subtle causal watery substance.`},{class:`b51`,text:` With the dissolution of material energy, the ƒÅtmƒÅ or individual soul is absorbed in brahma, the nondifferentiated mass of consciousness. The position of the different kinds of spiritual energy has been described by K·πõ·π£·πáa in <span class="e3">Bhagavad-gƒ´tƒÅ</span> (15.16‚Äì17) as follows:`},{class:`b60`,text:` dvƒÅv imau puru·π£au loke k·π£ara≈õ chƒÅk·π£ara eva cha<br />k·π£ara·∏• sarvƒÅ·πái bh≈´tƒÅni k≈´·π≠a-stho ‚Äôk·π£ara uchyate<br />uttama·∏• puru·π£as tv anya·∏• paramƒÅtmety udƒÅh·πõta·∏•<br />yo loka-trayam ƒÅvi≈õya bibharty avyaya ƒ´≈õvara·∏•`},{class:`b43`,text:` ‚ÄúThere are two kinds of beings: the perfect and unchanging, or infallible, and the fallible souls. The fallible souls reside in the material world, and the infallible souls reside in the spiritual world.‚Äù K·πõ·π£·πáa says, ‚ÄúI exist, transcending both fallible and infallible aspects of spiritual substance (k·π£ara and ak·π£ara), so I am Puru·π£ottam, VƒÅsudev, Parambrahma, the Supreme Absolute Truth. Within Me, the whole of My jurisdiction is also to be considered.‚Äù`},{class:`b44`,text:` Vaiku·πá·π≠ha, Goloka‚Äîthe whole creation‚Äîis represented by the name of Puru·π£ottam or VƒÅsudev. Then, when one enters into that domain of VƒÅsudev, he can see so many demarcations, stages of reality, Pastimes, and transcendental dealings and activities. There he will find the perfected living beings busy in their dedicated life in the eternal world.`},{class:`b44`,text:` The general conception of the spiritual world is Vaiku·πá·π≠ha wherein we find calculative dedication. Above that is the plane of spontaneous dedication. That realm is called Goloka, and there are many different kinds of Pastimes there. In Goloka, all the various relationships with Godhead are represented in full: ≈õƒÅnta, passive, dƒÅsya, servitude, sakhya, friendship, vƒÅtsalya, parenthood, and madhura, conjugal. And the conjugal mellow can be subdivided into svakƒ´ya, wedded love, and parakƒ´ya, a paramour relationship. This is, of course, a very elevated subject matter. Still, we have to have some view of these things since our fate is ultimately connected with such high things given to us by ≈örƒ´ Chaitanya MahƒÅprabhu and great ƒÄchƒÅryas like Bhakti Vinod ·π¨hƒÅkur and discussed in scriptures like <span class="e3">≈örƒ´mad BhƒÅgavatam</span> and <span class="e3">Chaitanya-charitƒÅm·πõta</span>.`},{class:`b51`,text:` What is found in their teachings about Goloka is our prospect, our aspiration. According to our devotional taste, we will develop, and our taste can also be improved by hearing from a higher source. The spirit of our selection may be improved when we are shown different ideas, different models of transcendental reality. And according to what attracts us most based upon our inner choice, we shall have to act.`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Question: </span>What part do the individual souls play in the process of creation?`},{class:`b43`,text:` <span class="e2">≈örƒ´la ≈örƒ´dhar MahƒÅrƒÅj:</span> I have described that. At first, a general, conglomerate false ego (aha·πÖkƒÅr) is created. This is called ≈öambhu in <span class="e3">Brahma-sa·πÅhitƒÅ</span>, wherein it explains how the soul as a ray of consciousness mingles with material energy. Consciousness and prak·πõti, the most primitive conceptions of energy, are categorically different. The conglomerate consciousness comes in contact with mass energy, and as they mingle together, a general ego evolves. That general ego gradually dissolves into innumerable egos, and the conglomerate consciousness distributes itself as individual units of consciousness absorbed in material energy. In this way, gradually, the individual conditioned souls come down and are entangled within the material world.`},{class:`b44`,text:` In a primitive state when the individual souls are massed together as a common whole, the conglomerate false ego, or aha·πÖkƒÅra, is known as mahat-tattva. As it evolves, it differentiates into innumerable individual units. Just as an atom can be broken down into subatomic particles, electrons, protons, neutrons, and so on, the conglomerate ego gradually breaks into its component individual egos, jƒ´va-souls. Their position is ta·π≠astha, marginal, and undetectable. From that subtle, undetectable plane of marginal energy, consciousness first develops into the detectable plane as a whole, and then innumerable individual spiritual units are manifest from that mass lump of ego, or mahat-tattva. Gradually, the other elements of creation develop within this negative plane of exploitation.`},{class:`b44`,text:` This world is sometimes pushing forth, and sometimes withdrawing. In the same way that the heart expands and contracts again and again, the whole universe expands and contracts. Regrouping within the one, and again manifest as the many‚Äîthe one and the many‚Äîthe evolution and dissolution of the material universe takes place. As a heart expands and contracts, the whole universe is manifest and withdrawn.`},{class:`b44`,text:` The same characteristics that we find in the smallest unit can be traced in the bigger units. This is the suggestion by which we may know the whole, more or less. There are also some categorically new elements to be added to our knowledge. In this way, those who are within this universe can have some partial knowledge.`},{class:`b44`,text:` But those who are independent, outside the contracting and expanding world, who are impartial onlookers, can give the real history. That is the revealed truth, which is distributed in instalments according to the capacity of the people, of the time, place, and circumstance. The revealed truth is found in varying degrees in the Bible, the Koran, the Vedas, and the other scriptures of the world. Through this process, the truth is partially revealed in different places of the world in proportion to the thinking and capacity of each particular group of people. The revealed truth is reliable, but still it is modified to fit the persons to whom it is extended.`},{class:`b44`,text:` For that reason, we find differences in the different versions of the revealed truth. It is said in <span class="e3">≈örƒ´mad BhƒÅgavatam</span> that medicine may be hidden within candy to treat the ignorant. In the same way, the revealed truth may be hidden within the mundane concessions of ordinary religion to help the ignorant class of men: <span class="e3">parok·π£a-vƒÅdo Vedo ‚Äòya·πÅ</span>.`},{class:`b51`,text:` Still, Vedic revelation is conceived of by authorities as the most ancient as well as the most perfect of all versions of revealed truth. The revealed truth as presented by <span class="e3">≈örƒ´mad BhƒÅgavatam</span> and ≈örƒ´ Chaitanya MahƒÅprabhu must be considered full-fledged theism. There, it is mentioned what lies beyond this created world is the eternally dancing world. Here, we are trapped in the world of contraction and expansion, but in the spiritual realm, everything is an eternal, blissful dance. Still, even the reality there is of a lower and higher type according to the nature of rasa‚Äîtranscendental mellow, ƒÅnandam, ecstasy‚Äîwhich is the desired substance of every conscious unit.`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Question: </span>K·πõ·π£·πáa‚Äôs Pastimes are eternal. When K·πõ·π£·πáa finishes one Pastime in this universe, His Pastimes begin in another. At the time of the final annihilation, when all the universes are withdrawn, how do K·πõ·π£·πáa‚Äôs Pastimes continue?`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">≈örƒ´la ≈örƒ´dhar MahƒÅrƒÅj:</span> When the universe is destroyed in the total annihilation of all the stars and planets, the mahƒÅpralaya, this side almost equates to zero. It reaches equilibrium. But the spiritual world is always in full swing. No harm can be done to K·πõ·π£·πáa‚Äôs Pastimes because they have an eternal aspect.`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Question: </span>But what happens to K·πõ·π£·πáa‚Äôs lƒ´lƒÅ here on earth?`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">≈örƒ´la ≈örƒ´dhar MahƒÅrƒÅj:</span> Suppose fruit falls from a tree. The fruit is gradually finished, but the tree remains. It is something like that. This material world may equate to zero, but K·πõ·π£·πáa‚Äôs Pastimes continue eternally.`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Question: </span>What is the difference between Goloka, K·πõ·π£·πáa‚Äôs place of Pastimes in the transcendental world, and Gokula, K·πõ·π£·πáa‚Äôs pleasure abode in this earthly plane?`},{class:`b43`,text:` <span class="e2">≈örƒ´la ≈örƒ´dhar MahƒÅrƒÅj:</span> Gokula V·πõndƒÅvan eternally exists, but sometimes the seers are all absent. Gokula exists in the ideal world and is extended here. What we see, we see from our different positions of existence, but Gokula is there always. If you have no eye to see something, it cannot be seen. If you have no hand to touch it, it cannot be touched. It is the same with Gokula. It is in such a plane where the different external processes which exert control over material energy cannot touch the fine ideal of existence in Gokula.`},{class:`b51`,text:` If the earth vanishes, that does not mean that the whole solar system will vanish. The solar system may remain, but the men on the earth cannot see it any longer. Its influence on earth can no longer be felt. In a similar way, Gokula exists in another plane. It exists in the finest plane of reality. It is beyond the creation, beyond evolution and dissolution. Such subtle energy can be understood by analogy with ether. If earth is destroyed, ether may not be destroyed. Ether is within and outside earth, but with the dissolution of earth, ether may not dissolve, but continue to exist. The position of Gokula is something like that. This is confirmed by <span class="e3">≈örƒ´mad BhƒÅgavatam</span> (2.9.35):`},{class:`b60`,text:` yathƒÅ mahƒÅnti bh≈´tƒÅni bh≈´te·π£≈´chchƒÅvache·π£v anu<br />pravi·π£·π≠ƒÅny apravi·π£·π≠ƒÅni tathƒÅ te·π£u na te·π£v aham`},{class:`b43`,text:` ‚ÄúO BrahmƒÅ, please know that the universal elements enter into the cosmos and at the same time do not enter into the cosmos; similarly, I also exist within everything and at the same time I am outside everything.‚Äù`},{class:`b51`,text:` K·πõ·π£·πáa‚Äôs position is similar: He is there and not there. In <span class="e3">Bhagavad-gƒ´tƒÅ</span> (9.4-5), He tells Arjuna:`},{class:`b60`,text:` mayƒÅ tatam ida·πÅ sarva·πÅ jagad avyakta-m≈´rtinƒÅ<br />mat-sthƒÅni sarva-bh≈´tƒÅni na chƒÅha·πÅ te·π£v avasthita·∏•<br />na cha mat-sthƒÅni bh≈´tƒÅni pa≈õya me yogam ai≈õvaram<br />bh≈´ta-bh·πõn na cha bh≈´ta-stho mamƒÅtmƒÅ bh≈´ta-bhƒÅvana·∏•`},{class:`b43`,text:` ‚ÄúI am everywhere and nowhere. Everything is in Me, and yet nothing is in Me. In My unmanifested form, this entire universe is pervaded. Behold My mystic opulence, My simultaneous oneness and difference! Although I am the maintainer of all living entities and although I am everywhere, I am not implicated by any of this, for I am the very source of creation.‚Äù`},{class:`b52`,text:` We have to understand the relationship between cause and effect. The cause and its effect are of different types. Even the inner cause and the outer cause may have different positions. The body may be disturbed, but the mind may not be. The mind may be disturbed, but the soul may not be. By this, we are to understand the difference between cause and effect, subtle and gross, matter and spirit.`}]},{title:`Consciousness & Evolution`,paragraphs:[{class:`b46`,text:`\r`},{class:`b47`,text:` Consciousness & Evolution`},{class:`b43`,text:` Prak·πõti, the material nature, does not evolve consciousness like fossilism. But on the other hand, both are within consciousness. There is no necessity of movement for the soul here. The soul is inactive, indifferent, passive in this enjoying plane. That is another original conception. The soul does not take its place in the negative side; it is meant for the positive side. But accepting that the soul is in the background, prak·πõti or material energy‚Äîthe body‚Äîworks on its behalf. The relationship between body and soul is like the relationship between a minor and his false guardians. It is something like what happens when the proprietor of an estate is a minor and the managers take advantage of his youth to loot and enjoy the estate. The baddha-jƒ´va-soul is in the minor‚Äôs position. The soul cannot control these revolting managers, the five senses. He need only have the contact of a major soul. With the help and guidance of the major soul, he can subdue his managers and gain mastery over his own property. A fallen soul‚Äôs position is like a minor proprietor. He is helpless. He is doing nothing. The managers are doing everything using his own resources; they are doing everything in the name of the proprietor. The soul is inactive, non-cooperating. But the body, mind, intelligence, and false ego are working on behalf of the soul‚Äîthe real ego‚Äîas if he were on their side. But if his real interest inside is roused by a major soul who is connected with ParamƒÅtmƒÅ and with BhagavƒÅn, then the soul will find his own field there. He‚Äôll control the senses and mind and utilise them in the service of the Lord. He‚Äôll say, ‚ÄúEverything is for K·πõ·π£·πáa, not for me.‚Äù`},{class:`b44`,text:` So K·πõ·π£·πáa says, ‚Äú<span class="e3">Sarva-dharmƒÅn parityajya MƒÅm eka·πÅ ≈õara·πáa·πÅ vraja</span>: give up all your duties and come to Me. And your present duties good or bad, whatever you can conceive from your present position‚Äîgive up everything and come straight to Me. I‚Äôm everything to you.‚Äù This is K·πõ·π£·πáa consciousness. K·πõ·π£·πáa is telling us, ‚ÄúYou belong to Me; you are My property. Just as you can say that you are master of any property, so you are My property, My slave.‚Äù That is the truth, and by accepting that truth we will live in a higher plane. We will be the gainer; we will come into our normal position. At present, in an abnormal position, we are suffering from thinking, ‚ÄúI‚Äôm the master, the monarch of all I survey.‚Äù But that ego is our worst enemy if we are to progress in devotional service.`},{class:`b44`,text:` And service to K·πõ·π£·πáa is of different varieties. There is service in general and then there are services of a particular type: ≈õƒÅnta, dƒÅsya, sakhya, vƒÅtsalya, and madhura. And then there are also divisions according to whether devotion is calculative or spontaneous. In this way, there is a hierarchy in the development of the devotional condition. The highest development is ujjvala-rasa. Ujjvala-rasa means super-fine, the brightest, surpassing all, where we find K·πõ·π£·πáa in consorthood without any consideration of any law. Autocratic consorthood. And this particular nature and behaviour is described in a book written by R≈´pa GoswƒÅmƒ´ titled <span class="e3">Ujjvala-nƒ´lama·πái</span>. The first part of devotion is given in <span class="e3">Bhakti-rasƒÅm·πõta-sindhu</span>. In that book, from the very beginning of an ordinary civilised religious life, R≈´pa GoswƒÅmƒ´ takes us up to different devotional relationships ≈õƒÅnta, dƒÅsya, sakhya, vƒÅtsalya, and madhura-rasa. But the details of madhura-rasa, the highest relationship with K·πõ·π£·πáa, has been described by R≈´pa GoswƒÅmƒ´ in <span class="e3">Ujjvala-nƒ´lama·πái</span>. Nƒ´lama·πái, K·πõ·π£·πáa, in His highest lustre: ujjvala. Nƒ´lama·πái in consorthood. And what are K·πõ·π£·πáa‚Äôs characteristics? How does He play with His paraphernalia in the madhura-rasa? That has been described in detail in <span class="e3">Ujjvala-nƒ´lama·πái</span>.`},{class:`b44`,text:` Even the greatest literary scholars are dumbfounded to find how divine love has been analysed so finely and elaborately in this book of R≈´pa GoswƒÅmƒ´. Subtle points have been analysed, organised, and distributed in that book. And the great scholars become dumbfounded when they come to such statements. As <span class="e3">BhƒÅgavatam</span> says: <span class="e3">muhyanti yat s≈´raya·∏•</span>. In the introduction, <span class="e3">BhƒÅgavatam</span> gives this warning, this caution to the scholars: ‚ÄúYou will all be dumbfounded when you attempt to come to this plane. Scholarship will not allow you to flourish here.‚Äù The nature of that plane is so mysterious that even great scholars won‚Äôt be considered fit to enter there.`},{class:`b44`,text:` Only the surrendered souls can understand and feel these subtle points of devotion. Outsiders, who remain objective enquirers and researchers, can‚Äôt have any entrance here. It is the superior subjective realm, the supersubjective realm. That plane is above even the plane of soul. And to understand this, we must first enquire about the soul. First, there is mind, mana·∏•, then intelligence, buddhi, then soul, ƒÅtmƒÅ. The soul is evergreen: it does not die. The soul is eternal, constant. It is said in the Upani·π£ads and in the <span class="e3">Gƒ´tƒÅ</span>: if once we can meet our soul, then a diametrical change comes in our life. At that time, we will be astonished to realise, ‚ÄúOh, such a highly qualified thing is here within me! In ignorance, I was considering that this perishable body and this flickering mind were my true self. But the material senses and mind are all trespassers. They have some inimical tendency towards my true self. I am soul. I have no necessity of all these things. Without these unnecessary material things I can live! No food is necessary for the soul from the jurisdiction of this material plane. The soul is independent. What a wonderful existence I have! In reality I am soul, and the nature of the soul is so noble, so high, so good.‚Äù A diametrical change of consciousness comes at this point and one tries to enter into that higher realm. Spiritual reality is what is necessary for us. We are soul, we are independent of matter. We are made of such transcendental existence. Nothing can threaten the soul‚Äôs existence‚Äînot the atomic bomb, nuclear war, lightning, thunder, or earthquakes. All the troubles of this material world are limited to this body which is a foreign carcass, a concocted representation of my true self. My true self exists on the spiritual plane, on a higher level. If we can really have a touch of that realisation, a glimpse of our own identity‚Äîif we can feel within that the soul is independent of matter‚Äîthen a revolutionary change will take place within our minds. Then, our attempt to progress in spiritual life becomes quite genuine. Otherwise, our progress is suspicious, doubtful. We grasp it intellectually and think, ‚ÄúYes, let me try. I‚Äôm hearing, of course, that I have a good prospect in spiritual life; by my intelligence I can follow something. Let me try.‚Äù But progress on the intellectual plane is only hesitating progress. When one comes to the plane of one‚Äôs own soul, however, one will find one‚Äôs self and realise, ‚ÄúHere I am!‚Äù At that time all false conceptions which have been held for so long will vanish like a dream. They will all be finished, and one will think, ‚ÄúI‚Äôm to start a new life.‚Äù And the new prospect will open to make progress in the higher plane.`},{class:`b44`,text:` Soul is nearby. We can try to find out what the soul is if we can eliminate the material elements. This is the process of the Upani·π£ads and is mentioned in the <span class="e3">Bhagavad-gƒ´tƒÅ </span>(3.42): <span class="e3">indriyƒÅ·πái parƒÅ·πáy ƒÅhur</span>. First we are to understand that our senses are primary. If my senses are removed, the entire world of our experience is nothing to me. Only through my senses can I be aware of the existence of the outside world. Minus senses, eyes, ears, no world is apparent to me. Then, above the senses is the mind. What is the mind? The mind deals with acceptance and rejection: sa·πÖkalpa-vikalpa. In other words, the mind thinks, ‚ÄúI want this; I don‚Äôt want that.‚Äù It deals with attachment and hatred. The mind determines who is enemy and who is friend. ‚ÄúThis is mine, that‚Äôs yours.‚Äù If we want to understand the mind, we have to look within, to enquire within: what is that element in me that seeks friends and avoids enemies? Where is he? Sometimes the mind is apparent; then other times it is hiding. I must find out where the mind exists. Of what substance is it composed? By analysis, I can understand what aspect of my inner self is the mind. Then, having some idea of what the mind is, I may analyse that part of me which deals with reason, the intelligence. Where is the intelligence?`},{class:`b44`,text:` When the mind demands something, the intelligence says, ‚ÄúDon‚Äôt take that, don‚Äôt eat that.‚Äù By introspection, I may look within and find out what is that principle in me which reasons? Where is that fine thing? What is its nature, its substance, its existence? We shall try in our introspection to find it out, substantially. If that is possible, then the next step will take us to the soul. What is that soul which makes possible the intelligence, the reason by which we act, which prompts the mind to want and also gives our senses the power to connect with things? What is that spark of knowledge? Where is that soul within me? What position does it hold? I want to see it face to face. Then in this way, we can evaporate like lightning all the misconceptions of the body and mind. By finding the soul through introspection, we may experience the lightning touch of realisation.`},{class:`b44`,text:` At that time, the whole world will be turned in a diametrically different line, and we shall see things differently: ‚ÄúOh, this material life is undesirable! These senses are enemies in the garb of friends. If I confront them now, they say that I may have an honourable friendship with them and that without them I can‚Äôt live. But it is all a hoax.‚Äù`},{class:`b44`,text:` From a realisation of the soul, from the point of that wonderful knowledge, one may come to see the ocean of knowledge. One may begin to see what is in the subjective area and hanker for how to come in connection with that divine realm. At that time, the very trend of one‚Äôs life will be changed, and a total change will come in our search, in our standard of prospect in life. And our search will take a concrete shape in devotion. In this way, we must begin our search after the higher sphere. And how to enter there?`},{class:`b44`,text:` It is the opposite of this plane of exploitation. In Milton‚Äôs <span class="e3">Paradise Lost</span>, Satan said, ‚ÄúIt is better to reign in hell than serve in heaven.‚Äù But we shall experience just the opposite: ‚ÄúIt is better to serve in heaven than to reign in hell.‚Äù To serve in heaven is highly superior than to reign in hell.`},{class:`b44`,text:` The question of energy and power is important in the mortal world, but in the constant and eternal world, this sort of energy has no value. That plane is composed of eternal substance. It is not like this troubling plane which is always breaking, always disappearing, always disappointing, and full of treachery. That divine plane is constant. Life goes on there without any need of food, rest, or medicine. There is no need of the labour to earn bread in that higher realm. All these things are not necessary in a plane of reality where everything is permanent and of eternal value. All these problems which are making us madly busy are easily eliminated in one stroke. That is the nature of that plane. And if we realise that we are members of that plane, then the question becomes what to do? How to approach the higher realm? That will be our problem. We cannot force our entry there; we must be granted a visa. We cannot master that finer realm; we must allow ourselves to be utilised by it. In other words, we must come to the position of slavery. We shall have to realise that mastership here in the mortal world is a curse and the slavery in that higher world is a boon.`},{class:`b51`,text:` And the <span class="e3">BhƒÅgavatam</span> will help us in our progressive march towards that higher plane.`},{class:`b60`,text:` na·π£·π≠a-prƒÅye·π£v abhadre·π£u nitya·πÅ bhƒÅgavata-sevayƒÅ<br />bhagavaty uttama-≈õloke bhaktir bhavati nai·π£·π≠hikƒ´`},{class:`b43`,text:` The impure, undesirable things within us are going to almost completely vanish, almost disappear by our serving association with the <span class="e3">≈örƒ´mad BhƒÅgavatam</span> and the devotee. SƒÅdhu and ≈õƒÅstra. In this way, the continuous connection with K·πõ·π£·πáa consciousness comes out from within. The interrupting elements that result from renunciation and enjoyment vanish, the covers vanish, and the continuous flow within, the connection with pure K·πõ·π£·πáa consciousness, comes out.`},{class:`b44`,text:` There are two covers: the exploiting tendency and the renouncing tendency‚Äîkarma and j√±ƒÅn‚Äîthe exploiting spirit and the tendency for knowledge that leads to liberation. They are not proper elements of our soul, of our real entity; they are only covers. And by our serving association with the <span class="e3">≈örƒ´mad BhƒÅgavatam</span> and the devotee, they are uncovered, and the continuous flow of K·πõ·π£·πáa consciousness within comes out.`},{class:`b51`,text:` Ni·π£·π≠hƒÅ means nairantarya, continuous:`},{class:`b60`,text:` ƒÅdau ≈õraddhƒÅ tata·∏• sƒÅdhu-sa·πÖgo ‚Äôtha bhajana-kriyƒÅ<br />tato ‚Äônartha-niv·πõtti·∏• syƒÅt tato ni·π£·π≠hƒÅ ruchis tata·∏•`},{class:`b50`,text:` When the covers are removed, then we find that inner continuity of flow with K·πõ·π£·πáa connection within us, and nai·π£thikƒ´-bhakti appears that is completely clear, cleansed. <span class="e3">Bhaktir bhavati nai·π£thikƒ´</span>: then on the basis of ni·π£·π≠hƒÅ, that is, the continuous flow, then further progress is made on the positive side‚ÄîƒÅsakti, attachment, then bhƒÅva, spiritual emotion, and then prema, divine love. In this way, the inner aspect of devotion will gradually come out. And we shall be able to dive deep into reality. As we give up the external covers and we experience what may be considered as death in the external world‚Äîdie to live‚Äîwe shall enter into the inner side more and more.`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Question: </span>This verse says <span class="e3">na·π£·π≠a-prƒÅye·π£v abhadre·π£u</span>: that the impurities are almost destroyed. Why not completely destroyed?`},{class:`b43`,text:` <span class="e2">≈örƒ´la ≈örƒ´dhar MahƒÅrƒÅj:</span> That means it happens gradually. The gradual development is described there. <span class="e3">Na·π£·π≠a-prƒÅye·π£u</span> means when the stage of ni·π£·π≠hƒÅ comes, when all the undesirabilities are almost finished, then we can have a real peep into the thing. Just as before sunrise, when there is twilight in the early morning, the sun is not there, but the darkness has been dispelled. The darkness has been mainly removed, but the sun has not yet risen. In the same way, the <span class="e3">BhƒÅgavatam</span> is describing how bhakti develops gradually. <span class="e3">Na·π£·π≠a-prƒÅye·π£u</span>: it is not finished immediately; there is a gradual process of sƒÅdhana‚Äîa means to an end. And gradually, slowly, according to the capacity of the devotee, and the endeavour, the sƒÅdhana, one‚Äôs bhakti develops. When darkness has almost been finished, the non-gentle, abnormal, exploitative symptoms, like the mean attempt to exploit the environment, gradually disappear. And in this way, gradually, we make further progress. It is not that all of a sudden‚Äîin one stroke‚Äîeverything is cleared. Rather, according to our bhajan, our sƒÅdhana, our attempt, the undesirable elements will gradually vanish, go away. And by different stages we shall reach the goal.`},{class:`b51`,text:` These stages have been described by R≈´pa GoswƒÅmƒ´ as follows in his <span class="e3">Bhakti-rasƒÅm·πõta-sindhu</span> (1.4.15‚Äì16):`},{class:`b60`,text:` ƒÅdau ≈õraddhƒÅ tata·∏• sƒÅdhu- sa·πÖgo ‚Äôtha bhajana-kriyƒÅ tato ‚Äônartha-niv·πõtti·∏• syƒÅt tato ni·π£·π≠hƒÅ ruchis tata·∏•<br />athƒÅsaktis tato bhƒÅvas tata·∏• premƒÅbhyuda√±chati<br />sƒÅdhakƒÅnƒÅm aya·πÅ prem·πáa·∏• prƒÅdurbhƒÅve bhavet krama·∏•`},{class:`b43`,text:` ‚ÄúIn the beginning there must be faith. Then one becomes interested in associating with pure devotees. Thereafter one is initiated by the spiritual master and executes the regulative principles under his orders. Thus one is freed from all unwanted habits and becomes firmly fixed in devotional service. Thereafter, one develops taste and then attachment. This is the way of sƒÅdhana-bhakti, the execution of devotional service according to the regulative principles. Gradually spiritual emotions manifest and intensify, then finally there is an awakening of divine love. This is the gradual development of love of Godhead for the devotee interested in K·πõ·π£·πáa consciousness.‚Äù`},{class:`b52`,text:` R≈´pa GoswƒÅmƒ´ says that ni·π£·π≠hƒÅ means ‚Äúcontinuous connection‚Äù. After ni·π£·π≠hƒÅ, the mundane negative side is eliminated, and then, in the positive side, we may make progress. Then, after this there are the higher stages: ƒÅsakti, bhƒÅva, and prema. Within prema, there are also different stages: sneha, mƒÅna, rƒÅga, anurƒÅga, bhƒÅva, and mahƒÅbhƒÅva. In this way, bhakti develops to the topmost plane, mahƒÅbhƒÅva. MahƒÅbhƒÅva means RƒÅdhƒÅrƒÅ·πáƒ´. That supermost intensity of bhakti which is not found anywhere else is found only in Her. That is called mahƒÅbhƒÅva. In this way, bhakti‚Äîdivine love‚Äîdevelops in different stages up to the highest level.`}]},{title:`The Plane of Misconception`,paragraphs:[{class:`b46`,text:`\r`},{class:`b47`,text:` The Plane of Misconception`},{class:`b99`,text:` This chapter is an excerpt from a conversation between ≈örƒ´la ≈örƒ´dhar MahƒÅrƒÅj and neurophysiologist Dr. Daniel Murphey, physical organic chemist Dr. Thoudam Singh, and Dr. Michael Marchetti.`},{class:`b43`,text:` We should understand that we are living in the plane of misconception. The whole thing is false. It is all a part of illusion. Within the world of illusion, something may have its place, but when we deal with the real truth, however, we will conclude that everything here is like a dream. This whole world is like a dream, a misconception. Any part of this world will therefore also be misconception. What is real, what is truth, will become apparent when a thing is judged in connection with the real world. The association of saints who have a genuine connection with spiritual reality promotes this transaction.`},{class:`b44`,text:` What is real and what is unreal? Whatever has a connection with the real self, with the soul, is real. Soul is consciousness in the world of pure consciousness. Whatever is connected with the mind in the mental world of false ego is all false. A part of the false is also false, extremely false. But it has got its negative utility.`},{class:`b44`,text:` Everything is true only by having connection with the Absolute Truth. Everything is there in the absolute. So, the finite cannot produce anything which is not in the infinite. The finite world, therefore, is rather a shadow or a perverted reflection of the whole truth.`},{class:`b44`,text:` The foundation of my argument is as follows: Chaitanya MahƒÅprabhu explained that while ≈öa·πÖkar ƒÄchƒÅrya has denied the existence of this perverted reflection, we cannot dismiss it. If it does not exist, then why has ≈öa·πÖkar come to preach VedƒÅnta? Illusion means ‚Äúthis is not that‚Äù. One thing may appear to be something else. An illusion is not what it appears to be, but it is not nonexistent. In that way it is real. It has its existence.`},{class:`b51`,text:` Within the real world which is created by the help of the Lord‚Äôs internal energy, svar≈´p-≈õakti, this world of misconception has no place. But in a relative way, the conditioned world has an indirect relationship with the unconditioned world. So, mƒÅyƒÅ is existing. In that sense it is true. But it is false in that it cannot give you the desired result you are searching after. In that sense it is all false.`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Dr. Marchetti:</span> Vai·π£·πáavism says that this material nature is real as a reflection. But it is not real as the absolute reality of the spiritual world. Could you explain?`},{class:`b43`,text:` <span class="e2">≈örƒ´la ≈örƒ´dhar MahƒÅrƒÅj:</span> Reality is composed of unreal substance and real substance. We may see it like that. This is the world of misconception. Misconception means, ‚ÄúI think something is mine, but really it is not mine.‚Äù Everything belongs to the Absolute. Everything belongs to Him. But we say, ‚ÄúIt is mine‚Äù, and we quarrel with each other. Actually, everything within this world is the property of another. But as a result of misconception, we fight with each other and so many reactions result from that fight. The difficulty is that the soul is entangled in this mock fight. Otherwise, this world of fighting and misconception has no value. But the dust of spirit, a very infinitesimal part of the spiritual reality, is entangled in this world and concerned with this world of mock fighting. Without the spiritual energy within this world, nothing would remain. A magician‚Äôs sleight of hand is all based on misconception. It is false. Still, we are perplexed by his tactics. That is also true. A magician or hypnotist can show what is not real to be real, and yet while we are under his spell we cannot deny its reality.`},{class:`b51`,text:` Everything, including our own self, belongs to K·πõ·π£·πáa. But the difficulty arises when we see something other than K·πõ·π£·πáa. Separate interest. The consciousness of separate interest is the root of all evils. We are one with K·πõ·π£·πáa, but whenever the seed of separate interest sprouts and we think we have some separate interest, that we are not included in the interest of K·πõ·π£·πáa, that is the root of such misconception.`},{class:`b60`,text:` bhaya·πÅ dvitƒ´yƒÅbhinive≈õata·∏• syƒÅd<br />ƒ´≈õƒÅd apetasya viparyayo ‚Äôsm·πõti·∏•<br />tan-mƒÅyayƒÅto budha ƒÅbhajet ta·πÅ<br />bhaktyaikaye≈õa·πÅ guru-devatƒÅtmƒÅ`},{class:`b50`,text:` In this way, the scriptures have given a diagnosis of the disease or concoction of false conception. We are living in a fool‚Äôs paradise. And the very beginning of material existence that we can trace is at the inception of separate interest. The first deviation from Advaya-j√±ƒÅn is a conception of separate interest.`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Question: </span>How can we know what is actually real?`},{class:`b43`,text:` <span class="e2">≈örƒ´la ≈örƒ´dhar MahƒÅrƒÅj:</span> The scriptural name is ≈õraddhƒÅ, or faith. That is the developed state of suk·πõti, or spiritual merit. When our faith is developed, it leads us to sƒÅdhu-sa·πÖga, the association of saints. The agents of the divine world, who are in the plane of reality‚Äîthe nirgu·πáa wave beyond this world of creation‚Äîcome to establish some connection with reality in our soul. That is the deepest element. The connection with saints produces faith, and faith can see reality.`},{class:`b51`,text:` There is a world which is only approachable by faith: <span class="e3">≈õraddhƒÅmayo ‚Äôya·πÅ loka·∏•</span>. Just as colour is seen by the eyes and sound is perceived by the ear, that world can be perceived only by faith. Only faith can see and feel it. The Supreme Reality cannot be perceived with any other senses. Faith is the real function of the soul and that is awakened by the agents of Vaiku·πá·π≠ha, the saints. By faith, one‚Äôs association with saints increases, and by this transaction the culture of reality takes place. Gradually, this process makes us become fully conscious. At that time we realise that this world in which we are living is all transient and that our home is elsewhere. Our real home is located in the world of pure consciousness.`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Question: </span>Is that the same process by which the materialist sees this world as real?`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">≈örƒ´la ≈örƒ´dhar MahƒÅrƒÅj:</span> No. Realisation of spiritual reality is independent of all material contamination or misconception. That injection into our soul is given by Vaiku·πá·π≠ha, by the eternal associates of Vi·π£·πáu. Perceiving spiritual reality is the function of the soul, not of the material ego or senses. It is independent of that. When a patient is unconscious, the doctor gives him an injection. Then consciousness comes, and after that he can cooperate with the doctor by describing his symptoms. But before one can cooperate with the doctor, the doctor does different things to help the unconscious patient. In the same way, when we are fully engrossed in our material engagement, the saints from the higher plane of reality act like doctors to inject some understanding of divinity into our consciousness. In this way, they try to awaken our spiritual self-interest, our consciousness of the soul.`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Dr. Singh:</span> Once BhaktivedƒÅnta SwƒÅmƒ´ MahƒÅrƒÅj asked us to prove that matter comes from life by using science. I didn‚Äôt know how to start. How can we prove that matter comes from life?`},{class:`b43`,text:` <span class="e2">≈örƒ´la ≈örƒ´dhar MahƒÅrƒÅj:</span> The definition of evolution given by Darwin is that life comes from the fossil. But we say just the opposite. Evolution from inside of consciousness is the cause of our seeing the different things of this world. The evolution is from within. Evolution is not from the outside, as we might ordinarily think. This is the teaching of VedƒÅnta. Reality does not develop from imperfection to perfection; it is only that a part of the perfection seems to be imperfect. To theorise that the imperfect is producing perfection is ludicrous.`},{class:`b44`,text:` It is far more reasonable and easy to conceive that a part of the perfection has somehow become imperfect. It is perceived by us to be imperfect. That is the natural and more reasonable conclusion. We have to accept something of what Darwin says but where does the fossil come from? And that the fossil can produce the infinite is a foolish idea.`},{class:`b44`,text:` The body is amazing the doctors with so many wonderful phenomena. They cannot fathom so many questions. How is it built? How are consciousness, intelligence, and genius centred in the brain? That wonderful thing which we find in the brain, the thought of the genius, is not produced by a material thing. The starting point must be the wonderful thing. We say that really exists‚Äîthat wonderful thing, the source of all wonders.`},{class:`b51`,text:` Everything is full of wonder. If we analyse the atom, we will be in wonder. Only we impose limitations. But when we analyse the atomic parts of wood or stone, we will be in wonder. The infinite is everywhere. Perfection is everywhere. The trouble is that with our limited thinking we have produced a world of limits. But we who are captured by the ‚Äúscientific‚Äù way of thinking are not ready to admit that. That is the puzzle. From the biggest to the smallest, from the lowest to the highest, everything is wonderful. But we won‚Äôt admit that. We will go to the fossil and say that the fossil is producing everything. But what is that fossil?`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Dr. Marchetti:</span> But how can we prove to the scientists that matter comes from life? These are philosophical arguments. The scientists will say, ‚ÄúWhat is the utility of philosophical arguments?‚Äù`},{class:`b43`,text:` <span class="e2">≈örƒ´la ≈örƒ´dhar MahƒÅrƒÅj:</span> In the beginning of the electric generation, the famous scientist Michael Faraday gave a public demonstration of the power of electricity. In one experiment, Faraday generated electricity. With the current generated by his dynamo, he was able to move some pieces of paper. After watching the wave of current move some pieces of paper, a lady challenged him, ‚ÄúWhat is the utility of your electricity, Dr. Faraday?‚Äù And he said, ‚ÄúMadam, would you please tell me, what is the utility of a newborn babe?‚Äù`},{class:`b44`,text:` Is death philosophical? Death is there to frustrate all other things if you don‚Äôt take shelter in philosophy. Only philosophy can face the greatest enemy, death. And death is not limited to a particular thing; it will include the whole world. The sun, the moon, the stars, this globe, and everything else will vanish in due course of time. The scientists themselves tell us so. If we want to live beyond the plane of death, philosophy will help us have an eternal life of eternal peace. Only philosophy can give us that.`},{class:`b51`,text:` All these sciences of technology are simply an attempt to increase the glamour of this life. They are all enemies of the soul, deadly enemies. All of them lead us but to the grave. The grave is true, and only dealing with the grave philosophically will relieve us. Otherwise, we are all finished. These materialistic scientific conceptions are cunning enemies surrounding us. They are tempting us, ‚ÄúLive in the material world. We shall help you.‚Äù This is illusion.`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Dr. Marchetti:</span> When you said that the world is in the mind, isn‚Äôt that idealism?`},{class:`b43`,text:` <span class="e2">≈örƒ´la ≈örƒ´dhar MahƒÅrƒÅj:</span> Berkeley‚Äôs idealism: not that we are in the world, but the world is in our mind. Of course in a higher sense, we are not concerned with the mind. The material mind is also a part of the world of misconception. The soul is living in the soul region, and the mind, ego, and everything else is dependent on the soul. If the soul is withdrawn, nothing remains. Here also, if life is gone, the body will perish.`},{class:`b44`,text:` If the souls are withdrawn from this world, nothing will remain. The soul is reality. This mundane reality is to be described as a misconception which appears in the soul much the same as a dream appears in a person. The soul himself is unconcerned. And if the soul is returned to the world of soul, and consciousness is withdrawn from this plane, nothing remains. It is all darkness. And it cannot exist independently. So, this material reality is created by the soul‚Äôs revolting attitude, his unhealthy attitude.`},{class:`b51`,text:` Just as a man who is in a diseased condition experiences delirium. Disease is the cause of delirium. The delirium itself has no independent existence. The hallucination does not exist outside his mind. If you want to remove the delirium, you must treat the patient. His brain needs medicine. When he is treated, the world of delirium vanishes. In a similar way, the soul has developed a diseased condition, and he suffers from delirium. And as the collective souls are suffering collectively from this delirium, this world appears real. Collectively so many misguided delirious persons are being connected or disconnected with this material reality.`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Dr. Murphey:</span> Then what is the difference between the world of reality and the material world?`},{class:`b43`,text:` <span class="e2">≈örƒ´la ≈örƒ´dhar MahƒÅrƒÅj:</span> This material world is only a reflection of complete reality; it is a conception we find exciting to us. Compelled by local interest of enjoyment, we have embraced this creation of the Lord. With our spiritual vision covered by the spectacles of prejudice, we are seeing things in a distorted way. The Lord is not to be blamed; our spectacles should be blamed. Everything is meant for Him. The only difference in our vision of reality is that our vision is tainted with the colours of our different kinds of selfish interests. And the different planetary systems in the material world are different sub-planes in the plane of enjoyment or exploitation. Our distorted consciousness is the source of the different colours of the things that surround us.`},{class:`b44`,text:` And when these illusory conceptions are fully removed, we will find that everywhere it is K·πõ·π£·πáa and K·πõ·π£·πáa only. And when the conception of Godhead as Lord and Master is removed, then receiving his impetus of activity from K·πõ·π£·πáa consciousness, the soul will find himself in V·πõndƒÅvan. But in order to attain that stage, we must have no consciousness of this body, or the mind, or the country conception, the nation conception, or the globe conception. All planes of limited conception must be crossed. From soul to Supersoul, the soul must enter deeper and deeper into reality. You will find everything there. There you will find that RƒÅdhƒÅrƒÅ·πáƒ´ and K·πõ·π£·πáa in V·πõndƒÅvan is not false. It is neither poetry nor imagination.`},{class:`b44`,text:` The only requirement is that we must develop our deeper nature, our self-identification, through self-determination. In Hegel‚Äôs language, self-determination is the fulfilment of all of us. Self-determination in the Vai·π£·πáava conception means svar≈´p-siddhi, spiritual identity. Who am I? What is my deeper self beyond my mind or my intelligence? Where am I? What is my inner self-interest? I must enter the plane of reality; I must get back my proper self. And in K·πõ·π£·πáa‚Äôs connection I will enter the environment and see what the world really is.`},{class:`b44`,text:` If I am given some wine or some poison, then I shall become beside myself. I shall see things in a distorted way. I will be unable to recognise my sister or mother, and actuated by animal nature, I will see everything as an object for my enjoyment. The crude tendency of lust will cover my vision of everything. Then again when I am sober, I shall see the same things, but my perception of them will be changed.`},{class:`b52`,text:` In this way, we must be prepared to go deeper beneath the surface reality, and find out who we are, what is our real self-interest. We should try to see the paraphernalia of reality according to our genuine self-interest. Through self-determination we must learn to see things the opposite of the way we are seeing them at present. We must try to understand how to find ourselves. And by surrendering ourselves to K·πõ·π£·πáa‚Äôs interest, then we shall try to go back home, back to Godhead.`}]},{title:`A Floating World of Experience`,paragraphs:[{class:`b46`,text:`\r`},{class:`b47`,text:` A Floating World of Experience`},{class:`b43`,text:` There are many schools of atheist philosophers. The most famous atheist in Indian philosophy was ChƒÅrvƒÅka Muni. His philosophy is paralleled by the extreme atheists of Western philosophy. According to their opinion, consciousness is the by-product of the chemical combinations of different material substances. With the dissolution of this physical body, neither soul nor consciousness remains. Only the physical combination of the different elements of the body remain. Just as the combination of different chemicals produces something more than the individual chemicals themselves, the physical combination of different material elements produce consciousness. With the dissolution of this fleshy body, nothing remains. This philosophy was first propounded in the West by Epicurus.`},{class:`b44`,text:` Then there is Buddhism. The Buddhists say that when the physical body is dissolved, the subtle body, the mental system, goes on to take another birth. The Buddhists admit transmigration from one body to the next, or reincarnation. According to them, although this body may vanish, we must enter another body according to our karma. If we work in a particular way, then the subtle body, the mental system, dissolves, and nothing remains. According to the Buddhists, there is no soul.`},{class:`b44`,text:` ≈öa·πÖkar ƒÄchƒÅrya‚Äôs philosophy is similar‚Äîwith a slight difference.`},{class:`b44`,text:` The Buddhist school says that the individual soul does not exist. According to them there is no permanent individual soul. ≈öa·πÖkar ƒÄchƒÅrya has also said that no permanent individual soul exists. But ≈öa·πÖkar ƒÄchƒÅrya says that conscious substance, brahma, exists as the ultimate reality. This is the difference between ≈öa·πÖkar ƒÄchƒÅrya and the Buddhists. According to ≈öa·πÖkar, consciousness itself is true; it is only the consciousness of separate existence that is false. In his view, the individual soul is only a reflection of the conscious substance which is the ultimate reality. With the dissolution of the mental system, each soul‚Äôs consciousness of individuality vanishes; it is nonexistent in that ultimate plane of reality.`},{class:`b44`,text:` He gives the example of the moon and its reflection in a mirror. Remove the mirror and there is no reflection. His view is that all individual souls are reflections from a common source: brahma, consciousness. So, ≈öa·πÖkar ƒÄchƒÅrya says in reality individual souls are one and the same with brahma.`},{class:`b44`,text:` ≈örƒ´ Chaitanya MahƒÅprabhu‚Äôs interpretation of VedƒÅnta is different from ≈öa·πÖkar ƒÄchƒÅrya‚Äôs. ≈örƒ´ Chaitanya says that we have to accept the Vedic truth in its entirety, without any modification. ≈öa·πÖkar ƒÄchƒÅrya has accepted only a few Vedic aphorisms which constitute a partial representation of the truth. His four principle expressions taken from the Vedas are, ‚Äú<span class="e3">Aha·πÅ brahmƒÅsmi</span>: I am brahma‚Äù, ‚Äú<span class="e3">Tat tvam asi</span>: thou art that‚Äù, ‚Äú<span class="e3">So ‚Äôham</span>: I am that‚Äù, and, ‚Äú<span class="e3">Sarva·πÅ khalv ida·πÅ brahma</span>: everything is brahma‚Äù. ≈örƒ´ Chaitanya analysed the meaning of the aphorism <span class="e3">sarva·πÅ khalv ida·πÅ brahma</span> as follows. According to ≈öa·πÖkar ƒÄchƒÅrya, everything is one. He says, ‚Äú<span class="e3">Brahma satya·πÅ jagan mithyƒÅ</span>: spirit is true, the world is false. ≈öa·πÖkar ƒÄchƒÅrya says that brahma (spirit) exists, and that sarva (everything) does not exist. If this is actually true, and everything is one, then why does the question of existence or nonexistence arise at all?`},{class:`b44`,text:` In the aphorism <span class="e3">sarva·πÅ khalv ida·πÅ brahma</span>, <span class="e3">sarva</span>‚Äîeverything‚Äîexists, and <span class="e3">brahma</span>‚Äîspirit‚Äîalso exists. In this expression, many exist and one also exists. There are many, and there is one.`},{class:`b44`,text:` Again, if everything is one, then the question arises: to whom are we speaking? For whom have the Vedas come with this advice? Both the relative and the absolute exist together; they are coexistent. The absolute and the relative are also represented in the VedƒÅntic aphorism <span class="e3">tat tvam asi</span>: thou art that. <span class="e3">Tat</span> or ‚Äòthat‚Äô is there, and <span class="e3">tvam</span>, ‚Äòyou‚Äô, is also there. Both variety and unity are found represented in the aphorism <span class="e3">tat tvam asi</span>, but ≈öa·πÖkar ƒÄchƒÅrya accepts one and rejects the other. His explanation is therefore a misinterpretation of the original meaning of the VedƒÅnta-s≈´tras. It is not a proper interpretation of the Vedas because he has thrust his own idea or conception forward in the name of the VedƒÅnta. ≈öa·πÖkar ƒÄchƒÅrya‚Äôs interpretation of VedƒÅnta is artificial. It is selfish and provincial.`},{class:`b44`,text:` This is the refutation of ≈öa·πÖkar ƒÄchƒÅrya given by ≈örƒ´ Chaitanya MahƒÅprabhu, and as far as we are concerned, it cannot be seen otherwise. If we try to follow the interpretation of ≈öa·πÖkar ƒÄchƒÅrya, then what meaning can be found in this statement of the Upani·π£ads, ‚Äú<span class="e3">Yato vƒÅ imƒÅni bh≈´tƒÅni jƒÅyante, yena jƒÅtƒÅni jƒ´vanti:</span> the Absolute Truth is He from whom everything is coming, who is maintaining everything, within whom everything exists, and into whom everything enters at the time of annihilation.‚Äù What does this mean? Does this statement say that the Absolute is nondifferentiated? It is sufficient for our understanding to accept its direct meaning. The self-explanatory meaning of these words is sufficient to understand this simple statement of the Upani·π£ads.`},{class:`b44`,text:` ≈örƒ´ Chaitanya MahƒÅprabhu defeats ≈öa·πÖkar ƒÄchƒÅrya through common sense. This is the unique characteristic of His argument. He defeats His philosophical opponents not with difficult, abstract, intellectual arguments, but with common sense.`},{class:`b44`,text:` When ≈örƒ´ Chaitanya wanted to demonstrate the supremacy of NƒÅrƒÅya·πá over ≈öiva, he said that one may just consider the position of the Ganges. The Ganges is the water that washes the feet of NƒÅrƒÅya·πá, and yet she rests on the head of ≈öiva. From this, we can easily use common sense to see which of the two holds the superior position. When ≈örƒ´ Chaitanya wanted to show that K·πõ·π£·πáa is greater than NƒÅrƒÅya·πá, He pointed to the example of Lak·π£mƒ´ Devƒ´. She aspires after the association of K·πõ·π£·πáa. Although she has everything with NƒÅrƒÅya·πá, still she has some aspiration for the company of K·πõ·π£·πáa. On the other hand, the gopƒ´s have no attraction for NƒÅrƒÅya·πá. When they meet NƒÅrƒÅya·πá, they pray that by His grace their devotion to K·πõ·π£·πáa may be enhanced.`},{class:`b51`,text:` In this way, by applying common sense, intuition, we may judge the nature of reality. Intuition will be far more helpful than abstruse argument. VedƒÅnta confirms this in the aphorism <span class="e3">tarkƒÅprati·π£·π≠hƒÅnƒÅt</span>: ‚ÄúArgument can never help us reach any real conclusion.‚Äù Rather, it is only intuition and common sense that can really help us. This is the recommendation of ≈örƒ´ Chaitanya, and this is how He refuted many scholars including even the great all-conquering Digvijayƒ´ Pa·πá·∏çit of Kashmir.`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Question: </span>The Buddhists say that after one transcends sensory experience, he will find that underneath it all there is actually no foundation of life. One will find that there‚Äôs nothing there but the void. According to their teaching, after our experience is removed, there is no soul, no basis of existence. How do the Vai·π£·πáava ƒÄchƒÅryas deal with Buddhism?`},{class:`b43`,text:` <span class="e2">≈örƒ´la ≈örƒ´dhar MahƒÅrƒÅj:</span> In South India, and especially in Andhra Pradesh, there are many Buddhist scholars. ≈örƒ´ Chaitanya MahƒÅprabhu met the Buddhists when He was passing through South India. Chaitanya MahƒÅprabhu says <span class="e3">Veda nƒÅ mƒÅniyƒÅ Bauddha haya ta‚Äô nƒÅstika</span>. Because the Buddhists do not accept the Vedic scriptures, they are considered atheists. ≈öa·πÖkar ƒÄchƒÅrya, in a hidden way, also preaches on behalf of the Buddhists. The difference between them is that ≈öa·πÖkar ƒÄchƒÅrya admits the existence of brahma as the fundamental reality whereas the Buddhists say that ultimately nothing exists.`},{class:`b44`,text:` The Vai·π£·πáava ƒÄchƒÅryas disagree with both ≈öa·πÖkar ƒÄchƒÅrya and with Buddha. They say that the jƒ´va is an individual eternal soul. This particle of spiritual energy known as the jƒ´va or spirit is tiny, like the dust particles of earth or the pencils-rays of the sun. There is the Supreme Infinite Soul or Consciousness, and the finite sparks of consciousness. Their relationship may be compared to the relationship between a great fire and the sparks that emanate from the fire. The sparks that emanate from the fire may become covered by darkness, but when they re-enter the shelter of that great conflagration, they are again perfectly situated.`},{class:`b44`,text:` To refute the atheism of the Buddhists, we may look to the modern European philosopher Descartes. Descartes said, ‚ÄúI doubt everything. Whatever you say, I doubt.‚Äù Then, Descartes says, the question that arises is, ‚ÄúDoes the doubter exist: true or false?‚Äù You have to start your search for truth from there. Who am I? To whatever truth is related, whatever idea is stated, one may say, ‚ÄúI oppose that statement. I doubt it.‚Äù Then the question arises does the doubter exist, or is he nonexistent? If he is nonexistent, then there can be no question of doubting. If one takes the position of an extreme sceptic, he must explain his own position. He may assert, ‚ÄúWhatever you have said, I doubt‚Äù, but he must discern whether or not he really exists. That must be the starting point for any further enquiry.`},{class:`b44`,text:` And what is the doubter? Is he an atom? A particle of dust? Is he without knowledge? And if so, then how has he comes to assert doubt? This question should be examined. Whenever one may doubt, the question must be asked, ‚ÄúWho is the doubter? Is he conscious? Does he have reason? Has he any existence at all? Or is he imaginary? Is it matter that is submitting the question? Or is a unit of consciousness asking the question? What is the origin of this question? Who is asking the question? Has it come from the conscious region? If it has, then what shall we consider as the basis of existence? Consciousness or matter? A fossil or God?‚Äù`},{class:`b44`,text:` Before the First World War, I was a student of law in the university. In my senior year, I studied philosophy under a professor named Mr. Stevenson. He was a German scholar, but during the war he took Indian citizenship. His class dealt with ontology and psychology. Professor Stevenson‚Äôs language was very simple, and he used fine arguments to make his point. He gave four arguments against atheism, one of which I find very useful: ‚ÄúConsciousness is the starting point of everything.‚Äù Whatever you say presupposes consciousness. Any statement presupposes consciousness.`},{class:`b44`,text:` If we examine the fossil, what do we see? It is black, it is hard, it has some smell, some attributes, but what are these things? These are all different stages of consciousness. Without the help of consciousness, no assertion can be made. No assertion is possible at all. One may say that the fossil is the most elemental substance, but a fossil means what? Some colour, sensation, hardness, taste, but the background is consciousness.`},{class:`b44`,text:` After everything is analysed, we will find that it is an idea. This is Berkeley‚Äôs theory. Everything is an idea in the ocean of consciousness. Just as an iceberg floats in the salt ocean, so the fossil is floating in the conscious ocean. Ultimately, everything‚Äîwhatever we can assert, whatever is within the world of our experience‚Äîis floating like an iceberg in the ocean of consciousness. This point can never be refuted.`},{class:`b44`,text:` I have had personal experience of this. When I was twenty-three, I had some deep and natural indifference to the world. At that time, I had an experience of the reality of consciousness. I felt the material world floating on consciousness just as cream floats on milk. Conscious reality is much deeper than the apparent reality of our present experience. The world of experience is like cream floating on milk which is the mind. This physical world is only the visible portion of reality floating over the mental world. I felt this myself. When there is a huge quantity of milk, the cream that floats over the milk and covers it is very meagre. In the same way, I could feel at that time that this physical world is only a meagre portion of reality, and that the subtle world, which is at present in the background, is far more vast. The mental world is a huge and vast reality, and the physical world is a small cover over that mental world.`},{class:`b44`,text:` Whatever can be perceived by the eye, the ear, the tongue, the nose, the skin‚Äîany of the external senses‚Äîis only a covering of reality. In <span class="e3">≈örƒ´mad BhƒÅgavatam</span>, PrahlƒÅd MahƒÅrƒÅj says, <span class="e3">na te vidu·∏• svƒÅrtha-gati·πÅ hi Vi·π£·πáu·πÅ durƒÅ≈õayƒÅ ye bahir-artha-mƒÅnina·∏•</span>. We are making too much of the covering of reality, we are devoting our minds to the external coating‚Äî<span class="e3">bahir-artha-mƒÅnina·∏•</span>‚Äîbut we do not dive deep into the eternal substance. If only we were to dive deep into reality, there we would find Vi·π£·πáu. The most peaceful substance is within, but it is covered, just as milk is covered by cream, and we are making much of that cover. The real substance is within, just as fruit is covered by its skin. What we experience at present is the cover, the skin, and we are making much of that, ignoring the very substance which the cover is protecting.`},{class:`b44`,text:` The primary step in the search for truth is to penetrate the covering and find the knower within. And then begin our analysis. What is he? Is he an atom like an atomic particle of dust? Or is he a fantastic atom in the conscious plane? At first we must approach reality in this way. There is the knower and the unknown, the enquirer and the enquired.`},{class:`b44`,text:` Try to find yourself. Then gradually, you will come to know that you are the soul, the particle of consciousness within. And just as you are spirit covered by matter, the whole world is also like that; the spiritual reality within is covered. Upon realising your self as spirit soul, you will be able to see that everything is a part of consciousness. Within the world of consciousness, worlds of different sorts of experience are floating. In the conscious sea, the sun, the moon, trees, stones, human beings, our friends, and our enemies are all floating. As we approach the spiritual plane, we will find it to be nearer to our real self. And in this way, we will see that matter is far, far away, but the soul is near.`},{class:`b44`,text:` Try to conceive of reality along these lines. Soul, spirit, consciousness, is nearer to the soul, and you are a child of that soil. Matter is far, far away. But the interrupting planes are so close together that we don‚Äôt see the nature of spiritual reality. Just as if you put your hand over your eye, you can‚Äôt see the hand. But if the hand is only one foot away, we can see it very clearly. Sometimes what is very close, we cannot see. I may be able to see so many things, but I cannot see myself.`},{class:`b51`,text:` Although the Buddhists and other atheists argue that consciousness is a material thing, I say that there is no material thing. If I am to answer the question of whether or not consciousness is produced from matter, then I shall say that nothing is material. Whatever we feel is only a part of consciousness. Everything is an idea. We are concerned only with consciousness from the beginning to the end of our experience. Beyond that we cannot go. Everything is an idea: the stone, the tree, the house, the body‚Äîall are ideas. The plane of consciousness is very much closer to us than we perceive. And what is shown as a particular thing is far away. We are involved only with ideas. We can‚Äôt go outside that. Everything within our experience is a part of our mind.`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Question: </span>The PurƒÅ·πáas say that there are 8,400,000 species of life. Are they only ideas?`},{class:`b43`,text:` <span class="e2">≈örƒ´la ≈örƒ´dhar MahƒÅrƒÅj:</span> All ideas. Consciousness is always in the primary position. Yet these ideas are real because they are also originally present in the spiritual reality V·πõndƒÅvan. Nothing is eliminated in our conception of reality; everything is harmonious. Everything has its proper position; nothing is to be eliminated. The only thing necessary is harmony. Only our outlook, our angle of vision, needs to be changed. But in order to have that kind of vision, we must give up being self-centred. Both exploitation and renunciation must be given up. These two things cause this hallucination. Everything has its contribution to the service of the Supreme Centre, and if we can understand that, we become free from this relative world. The material world is a reflection of the spiritual world. There is undesirability here. From BrahmƒÅ, who holds the highest position in this universe, to the lowest creature (<span class="e3">ƒÅbrahma-bhuvanƒÅl lokƒÅ·∏•</span>), everyone is prone to misconception. On the other hand, everything in V·πõndƒÅvan contributes towards the Pastimes of RƒÅdhƒÅ-Govinda.`},{class:`b44`,text:` Everything in V·πõndƒÅvan is K·πõ·π£·πáa conscious: every tree, creeper, and shrub. How can they be useless or ordinary shrubs and creepers? Uddhava is the greatest devotee of K·πõ·π£·πáa, and he aspires to take birth as a creeper or a shrub in V·πõndƒÅvan. What then, is the value of the shrubs and creepers of V·πõndƒÅvan! Should we think that Uddhava‚Äôs aspiration is imaginary or theoretical, with no practical value?`},{class:`b44`,text:` Everything in V·πõndƒÅvan is necessary for the Pastimes of RƒÅdhƒÅ-Govinda. Everything in the spiritual environment has its indirect value. This is called ≈õƒÅnta-rasa, or passive mellow. It may be understood in this way: if a man does not harm anybody, even a fly or a mosquito, that does not mean that he is paralysed or diseased; he is simply in a passive mood. So, in V·πõndƒÅvan, service may be rendered in a passive mood. The YamunƒÅ River, the trees, the birds, and the insects, are absorbed in rendering service in a passive mood.`},{class:`b44`,text:` How this is so can be understood by the analogy of a drama. In a drama in the theatre, an actor may play the part of a dead man. As his body is being carried, he can‚Äôt say anything; he can‚Äôt move. That does not mean that he is dead. Similarly, a devotee in ≈õƒÅnta-rasa may assume a passive role as a creeper, a shrub, or a tree in V·πõndƒÅvan, in order to enhance the drama of RƒÅdhƒÅ-Govinda-lƒ´lƒÅ.`},{class:`b44`,text:` A devotee may also accept the role of a servant. He may be a king, but for the satisfaction of the Lord, he may play the part of a sweeper. While one is playing the part of a sweeper, he may perform his role so nicely that the men standing by applaud in appreciation. So, the mood of servitude is also a contribution to the service of K·πõ·π£·πáa.`},{class:`b44`,text:` Another example of ≈õƒÅnta-rasa is RƒÅdhƒÅ Ku·πá·∏ça. RƒÅdhƒÅ Ku·πá·∏ça, the bathing place of ≈örƒ´matƒ´ RƒÅdhƒÅrƒÅ·πáƒ´, where K·πõ·π£·πáa enacts His Pastimes of conjugal love, is considered to be the highest place in V·πõndƒÅvan. The gods and devotees all praise RƒÅdhƒÅ Ku·πá·∏ça. Should we think it to be an ordinary body of water? Rather, how exalted is the position of RƒÅdhƒÅ Ku·πá·∏ça.`},{class:`b44`,text:` Then there is Govardhan Hill. That is also a kind of pose. Apparently it is a hill, but Govardhan is worshiped as K·πõ·π£·πáa Himself. He also appears as a stone, as ≈öƒÅlagrƒÅm; He appears in the form of the Deities.`},{class:`b44`,text:` ≈örƒ´ Chaitanya MahƒÅprabhu prays, ‚ÄúO Lord, please consider me as the dust of Your holy feet‚Äù, expressing Himself as a vibhinnƒÅ·πÅ≈õa jƒ´va. Foot-dust is generally inanimate. But when Chaitanya MahƒÅprabhu prays, ‚ÄúConsider me foot-dust‚Äù, the dust He speaks of is not matter; it is a unit of consciousness filled with knowledge and love. The dust of the Lord‚Äôs lotus feet is the emblem of knowledge and ecstasy. In the spiritual realm, existence and knowledge is presupposed. But more than that, the souls there are points of divine love in V·πõndƒÅvan and Nabadwƒ´p. And with the wholesale conversion of the souls of this world, everywhere we will find the kingdom of God. K·πõ·π£·πáa‚Äôs kingdom, MahƒÅprabhu‚Äôs kingdom, exists; we have only lost the proper angle of vision by which to see it. We must once again acquire that vision. At present we are in the midst of enemies, but if our angle of vision is changed, we shall think, ‚ÄúNo, I am in the midst of friends.‚Äù`},{class:`b44`,text:` And that angle of vision is so broad that one who sees in that way becomes fearless. When Ja·∏ça BhƒÅrat was captured by dacoits and taken to the deity of KƒÅlƒ´ to be sacrificed, his angle of vision was so spacious that he did not care for anything. He thought, ‚ÄúWhatever is happening is the Lord‚Äôs will. He is the proprietor and witness of all. He sees everything. Everything is His will, and I have nothing to do with the outcome.‚Äù With this idea, wherever Ja·∏ça BhƒÅrat was taken, he went without resistance. Although he was about to be sacrificed, he was unconcerned. He thought, ‚ÄúI am in a friendly circle. There is no danger.‚Äù He was in such a plane of consciousness that no apprehension, no danger, could affect him. He thought, ‚ÄúI am under K·πõ·π£·πáa‚Äôs care.‚Äù And so it is proved by Ja·∏ça BhƒÅrat‚Äôs practical example that this angle of vision is not simply philosophy or imagination. It is reality.`},{class:`b44`,text:` K·πõ·π£·πáa‚Äôs divine will is in the background of everything that exists. And when one comes in connection with that paramount power, that original plane of reality, he will not have any care; he will become fearless, <span class="e3">MayƒÅ santu·π£·π≠a-manasa·∏• sarvƒÅ·∏• sukha-mayƒÅ di≈õa·∏•</span> (<span class="e3">SB</span> 11.14.13).`},{class:`b44`,text:` Yet, in the plane of reality where K·πõ·π£·πáa is worshipped with knowledge-free devotion, j√±ƒÅna-≈õ≈´nyƒÅ-bhakti, that sort of posing is there. There appears to be fear and concern, but that concern is quite different in nature from material cares. Influenced by yogamƒÅyƒÅ, the gopƒ´s and K·πõ·π£·πáa‚Äôs friends want to know, ‚ÄúK·πõ·π£·πáa is not here! Where is He?‚Äù And in this way, the gopƒ´s and cowherd boys run here and there searching for K·πõ·π£·πáa. Even the cows are concerned and stop grazing, but all this is conducted by yogamƒÅyƒÅ for the satisfaction of K·πõ·π£·πáa. Such is the nature of lƒ´lƒÅ in the plane of j√±ƒÅna-≈õ≈´nyƒÅ-bhakti.`},{class:`b51`,text:` We are engaged in an inner search for truth. And in the Vedas the answer to our questions, the essence of the whole revealed truth of the scriptures, can be summarised in one word, Om: ‚ÄúYes!‚Äù What is the meaning of that ‚Äúyes‚Äù? ‚ÄúWhat you want: yes, it exists. What you are searching for: yes, it is there! Your inner search to live and to improve will be fulfilled: seek and ye shall find.‚Äù If you examine yourself and search out your innermost need, you will find that the revealed truth says, ‚ÄúYes, your thirst will be quenched. You will be well-fed.‚Äù`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Question: </span>In <span class="e3">Bhagavad-gƒ´tƒÅ</span>, K·πõ·π£·πáa says <span class="e3">jƒ´va-bh≈´tƒÅ·πÅ mahƒÅbƒÅho yayeda·πÅ dhƒÅryate jagat</span>: the spiritual energy is sustaining this material world. How are we to understand this?`},{class:`b43`,text:` <span class="e2">≈örƒ´la ≈örƒ´dhar MahƒÅrƒÅj:</span> The misguided souls of this world are from ta·π≠astha-loka, the marginal plane, and misguided by misconception they have come within this illusory angle of vision.`},{class:`b44`,text:` K·πõ·π£·πáa says this world is dead matter. The souls entered here and movement came. They entered into this material conception and began moving it. In that sense, they are sustaining the universe, <span class="e3">yayeda·πÅ dhƒÅryate jagat</span>. But ultimately everything is sustained by Him.`},{class:`b51`,text:` K·πõ·π£·πáa also says, ‚Äú<span class="e3">Aha·πÅ sarvasya prabhavo</span>: everything emanates from Me.‚Äù And in the Vedas it is said, <span class="e3">yato vƒÅ imƒÅni bh≈´tƒÅni jƒÅyante</span>. He is the origin of everything in its creation, its maintenance, and its annihilation. But here in this material world, the fallen souls as so many sparks have entered like glowworms into the dark region showing the darkness surrounding it. The jƒ´va-souls are like glow-worms in the dark night of this material world. Somehow they are carrying on in the darkness. We can barely trace them out as a meagre light in the dark. They are almost completely covered by darkness, but still they can be distinguished. Spirit can know itself.`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Question: </span>Who did you say was expounding the atheist philosophy in the West?`},{class:`b43`,text:` <span class="e2">≈örƒ´la ≈örƒ´dhar MahƒÅrƒÅj:</span> Epicurus is the greatest atheist of the West, as ChƒÅrvƒÅk Muni is in the East. According to Epicurus, with the dissolution of this physical body, nothing remains. And according to him there is no mental system; the mental system‚Äîwhat we come across in our dreams‚Äîdoes not have any separate existence. But ≈öa·πÖkar and Buddha both accept the existence of the mental system within the physical body. Transmigration of the soul is also admitted in their philosophy. But Buddha says that with the dissolution of the mental system‚Äîthe s≈´k·π£ma-≈õarƒ´ra‚Äînothing remains.`},{class:`b51`,text:` ≈öa·πÖkar ƒÄchƒÅrya, on the other hand, says that the consciousness within the mental body is a reflection of brahma, and brahma is the ultimate existence. According to him, with the dissolution of the body, nothing remains but brahma. ≈öa·πÖkar ƒÄchƒÅrya says:`},{class:`b60`,text:` ≈õlokƒÅrdhena pravak·π£yƒÅmi yad uktam grantha-ko·π≠ibhi·∏•<br />brahma satya·πÅ jagan mithyƒÅ jƒ´va brahmaiva nƒÅpara·∏•`},{class:`b43`,text:` ‚ÄúIn half a verse, I am summarising the truth that has been expressed by volumes and volumes of scripture. Within only half a verse I shall give the essence of all truths: ‚Äò<span class="e3">Brahma satya·πÅ jagan mithyƒÅ</span>: brahma, spirit, is true, this world is false, and the jƒ´va is nothing but brahma.‚Äô This is the substance of all the scriptures.‚Äù`},{class:`b44`,text:` Proper knowledge is not possible under the philosophical systems of Buddha and ≈öa·πÖkar ƒÄchƒÅrya. If what they say is true‚Äîthe world is false‚Äîthen we must ask, ‚ÄúWhy do you speak? And to whom? If everything is false, is your philosophy also imagination?‚Äù We will have to ask ≈öa·πÖkar ƒÄchƒÅrya, ‚ÄúDoes your coming to this world and your endeavour to refute Buddhism and establish oneness as the ultimate truth have no meaning? Who have you come to preach to? Why have you come to preach if this world has no reality? If this world is false, then why are you taking so much trouble to explain your philosophy? For what? Is your mission also imagination?‚Äù`},{class:`b44`,text:` The first great opponent of ≈öa·πÖkar ƒÄchƒÅrya was RƒÅmƒÅnuja. RƒÅmƒÅnuja‚Äôs refutation was very strong and based on a sound foundation. RƒÅmƒÅnuja argued: ‚ÄúWhat is the necessity for ≈öa·πÖkar ƒÄchƒÅrya to endeavour with so much energy to establish his philosophy if it is all fictitious? To say the world is false is a suicidal position. Has he come here to do nothing? He has come to correct us and free us from error, but there must be errors. Error or misconception has reality; otherwise, what is the necessity of spending so much energy refuting so many propositions? MƒÅyƒÅ exists. MƒÅyƒÅ is eternal. The individual soul is eternal, and mƒÅyƒÅ is also eternal.‚Äù`},{class:`b44`,text:` The basis of material existence is the possibility of the ta·π≠astha-jƒ´va committing a mistake and developing misconception. The soul is a·πáu-chetana, atomic consciousness. And as atomic units of consciousness, our freedom is not perfect. Our defective freedom is the cause of this illusion. The soul must have freedom. Before a crime is committed, the possibility of committing a crime is present in the ordinary peace-loving subject. The possibility of disease is there, so hospitals, medicine, and special diets are all necessary. In the same way, the possibility for misconception is there in the soul because we are weak and limited.`},{class:`b44`,text:` MƒÅyƒÅ, the world of measurement, is unnecessary for the Absolute, but necessary for those in the relative position. When there is only one self-interest, mƒÅyƒÅ is not necessary. But where there is division, differentiation, and distribution, when there are many ideas of self-interest, mƒÅyƒÅ is necessary.`},{class:`b44`,text:` Within the world of misconception, mƒÅyƒÅ is the law of the land. The law helps the law-abiding, and the law punishes the law-breaking. The law is the same for everyone, and that same law means protection for the good and suppression for the bad. Law means to divide rights. One and the same law provides for protection of the good and punishment of the bad. The svar≈´p-≈õakti, the Lord‚Äôs internal energy, helps the good, and the mƒÅyƒÅ-≈õakti punishes the bad.`},{class:`b44`,text:` ≈öakti, or energy, serves the purpose of the Lord, and therefore necessarily has two aspects, <span class="e3">paritrƒÅ·πáƒÅya sƒÅdh≈´nƒÅ·πÅ vinƒÅ≈õƒÅya cha du·π£k·πõtƒÅm</span>: to chastise the wicked and reward the good. When the Lord Himself appears, His purpose has two aspects: one for the good, another for the bad. He also comes here with that combined purpose. So, although He is one, we see these two aspects of His character.`},{class:`b51`,text:` The conception that the unity of the absolute is not a stale, nondifferentiated thing is a theory that was propounded by RƒÅmƒÅnuja. This is called vi≈õi·π£·π≠ƒÅdvaitavƒÅd, oneness with difference. The philosophy of ≈öa·πÖkar ƒÄchƒÅrya, on the other hand, is known as kevala-advaitavƒÅd, exclusive oneness. RƒÅmƒÅnuja accepts that the Absolute Truth is one, but according to him, it is a differentiated oneness. He does not accept nondifferentiated oneness. That it is one, he has no doubt. But that one is characterised by specification and differentiation. This is similar to the panentheism of Hegel.`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Question: </span>According to what you are saying, matter is also conscious because it is coming from the Lord who is the Supreme Consciousness. In the beginning, when we first differentiate between matter and spirit, we learn that matter is dead and the living entities manipulate it, but when we develop a higher realisation will we see that matter is also living?`},{class:`b43`,text:` <span class="e2">≈örƒ´la ≈örƒ´dhar MahƒÅrƒÅj:</span> Yes, and that is known as ≈õƒÅnta-rasa. In a higher stage of realisation we can detect consciousness everywhere: within glass, stone, earth, wood‚Äîin all the innumerable shapes and colours in which matter may appear.`},{class:`b43`,text:` We are always in the midst of consciousness. Consciousness is all-pervading but is situated in different gradations of conception. The gradation of conception may differ, but it is all consciousness, all eternal: <span class="e3">tva·πÅ tu rƒÅjan mari·π£yeti pa≈õu-buddhim</span>. We must try to reinstate ourselves in our own plane of reality. There, without the help of this mortal element, we can live happily. That transcendental plane is not a nondifferentiated world. It is not that there you have no individuality. If a nondifferentiated mass of consciousness can be admitted, then why should we not admit the existence of a system of consciousness? RƒÅmƒÅnuja says that it is a system. ≈öa·πÖkar ƒÄchƒÅrya says there is only a nondifferentiated mass of light-consciousness. RƒÅmƒÅnuja disagrees. He says that a differentiated light-mass of consciousness is the basis of reality. It is not undifferentiated or non-distinguishable.`},{class:`b44`,text:` And ≈örƒ´ Chaitanya MahƒÅprabhu says that the basis of reality is achintya-bhedƒÅbheda, inconceivable bipolarity. Everywhere there is something common and something different. Whatever opposing points you may discuss will have something in common, and something different. Nothing is quite the same as anything else. And above all, the infinite is not within your fist. It is inconceivable. The unified and differentiated character of reality is inconceivable; its secret is in the hand of the Supreme. It does not depend upon your whim. Still, that differentiated character of the Absolute will be seen differently according to the subjective relationship we have with Him.`},{class:`b51`,text:` An example of this is found in <span class="e3">≈örƒ´mad BhƒÅgavatam</span> (10.43.17):`},{class:`b64`,text:` mallƒÅnƒÅm a≈õanir n·πõ·πáƒÅ·πÅ nara-vara·∏• strƒ´·πáƒÅ·πÅ smaro m≈´rtimƒÅn<br />gopƒÅnƒÅ·πÅ sva-jano ‚ÄôsatƒÅ·πÅ k·π£iti-bhujƒÅ·πÅ ≈õƒÅstƒÅ sva-pitro·∏• ≈õi≈õu·∏•<br />m·πõtyur bhoja-pater virƒÅ·∏ç avidu·π£ƒÅ·πÅ tattva·πÅ para·πÅ yoginƒÅ·πÅ<br />v·πõ·π£·πáƒ´nƒÅ·πÅ para-devateti vidito ra·πÖga·πÅ gata·∏• sƒÅgraja·∏•`},{class:`b43`,text:` ‚ÄúWhen Lord K·πõ·π£·πáa, accompanied by Baladev, entered Ka·πÅsa‚Äôs wrestling arena, He appeared to the spectators in different ways. Everyone viewed Him according to their own relationship (rasa) with Him. To the wrestlers, He appeared as a lightning bolt. To the people in general, He appeared as the most beautiful personality. To the ladies, He appeared to be the most attractive young man, Cupid personified, and thus increased their lust. The cowherd men looked upon K·πõ·π£·πáa as their own kinsman coming from the same village of V·πõndƒÅvan. The kings who were present there saw Him as the most powerful ruler. His parents Nanda and Ya≈õodƒÅ saw Him as their most beloved child. Ka·πÅsa, the king of the Bhoja dynasty, saw Him as death personified. The worldly-minded saw Him as the universal form, the unintelligent saw Him as incapable, and to the yogis, He appeared to be the Supersoul. To the members of the V·πõ·π£·πái dynasty, He appeared to be their most celebrated descendant.‚Äù`},{class:`b51`,text:` When K·πõ·π£·πáa entered the arena, everyone saw Him in their own way. In this way, we can understand how He satisfies everyone. When Ya≈õodƒÅ sees Him, she says, ‚ÄúMy boy!‚Äù But the gopƒ´s see a grown-up‚Äînot a child. His friends see Him as one of their playmates. K·πõ·π£·πáa satisfies everyone. Even the animals in V·πõndƒÅvan become ecstatic when they come in connection with K·πõ·π£·πáa.`},{class:`b59`,text:` barhƒÅpƒ´·∏ça·πÅ na·π≠a-vara-vapu·∏• kar·πáayo·∏• kar·πáikƒÅra·πÅ<br />bibhrad vƒÅsa·∏• kanaka-kapi≈õa·πÅ vaijayantƒ´·πÅ cha mƒÅlƒÅm<br />randhrƒÅn ve·πáor adhara-sudhayƒÅp≈´rayan gopa-v·πõndair<br />v·πõndƒÅra·πáya·πÅ sva-pada-rama·πáa·πÅ prƒÅvi≈õad gƒ´ta-kƒ´rti·∏•`},{class:`b54`,text:` (≈örƒ´mad BhƒÅgavatam: 10.21.5)`},{class:`b43`,text:` ‚ÄúWhile the gopƒ´s were describing the sweet vibration of K·πõ·π£·πáa‚Äôs flute, they also remembered their Pastimes with Him; thus their minds became enchanted, and they were unable to describe completely the beautiful vibrations. While discussing the transcendental vibration, they remembered also how K·πõ·π£·πáa dressed, decorated with a peacock feather on His head, just like a dancing actor, and with blue flowers pushed over His ear. His garment glowed yellow-gold, and He was garlanded with a vaijayantƒ´ garland made of tulasƒ´, ku·πá·∏ça, mandƒÅra, pƒÅrijƒÅta, and lotus flowers. Dressed in such an attractive way, K·πõ·π£·πáa filled up the holes of His flute with the nectar emanating from His lips. So, they remembered Him, entering the forest of V·πõndƒÅvan, whose soil experiences the pleasure of consorthood upon being embraced by the touch of K·πõ·π£·πáa‚Äôs lotus feet.‚Äù`},{class:`b44`,text:` K·πõ·π£·πáa consciousness means full-fledged theism, up to consorthood. All conceptions of fulfilment are found there in their purest and most desirable position. This material world, however, is only a shadow, a black imitation of reality. Full-fledged theism means K·πõ·π£·πáa consciousness. In the full-fledged conception of theism, the Infinite embraces the whole of the finite. It comes down to completely embrace and welcome the finite. This kind of full-fledged theism is found in V·πõndƒÅvan. There, one negligent part of the finite may find the bliss of the embrace of the whole of the Infinite. In V·πõndƒÅvan, not a corner of the finite is left unfulfilled; every particle of sand and every creeper is well-represented there with complete personality in the loving Pastimes of ≈örƒ´ K·πõ·π£·πáa.`},{class:`b44`,text:` Here in this material world, however, a particle of sand is nothing; it is ignored. But there, everything is well-attended. In V·πõndƒÅvan there is no ignorance. No interest of anything is ignored there; everything is harmonised, and therefore the conception of V·πõndƒÅvan in K·πõ·π£·πáa consciousness is the highest conception of full-fledged theism. <span class="e3">≈örƒ´mad BhƒÅgavatam</span> says, ‚ÄúWhenever K·πõ·π£·πáa sets His lotus feet within V·πõndƒÅvan, the earth personified says, ‚ÄòMy fate is fulfilled. I have achieved my highest fortune.‚Äô In V·πõndƒÅvan, the earth, the very dust, feels the pleasure of the highest type of conjugal love merely by the touch of His lotus feet. Wherever K·πõ·π£·πáa puts His footsteps, the earth‚Äôs joy knows no bounds. By His touch, the earth feels the most intense type of ecstasy.`},{class:`b44`,text:` In V·πõndƒÅvan, K·πõ·π£·πáa is mƒÅdhurya, sweetness personified. He is ƒÅnanda, ecstasy personified. And K·πõ·π£·πáa responds to our own inner demands in every way. The Supreme Centre has the peculiar capacity of responding to all our needs and satisfying the thirst of all existence. According to their capacity, rank, and dignity, K·πõ·π£·πáa distributes to all souls the juice from the sweet sea of transcendental mellow, <span class="e3">yo yach chhraddha·∏• sa eva sa·∏•</span>.`},{class:`b44`,text:` One can taste the sugar-candy sweetness of the Absolute according to one‚Äôs capacity, just as sugar candy is tasted in different ways. For a normal tongue, sugar candy is very sweet, but if there is a boil on the tongue even sugar candy is bitter.`},{class:`b52`,text:` When a man is working, his manager will see him as a worker, his child will see him as a father, and his wife will see him as a husband. His servant will see him as master. Dogs and other animals will view him in another way. The same person will be seen differently according to the relationship between seer and seen. Similarly, K·πõ·π£·πáa appears differently to those who view Him according to their respective rasa. In this way, the differentiated character of the Absolute is revealed according to the soul‚Äôs subjective qualifications.`}]},{title:`Thesis, Antithesis, & Synthesis`,paragraphs:[{class:`b46`,text:`\r`},{class:`b47`,text:` Thesis, Antithesis, & Synthesis`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">≈örƒ´la ≈örƒ´dhar MahƒÅrƒÅj:</span> What subjects are you studying?`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Student:</span> Philosophy and religion.`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">≈örƒ´la ≈örƒ´dhar MahƒÅrƒÅj:</span> In which university?`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Student:</span> San Francisco State.`},{class:`b43`,text:` <span class="e2">≈örƒ´la ≈örƒ´dhar MahƒÅrƒÅj:</span> You are a student of religion and philosophy. Have you studied Hegel? Hegel‚Äôs philosophy is sometimes described as panentheism. Panentheism proposes that God is present in all things, but in contrast to pantheism it affirms that God is also an independent being above and beyond all things. Hegel is also known for Perfectionism. He says that the nature of the Absolute is both conditioned and unconditioned combined. The truth develops through thesis, antithesis, and synthesis, and by this method everything progresses. According to Hegel, the Absolute is by Itself and for Itself. And he also used the German equivalent of the expression ‚Äúdie to live‚Äù. These were his chosen expressions.`},{class:`b51`,text:` Such expressions are very useful for those in the theistic line. If you want to live a progressive life, you will have to die as you are. Your ego must be dissolved, and then the real inner or finer self will come out. This is a good philosophy to have appeared amongst the Westerners. The concept of die to live comes in the line of Vai·π£·πáavism. Hegel has also said that the Absolute is ‚Äúby Himself‚Äù and ‚Äúfor Himself‚Äù. ‚ÄúFor Himself‚Äù means that the Absolute Truth is the Supreme Enjoyer. In the <span class="e3">Bhagavad-gƒ´tƒÅ</span>, K·πõ·π£·πáa says:`},{class:`b60`,text:` aha·πÅ hi sarva-yaj√±ƒÅnƒÅ·πÅ bhoktƒÅ cha prabhur eva cha<br />na tu mƒÅm abhijƒÅnanti tattvenƒÅta≈õ chyavanti te`},{class:`b43`,text:` This is the most vital point to establish God as a person. He is the enjoyer. If anything is enjoyed, the enjoyer will hold the supreme position. This cannot but be. Everything is meant for His enjoyment. And He is the supreme. ‚ÄúBy Himself‚Äù means that the Absolute is supreme‚Äîeverything is meant for His satisfaction. This is a necessary truth; it is not questionable. And also, His existence is subjective.`},{class:`b51`,text:` No object can exist without a subject. No thing can exist without a thinker. There must be a thinker. For example, what is a fossil? As we examine it, we observe colour and the hardness of stone, but these qualities are simply thoughts within us‚Äîa thinking stage. What is colour? A concept within our consciousness. So any kind of existence presupposes a subject or consciousness. This is the crux of the argument. No object can exist without a subject. And no subject can exist without an object. There is the thinker and the thought. If there is a thinker, he must be thinking something‚Äîso an object is there. And if there is an object, then whatever attribute it has must be reflected in the consciousness of a subject. Otherwise, no existence is possible. Do you follow?`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Student:</span> Yes. It is very clear.`},{class:`b43`,text:` <span class="e2">≈örƒ´la ≈örƒ´dhar MahƒÅrƒÅj:</span> These are all Hegel‚Äôs original conceptions, his contributions to philosophy. He was a very important philosopher. And for a Western thinker, his philosophy was very near to that of the Eastern thinkers. In many respects, Hegel‚Äôs philosophy is very close to RƒÅmƒÅnuja‚Äôs philosophy.`},{class:`b51`,text:` Of course, there are many important Western philosophers. Kant‚Äôs philosophy is very influential. Are you familiar with Kant?`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Student:</span> Yes.`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">≈örƒ´la ≈örƒ´dhar MahƒÅrƒÅj:</span> Have you studied Descartes?`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Student:</span> Yes, somewhat. He said, ‚ÄúI think, therefore I am.‚Äù`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">≈örƒ´la ≈örƒ´dhar MahƒÅrƒÅj:</span> He is said to be the father of modern philosophy. Then there is Berkeley: he is an extreme subjective thinker. Locke, Hume, Mill, Berkeley, Johnson, Kant, Hegel‚Äîall these are important Western philosophers.`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Student:</span> I prefer to study Eastern philosophy.`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">≈örƒ´la ≈örƒ´dhar MahƒÅrƒÅj:</span> What kind of Eastern philosophy do you study? SƒÅ·πÖkhya? Yoga? NyƒÅya? Vai≈õe·π£ika?`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Student:</span> Zen Buddhism and Taoism‚ÄîChinese philosophy.`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">≈örƒ´la ≈örƒ´dhar MahƒÅrƒÅj:</span> Confucius came from China. Before Buddhism, Confucius was present in China. Then gradually moving West, we find Socrates, Plato, and Aristotle. Have you studied them?`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Student:</span> Yes, I have studied them a little.`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">≈örƒ´la ≈örƒ´dhar MahƒÅrƒÅj:</span> The concept of Parallelism forwarded by Plato is also accepted in Vai·π£·πáava philosophy to a certain extent. According to Plato, the forms we experience are a reflection of ideal form. This was his understanding of how the forms we perceive are a perverted reflection of the original spiritual world. That is the theory of Parallelism of Plato.`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Student:</span> Can you please explain more about the parallels between Hegel‚Äôs philosophy and K·πõ·π£·πáa consciousness?`},{class:`b43`,text:` <span class="e2">≈örƒ´la ≈örƒ´dhar MahƒÅrƒÅj:</span> In Hegel‚Äôs philosophy, truth progresses through thesis, antithesis, and synthesis. The truth moves in a crooked way. In the philosophy of K·πõ·π£·πáa consciousness, the word <span class="e3">vilƒÅsa</span> means ‚Äúplayful movement‚Äù. You may take it to mean that the Absolute is absorbed in play. And that is expressed through crookedness. <span class="e3">Aher iva gati·∏• premna·∏• svabhƒÅva-ku·π≠ilƒÅ bhavet</span>: a serpent moves in a crooked way. Similarly, the movements of the Absolute are not straight, but crooked. VilƒÅsa, or the conception of lƒ´lƒÅ‚Äîthe divine Pastimes of the Lord‚Äîis something like that. This is similar to Hegel‚Äôs opinion in which the truth develops in a crooked way through thesis, antithesis, and synthesis. There is thesis, then its opposite, and then again they unify and create a new thesis. Then again antithesis, and again a greater harmony in synthesis.`},{class:`b51`,text:` In this way, truth is dynamic; it develops and makes progress. Hegel was the deepest thinker amongst the Western philosophers. Of course, other German scholars like Max Muller were also deep thinkers. In fact, Germany had such great appreciation and fondness for Indian culture that certain ancient books that can no longer be found in India may still be found in Germany. The Germans were never the colonial masters of India, but still they were extremely inquisitive to know about the cultural books of India. In spite of the war, many rare, ancient Indian books that can no longer be found in India are still safely preserved in Germany.`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Student:</span> I had a question regarding the philosophy of Berkeley. According to Berkeley the world is in the mind. It seems that the Berkeley theory tends to negate the existence of this world. It tends to argue against any type of reality.`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">≈örƒ´la ≈örƒ´dhar MahƒÅrƒÅj:</span> But Hegel has come to relieve Berkeley somewhat. Someone may challenge Berkeley: ‚ÄúI may think that there is a hundred dollars in my pocket, but if I search my pocket, will I find it there?‚Äù Hegel says that it must be there somewhere in the Universal Mind. That is Hegel‚Äôs standpoint.`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Student:</span> Then it is present somewhere.`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">≈örƒ´la ≈örƒ´dhar MahƒÅrƒÅj:</span> And that wave comes gradually. This was my argument regarding Bhakti Vinod ·π¨hƒÅkur‚Äôs <span class="e3">Jaiva Dharma</span>. Have you read that book?`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Student:</span> No, I‚Äôm not familiar with that book.`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">≈örƒ´la ≈örƒ´dhar MahƒÅrƒÅj:</span> In that novel, the characters who speak on spiritual life are apparently imaginary. The different persons in that book‚ÄîVrajanƒÅtha, the BƒÅbƒÅjƒ´, and others‚Äîseem to be imaginary characters discussing spiritual life. But I once explained that what is in Bhakti Vinod ·π¨hƒÅkur‚Äôs mind, what he has written in <span class="e3">Jaiva-dharma</span>, is not imagination. At one time or other, the persons and events he mentions must have existed, and these things will again have to come into existence. Do you follow?`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Student:</span> I‚Äôm not sure.`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">≈örƒ´la ≈örƒ´dhar MahƒÅrƒÅj:</span> What Bhakti Vinod ·π¨hƒÅkur saw in his mind must exist somewhere in this world, sometime in the future, or sometime in the past. That very thing he describes in an apparently fictional way actually existed. Let me give you an example. When I speak, the sound moves at a certain speed. That sound can be heard later in another place. The same is true in the case of light, isn‚Äôt it?`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Student:</span> Yes.`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">≈örƒ´la ≈örƒ´dhar MahƒÅrƒÅj:</span> So, ≈örƒ´ Chaitanyadev, with His divine sound, chanted here and performed sa·πÖkƒ´rtan. He preached and the velocity of that divine wave is still going on. And now in some place in a universe, it may be found. Do you follow? Am I clear?`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Student:</span> I think so.`},{class:`b43`,text:` <span class="e2">≈örƒ´la ≈örƒ´dhar MahƒÅrƒÅj:</span> The velocity of that light is going on; it is not lost. In the same way, the sounds I am now pronouncing are not lost; they are travelling for some distance through time and space. Whatever I see, that wave of light, is also travelling. The radio broadcasts from World War II‚Äîthat war period, the war vision‚Äîis also there in space somewhere, vibrating at a certain rate. That vibration was once here, but now it is somewhere else. It is floating in some plane of reality in time and space. If I throw a flower into the waters of the Ganges, then it is carried away by the current. If I can move with more speed than the current, I can find that flower somewhere else far away in the river. So, the velocity of light‚Äîeyesight velocity‚Äîmoves 186,000 miles in a second. If it is possible to move faster than the speed of light, then we can overtake the wave of visual events that are carried by that light. It is possible.`},{class:`b44`,text:` In a similar way, what exists in the plane of imagination now must have existed in reality at some time in the past or future, but it is now found somewhere else. It is said that the Pastimes of K·πõ·π£·πáa move from one universe to the next in the same way that the sun moves from one time zone to the next. Now morning is here; five minutes from now, sunrise and morning will take place somewhere else. In this way, it is always sunrise somewhere. Here or there, the rising sun is to be found somewhere on the earth. If we can move at the speed of the sun, then for us it will always be sunrise.`},{class:`b44`,text:` What came within the mind of Bhakti Vinod ·π¨hƒÅkur, what he may have described in an apparently fictional way, must exist somewhere in the plane of reality in the past or in the future. It is reality, not imagination.`},{class:`b44`,text:` Everything is real. It is not imagination. What I see in my dreams is now false. But in some former lifetime in my past, I experienced that reality. I had that sort of vision, and that has come to me now as a dream. It was a fact, and only now is it a dream.`},{class:`b51`,text:` What is in the mind may be abstract to us, but in the Universal Mind, everything is concrete. Whatever exists within the plane of imagination must be and can be traced somewhere.`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Student:</span> Although everything is, in one sense, in the mind, still, when I feel hot and I find that others also feel hot, I conclude that it is hot. It seems that according to Berkeley, this is just going on in my mind.`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">≈örƒ´la ≈örƒ´dhar MahƒÅrƒÅj:</span> You have to understand the fundamental truth that what is hot to you may be a cold environment for some other organism. It is a question of degree. Our experience of coolness and heat depends on our degree of tolerance. What is cool to us may be hot to another. In this way, we have to adjust with the idea of reality; what is hot to me may be cool to another. Reality is one thing for human beings; it is something else entirely for insects, worms, and other organisms. What is bright to us is dark to another. What is bright to an owl is dark to us. Do you follow?`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Student:</span> Yes.`},{class:`b43`,text:` <span class="e2">≈örƒ´la ≈örƒ´dhar MahƒÅrƒÅj:</span> Creation is of a variegated nature. The experience of our eyes and ears is different from the experience of others whose senses are different from ours. What we can hear, others cannot hear. But our ears cannot detect subsonic or ultrasonic sounds. Our ears can detect only a limited spectrum of sound. Our vision is also limited. We can see neither infrared nor ultraviolet light. Our feeling, our sense of touch, is sensitive to an extremely limited degree. So, all realities are coexistent; reality is adjusted according to our own experience. Something feels cool to me; that very thing is hot to another. In this way, it is ‚Äúhot‚Äù or ‚Äúcold‚Äù according to our subjective experience. And so ‚Äúour reality‚Äù will exist. So, what is perceived by the mind is not imagination; it is reality. What is imagination to me is reality to another. The rising sun and the setting sun can be perceived simultaneously from different angles of vision. Within the whole creation, all experience is coexistent.`},{class:`b51`,text:` What you now feel to be cool, you can easily feel to be very hot by the will of the Supreme Lord. By His will, everything is possible. Everything depends on Him. He is the ultimate cause. What you consider as intolerably hot, you will be forced to feel as intolerably cold in a minute if God so wills it. Everything depends upon His will. And that is coming here in either a modified way, in a general way, or in a particular special way according to His whim. In this way, there may exist a gradation in how He manifests His will, but His will is the prime cause of everything. And He is above law. We must be conscious of that. Then we will be able to explain anything.`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Student:</span> So, He is something like a hypnotist.`},{class:`b43`,text:` <span class="e2">≈örƒ´la ≈örƒ´dhar MahƒÅrƒÅj:</span> Yes, He is a hypnotist. Everything depends on the sweet will of the Absolute. Everything is designed and destined by Him. Everything is in His hands. The Absolute Centre is by Himself and for Himself. He alone knows the purpose of everything. No one else. He alone knows His ways; no one else can know His ways. We may know only as much as He wants us to know. And that also can change by His sweet will. So, He is completely free, an autocrat.`},{class:`b44`,text:` And that Supreme Autocrat can be captured only by love, not by knowledge. His ways are uncertain. How will our knowledge help us to understand Him? Knowledge may be useful in understanding a thing if it follows a fixed law and has a fixed nature. But the Absolute is an autocrat; at any moment He can change all the laws. Then how shall we know the Infinite? In trying to understand the Absolute Truth, all our previous experience becomes null and void. At every second He can show us a new colour. No degree of knowledge can make any clear statement of truth about God. Knowledge is futile in regard to the Infinite. First He is moving in one way, then another. On what basis will we make our calculation? His position is always changing by His sweet will.`},{class:`b51`,text:` His heart can be captured only by surrender. Through surrender alone we may please Him. And if He likes, He may make Himself known to us, but even then we may only know that portion of His personality, only that much about Him, that He cares to reveal to us. The designer of reality is an autocrat; He is above law. We must consider this carefully. He who is designing this universe is above law. He is not under the jurisdiction of any law. He does not have any fixed nature. At any time, He may change His position according to His sweet will. And whatever He wills, that must come about.`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Student:</span> Bertrand Russell says that if there is a God, He must not be good. God Himself is not bound by law, but if we violate the law of God, we suffer. If God were good, He could have created all the souls of this world above law.`},{class:`b43`,text:` <span class="e2">≈örƒ´la ≈örƒ´dhar MahƒÅrƒÅj:</span> If he says that, then that means that he wants to become the God of Gods. To Mr. Russell we say, ‚ÄúThe Absolute Truth is unknown and unknowable. How can His ways be known? He is an autocrat. And you want to impose your crooked, meagre, finite experience upon the Universal Truth! Your experience is the limited of the limited. And you want to thrust that small experience onto the unlimited whole? It is a most deplorable argument based on an assertion of faulty knowledge. From your finite position, you want to know the measure of the whole Infinite and then criticise Him. What is the foundation of your criticism? From what basis are you approaching the Infinite to criticise Him? How much do you know about Him?`},{class:`b44`,text:` ‚ÄúIf you see a mother chastising her son, and you see only that portion of her behaviour, you may conclude that she is very cruel. But you do not know the affection with which the mother cares for the child. You are not aware of how she feels for his future good. You are unaware of all this. You may say that she is punishing the son and that she is therefore cruel, but you do not know the context of her behaviour. Every incident must have its future and its past, and you must carefully trace that out before passing any judgment or making any remark.`},{class:`b51`,text:` ‚ÄúIn your case, how much are you limited in relationship to the Infinite? To what extent can you understand Him? Your capacity for knowing the Infinite is very meagre. No one should attempt to make any remark about the infinite will on the basis of his own limited capacity. That is injudicious and suicidal to a man of understanding.‚Äù`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Student:</span> I have heard it said that according to Vedic ontology, the soul is marginal. Do the jƒ´va-souls in the marginal or ta·π≠astha position have knowledge that there is an upper and a lower world, that there is suffering in the material world, and divine service in the spiritual world?`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">≈örƒ´la ≈örƒ´dhar MahƒÅrƒÅj:</span> A jƒ´va-soul has adaptability of both sides; marginal means, ‚ÄúEndowed with adaptability towards both the spiritual and material worlds without participation or any experience of either.‚Äù The marginal soul (ta·π≠asthƒÅ-jƒ´va) has only seed adaptability towards both. He is situated in the margin between the spiritual and material worlds, and the margin strictly means that one is in a position to analyse adaptability. He can go towards the spiritual world, and he can come towards the material world. The possibility of either is there in potentiality, but he is left to exercise his freedom. Because the soul is a conscious unit, he has free will. Freedom is inseparable from consciousness. A conscious unit and freedom are one and the same. Conscious atom means endowed with freedom. Without freedom, it is matter.`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Student:</span> The soul has freedom, but does it have knowledge of the different aspects of reality?`},{class:`b43`,text:` <span class="e2">≈örƒ´la ≈örƒ´dhar MahƒÅrƒÅj:</span> Because the soul is very small, his freedom is also imperfect; a soul in the marginal position is very vulnerable. Freedom does not mean absolute freedom. Because the soul‚Äôs existence is small, his freedom is defective; there is the possibility of committing a mistake. Freedom of the minute soul does not mean perfect freedom. Complete freedom would be perfect reality, but the minute soul is endowed with the smallest atomic freedom. This is the position of the atoms of consciousness, and this is why they are vulnerable. They may judge properly or improperly; that is the position of those who are situated in the marginal position. If the soul were not endowed with the freedom to determine his position, we would have to blame God for our suffering. But we cannot blame God. The starting point of the soul‚Äôs suffering is within himself.`},{class:`b44`,text:` The suffering of the soul in bondage is similar to the suffering of one who is addicted to a drug. Before one begins taking intoxication, the first step towards addiction is curiosity. Then after one has taken intoxication for a certain amount of time, he cannot do without intoxication. Our attachment to mƒÅyƒÅ, or misconception, is like addiction to a drug. At first we are curious, but when we become habituated to the intoxication of misconception, we are forced to continue using that intoxicating substance.`},{class:`b44`,text:` Before beginning the habit it might never have begun. But once you have begun, as much as you cultivate an addiction, the intoxication will devour you.`},{class:`b51`,text:` The first cause of our entanglement with material nature was our mixing with mƒÅyƒÅ in a play of curiosity. But as much as we make friends with her, so much she comes to devour us. In this way, we are in the clutches of mƒÅyƒÅ. But in the beginning our involvement was very slight like one experimenting with drugs. The beginning of our play with mƒÅyƒÅ involved the voluntary misuse of our free will, and that has led us to this present stage where mƒÅyƒÅ has devoured us. MƒÅyƒÅ means our attraction for intoxication: where there is love of exploitation, there is mƒÅyƒÅ. And truth is the opposite of exploitation. Truth is found in dedicating everything for the Centre, for K·πõ·π£·πáa.`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Student:</span> If in the marginal position (ta·π≠asthƒÅ) the soul has exposure to both reality and illusion, why doesn‚Äôt he have enough discrimination to come to the right path?`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">≈örƒ´la ≈örƒ´dhar MahƒÅrƒÅj:</span> He has no real depth of discrimination; only a little discrimination. But it is there. However small it may be, it is there.`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Student:</span> Can he also go to the spiritual domain of the Lord?`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">≈örƒ´la ≈örƒ´dhar MahƒÅrƒÅj:</span> Yes, and some souls do go to that side. Some go to that side, and some come to this side. The soul has independence. Not all come to one side or the other. Then there would be some compulsion. But there is no compulsion. It is a free choice; some are coming to this side, and some are going to that side.`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Student:</span> Is there any knowledge that can come from outside, or is it possible for the soul in the marginal position to get help from an outside agent?`},{class:`b55`,text:` <span class="e2">≈örƒ´la ≈örƒ´dhar MahƒÅrƒÅj:</span> At every stage in our existence, outward help is present. But in the undifferentiated stage of spiritual existence in the marginal plane, only higher agents can help. An ordinary saintly person cannot detect the defects or transcendental qualities in the undifferentiated soul. Such help is the work of a higher personality. Only God Himself or an exalted or empowered saintly person can help a soul in that condition. Suppose you have a newborn baby. Only a doctor who is a specialist with advanced knowledge can treat the newborn. But when the child is a little grown up and can talk, he can explain the symptoms of what is paining him. At that time, an ordinary doctor may help him. Ordinary saints cannot help us in every stage of life. They can guide us and help us only up to a certain standard. But the Lord Himself and those highly empowered saints who are closely connected to Him can help us in any stage of our spiritual development.`}]},{title:`The Supersubject`,paragraphs:[{class:`b46`,text:`\r`},{class:`b47`,text:` The Supersubject`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Question: </span>How can we apply proper discrimination and judgment in our search for knowledge of the Infinite?`},{class:`b43`,text:` <span class="e2">≈örƒ´la ≈örƒ´dhar MahƒÅrƒÅj:</span> Discrimination may take place in different planes, but it must have a connection with the higher plane. Judgment and discrimination should be in the right plane. Judgment and discrimination come from our side, but our progress depends on the favour of the higher side. It must have that connection, so surrender is required. Then, the Lord will approach us and take us up to that higher plane. Somehow, we have to persuade the highest authority to favour us. We must invite the higher authority to accept us. It does not depend so much on our own ability, but on our submission and surrender, our hankering for mercy‚Äînot our positive capacity but our negative character, our surrender. As a subject, I cannot make the Infinite the object of my discrimination; He is always the supersubject. I cannot make God the object of my discrimination. He is supersubjective. My position, my attitude, must invite the higher authority to come down to my level and help me, favour me. Real discrimination or knowledge should take us to self-surrender. Surrender is necessary to attract the attention of the Lord. Everything depends on His sweet will. He is an autocrat: His sweet will is everything. To attract His sweet will, to increase our negative side, our tendency for surrender, to attract His favour, this will be our real problem if we wish to progress in spiritual life. And to attract the Lord‚Äôs attention, all our qualifications must be of a negative character: we shall require surrender, submission, humility. And then we can press our position by praying, ‚ÄúO my Lord, I‚Äôm in the worst need; without Your grace I can‚Äôt stand. I am helpless. I cannot endure without Your favour.‚Äù That sort of hankering, earnestness, and necessity for His mercy will help us. In other words, we are to improve our negative character, and in that way we shall attract the positive, K·πõ·π£·πáa.`},{class:`b51`,text:` Then we shall develop proper discrimination, for at that time our subjective character will be to act only as His agent. He will inspire from within in whatever we do. Our discrimination will be utilised in carrying out His order. It will not be possible for us to have any separate interest, any original discrimination. I will carry out His order, or the order of the higher officer of the Supreme Lord. I may use my discrimination about how to make the lower arrangements in carrying out that order. But towards the Lord, who is higher than me, my attitude will always be one of submission, surrender, obedience, allegiance, unconditional slavery. The slave mentality will help us in entering that plane. If we truly feel ourselves to be low and in want, then the supply of mercy will come from the higher plane. This should always be the tenor of our thought: high and low, subjective and objective. And K·πõ·π£·πáa is not subject to any rule; He is an autocrat. These are the data we must keep in our mind always. Everything moves according to His sweet will. Our problem, then, is how to draw His attention. This will be possible only by increasing our negative tendency, by proving to Him, in a bona fide way, that I‚Äôm the most needy. At that time, we shall develop proper discrimination and knowledge; that is, our discrimination will be utilised in carrying out His order.`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Question: </span>In the <span class="e3">ƒ™≈õopani·π£ad</span>, there is a mantra:`},{class:`b60`,text:` vidyƒÅ·πÅ chƒÅvidyƒÅ·πÅ cha yas tad vedobhaya·πÅ saha<br />avidyayƒÅ m·πõtyu·πÅ tƒ´rtvƒÅ vidyayƒÅm·πõtam a≈õnute`},{class:`b50`,text:` The translation has been given by ≈örƒ´pƒÅd BhaktivedƒÅnta SwƒÅmƒ´ MahƒÅrƒÅj as follows: ‚ÄúOnly one who can learn the process of nescience and that of transcendental knowledge side by side can transcend the influence of repeated birth and death and enjoy the full blessings of immortality.‚Äù What does he mean by learning the process of nescience and that of knowledge side by side?`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">≈örƒ´la ≈örƒ´dhar MahƒÅrƒÅj:</span> One is negative and another is positive. Knowledge means to know what is false and to leave that and to recognise what is true and to accept that. Do you follow? To cultivate an understanding about falsehood and truth means to know, ‚ÄúThis is false, we must reject it; this is truth, I must accept it.‚Äù In that way, this verse may be understood. To know the bad, to culture the bad, means to know when a thing is bad and to reject it, and to culture the truth means to accept it. Not that culture means that we should culture ignorance in order to have it. What is encouraged here in this mantra is rejection of falsehood and acceptance of truth. The defects of mƒÅyƒÅ should be analysed. We must know: ‚ÄúOh, this is mƒÅyƒÅ. This is bad, this is hopeless, this is undesirable.‚Äù We must know to avoid these things. We must reject nescience, and we shall try to attain science, knowledge. We shall try to understand the bright side and aim for the light, to accept it more and more and progress towards truth.`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Question: </span>A fifteenth century German Catholic philosopher, Nicholas of Cusa*, taught the doctrine <span class="e3">Of Learned Ignorance</span>. How would that compare to Vai·π£·πáava philosophy?`},{class:`b50`,text:` * The Dictionary of Philosophy contains the following entry: ‚ÄúNicholas of Cusa (or Nicholas Cusanus) (c. 1400‚Äî64) German cardinal, whose ‚Äútheological negativa‚Äù was influential in the Renaissance. Main philosophical work: De Docta Ignorantia (Of Learned Ignorance) (1440). Using the methods of medieval logic, Cusanus examined the nature of God (Book I) and the Universe (Book II). His view of their relationship was fundamentally Neoplatonic; the Universe (maximum contractum), seen as the totality of finite things, flows out from and returns to God (maximum absolutum), whose nature is unknowable. Hence all human knowledge is simply learned ignorance.`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">≈örƒ´la ≈örƒ´dhar MahƒÅrƒÅj:</span> We may accept the bright side. Noble ignorance in our view is j√±ƒÅna-≈õ≈´nyƒÅ-bhakti, knowledge-free devotion. Noble ignorance means not to attempt to calculate in this world but to surrender: to lose our faith in calculation, in our subjective capacity of calculation, and to surrender to the Supreme. We may interpret j√±ƒÅna-≈õ≈´nyƒÅ-bhakti like that. ‚ÄúLearned ignorance‚Äù is when learning understands its own limit, when one realises, ‚ÄúI‚Äôm finite, my learning is also finite; learning cannot make me a bona fide enquirer about the Infinite.‚Äù It is better to surrender to the Infinite and let Him work within us for our best interest. Submission, surrender to the Infinite, is the highest reach of learning. Learned ignorance means to realise that we can‚Äôt know the Infinite. If he makes Himself known to us, then we can know Him, otherwise not.`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Question: </span>Nicholas of Cusa said, ‚ÄúGod is inconceivable by thought.‚Äù What do you say?`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">≈örƒ´la ≈örƒ´dhar MahƒÅrƒÅj:</span> Yes, only through devotion and by His grace may God be known. Our cultivation of knowledge won‚Äôt give us God. That is the failure of knowledge‚Äîinvestigation about God, the Infinite. Only His grace can give Him. We have to come to the side of devotion and do away with knowledge. Our attempts to make much of knowledge will be stopped when coming in connection with the Infinite. Knowledge has got its limit. And when knowledge fails, faith begins. Knowledge fails and faith develops. You must develop faith and give up hope in knowledge. A research laboratory cannot give you God. When the Russian cosmonaut Yuri Gagarin returned from space, an old lady enquired from him: ‚ÄúYou went so high; have you seen God there?‚Äù But he was an atheist. He said, ‚ÄúGod is like a horse drawing our cart. What do you think about God for? We use God in our service. With our knowledge and our research science we have forced God to serve us.‚Äù This is the proud boast of science: ‚ÄúWe have engaged God in our service; we are above God, superior to God. God is our creation.‚Äù As if He is the creation of a particular half-mad section of society.`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Question: </span>Nicholas of Cusa also taught that ‚Äúin God, opposites coincide. Opposites‚Äîsmallest and greatest‚Äîcome together in God.‚Äù What is your understanding?`},{class:`b55`,text:` <span class="e2">≈örƒ´la ≈örƒ´dhar MahƒÅrƒÅj:</span> Not only big and small, but even good and bad, even anti-parties, everything is harmonised in God. Good-bad, friend-enemy, everything is harmonised and accommodated there. And they lose their poison; all become good. He is the all-accommodating, all-harmonising, all-adjusting principle, both directly and indirectly. Thesis and antithesis find their highest synthesis in the K·πõ·π£·πáa conception of divinity.`}]},{title:`Science vs. Nescience`,paragraphs:[{class:`b46`,text:`\r`},{class:`b47`,text:` Science vs. Nescience`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Student:</span> I have finished my studies and now I am taking a break, a vacation.`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">≈örƒ´la ≈örƒ´dhar MahƒÅrƒÅj:</span> Please don‚Äôt take offense, but that you are involved in the present system of education means that you are diving deeply in the ocean of ignorance. You are making progress in the ocean of ignorance.`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Student:</span> What do you mean by that?`},{class:`b43`,text:` <span class="e2">≈örƒ´la ≈örƒ´dhar MahƒÅrƒÅj:</span> As a student of nescience, you are moving in the opposite direction from truth. You are being taught that you and other souls of your type are the subjects, the centre of the universe, and everything, all else, is an object meant only for your exploitation. You are being taught that we are exploiters and that the entire environment is for our exploitation. That is the foundation upon which the present system of education is based‚Äîa conception which is completely false.`},{class:`b44`,text:` In reality, we are not the subject, the centre of the universe. The cause is in the higher world. K·πõ·π£·πáa is the Supreme Absolute Truth. Simply by His will, everything is brought into existence. He said, ‚ÄúLet there be light,‚Äù there was light; ‚ÄúLet there be water,‚Äù there was water; ‚ÄúLet there be earth,‚Äù there was earth. His will is all-powerful. To know this is real education‚Äîsubjective learning. What we experience sprang up from the divine will. Just as if He were a magician, He can show one thing to you and something entirely different to me. The Supersubject, the universal subject, has such power. So our idea is completely the opposite of the fossilists. It is not that from time eternal the fossil is developing into this world of experience; it is just the opposite. Therefore, by conceiving of this world on the basis of fossilism, we are diving deep into an intense ocean of ignorance.`},{class:`b44`,text:` BhaktivedƒÅnta SwƒÅmƒ´ MahƒÅrƒÅj asked a few of his disciples who were research scholars to crush the fossilism of Darwin, that is, the idea that everything is coming from fossils. This idea must be demolished. It is not so.`},{class:`b44`,text:` Everything is coming from above. What we experience at present is like the outcome of hypnosis. In the process of hypnosis, the hypnotist can make us withdraw our consciousness from anything at any moment and show us another way to view reality. In the same way, Godhead is free, and whatever He wills becomes reality. Whatever He imagines becomes reality (satya-sa·πÖkalpa). He can force us to see something, and when He does so, we cannot see it in any other way.`},{class:`b44`,text:` If you can understand this principle, you can understand how everything is possible with divinity. Then you can have some faith in what is Godhead. Godhead means this: the origin of creation. And yet this creation is only an insignificant part of His divine nature. He has infinite qualities and activities. And this world in which we live is only a negligible part of the cosmic manifestation. The whole basis of everything is there in Him. It comes from up to down, and not from down to up. To the idea that everything is developing from downward to up, we must say, ‚Äúno‚Äù. A fossil is not a thing perfect or sufficient enough to create all this. To say that from a fossil intelligence is coming is a fool‚Äôs conception.`},{class:`b44`,text:` Intelligence can be traced everywhere. As much as we analyse, we find higher reason, higher intelligence. Scientists are astonished to find the intelligence that is within nature. They continue to discover higher and higher laws. And yet all those laws already existed. It is just that these fools had no awareness of it, but an extremely fine degree of order existed long before their ‚Äúdiscovery‚Äù. The wonderful laws of nature existed long before their invention. And this is evident everywhere. The physical laws of nature do not exist by dint of their creation. Do the scientists create the laws of nature? They may invent so many things, but the intelligence within nature already exists. And there is something more: power exists everywhere. Where has it come from? The scientists, intelligence to discover or invent a thing: where has it come from? Is it coming from the brain? Or is it merely a portion of dead flesh? Does intelligence come from somewhere else?`},{class:`b44`,text:` Consciousness, spirit, is all-pervading. It is present even in the trees, stones, earth, ether, and air‚Äîeverywhere. And to know the truth, we must connect with the conscious principle of the Infinite. What is the Infinite? He is almighty, omniscient, omnipotent, all-sympathetic, and all-loving. Our real aspiration must be to have a direct connection with Him, leaving aside the charm of His created substance. We should want to negotiate how we can have a connection with the Creator Himself.`},{class:`b44`,text:` And His position is not simply that of creator. This world is a creation of a lower order. But a higher creation also exists in a plane of reality which is infinitely higher than this world of experience. We should enquire whether it is possible for us to have a life in that soil. We should try to understand what are the layers of reality in that realm of consciousness, and how we can go higher and higher in that plane. We should enquire about that and find out how we can enter there. We must try to understand what is the key to the entrance into that transcendental abode. This should be the basis of our search for truth. We should enquire into how to become free from both the plane of renunciation and the plane of exploitation.`},{class:`b44`,text:` Once, K·πõ·π£·πáa went to the court of the Kauravas, the camp of Duryodhan and Dh·πõtarƒÅ·π£·π≠ra, with talk of peace. At that time, Kar·πáa, Duryodhan, and the others in the party attempted to bind Him down and put Him into prison. They thought that if K·πõ·π£·πáa were to be imprisoned, then the whole PƒÅ·πá·∏çava camp would automatically be finished. They knew that K·πõ·π£·πáa was the life and soul as well as advisor of their enemies, the PƒÅ·πá·∏çavas. They thought, ‚ÄúNow we have K·πõ·π£·πáa in our fist; we must immediately imprison Him.‚Äù They went to tie Him down, but K·πõ·π£·πáa manifested His universal form. At that time, He revealed His divine nature in such a way that the men who went to tie Him down were perplexed. They thought, ‚ÄúWhat is He!‚Äù When K·πõ·π£·πáa manifested His universal form of thousands of heads, hands, and legs, they thought, ‚ÄúThis is a gigantic thing! Here in this form we find Baladev on one side, Arjuna on another, and Bh·πõgu on another. Where are we to apply the rope? We can‚Äôt!‚Äù They were perplexed.`},{class:`b44`,text:` At that time when K·πõ·π£·πáa showed His universal form in the assembly of Kurus at HastinƒÅpur, those who were present began to chant in praise of K·πõ·π£·πáa. Bhƒ´·π£ma, Drona, NƒÅrad, and VyƒÅs were present at that time in the assembly, and they began to praise the Lord. Hearing their voices, the blind king Dh·πõtarƒÅ·π£·π≠ra was charmed, and prayed to K·πõ·π£·πáa, ‚ÄúI can‚Äôt see You; I am blind. But I hear these great persons chanting Your praises upon seeing Your wonderful form. You can do anything and everything. So for the time being, please remove my blindness; let me see Your figure and colour. Let me behold the beauty which they are praising so much. After removing my blindness, You may again make me blind.‚Äù K·πõ·π£·πáa replied, ‚ÄúIt is not necessary for your blindness to be removed. I need only command that you see Me, and you will be able to see Me.‚Äù`},{class:`b44`,text:` That is the very nature of seeing Him. Our vision of Godhead depends on His will. It is not the eye that can see Him, nor the ear that can hear Him. He is above sense experience. Only by His will may He be seen. He said, ‚ÄúYou will see Me‚Äù, and Dh·πõtarƒÅ·π£·π≠ra saw Him. Although he was blind, still he could see K·πõ·π£·πáa‚Äôs divine form. Then, what is K·πõ·π£·πáa? If a deaf man can hear Him and a blind man can see Him, then what is the nature of that divine substance which is K·πõ·π£·πáa?`},{class:`b44`,text:` Another time, when Arjuna wanted to see the universal form of K·πõ·π£·πáa, the vi≈õvar≈´p, K·πõ·π£·πáa said, ‚ÄúYes, Arjuna, see Me!‚Äù Arjuna beheld His universal form. K·πõ·π£·πáa asked him, ‚ÄúWhat do you see?‚Äù And Arjuna replied, ‚ÄúI am seeing so many wonderful divine manifestations. It is a wonder of wonders!‚Äù So, K·πõ·π£·πáa‚Äôs sweet will is the basis of everything. We are living in correlation with that absolute power. There is no stability to the environment where we live at present. All importance is on the divine will of Godhead. He is the cause of all causes. From Him this world emanates, and by Him it is maintained.`},{class:`b44`,text:` The plane of dedication, however, is far higher than the mundane realm. And we are told that by dedication, by surrender, we can have a direct connection with the centre of everything that be. So, our advice to the scientists is: ‚ÄúPhysician, cure thyself! You have come to give so many dazzling models of civilisation to the world, but first you should cure yourself fully. What you have come to distribute is all a hoax. The laws of nature, abided by everything that surrounds us, are only the sweet will of the Supreme. The laws of nature are not a rigid thing. Their basis is the sweet will of an autocrat. So, what you know‚Äîthat is nothing; it is no knowledge.‚Äù At any moment, the laws of nature may be changed by the sweet will of the Supreme Autocrat, and another set of rules may completely replace them.`},{class:`b44`,text:` The key to enact the change in our ability to experience reality is in His hands. He may easily say, ‚ÄúO Arjuna, you see this but I am that.‚Äù And Arjuna will say, ‚ÄúYes, now I see that You are that.‚Äù Everything may be seen in one way by His will, and at the next moment that vision of reality may be withdrawn by Him. So, the knowledge we can acquire through materialistic education has no value at all. With this realisation, we should enthusiastically begin the search for ≈örƒ´ K·πõ·π£·πáa, Reality the Beautiful.`},{class:`b44`,text:` K·πõ·π£·πáa is charm Himself. He is the all-charming Absolute. Our innate need is to find sweetness, beauty, rasa, ƒÅnandam, ecstasy, happiness. Everyone wants this. No one can say, ‚ÄúI do not want happiness.‚Äù No one, from the lowest atheist to the highest theist, can deny this. All will say, ‚ÄúYes, I want ecstasy; I want sweetness, happiness, peace.‚Äù This is the common demand in every conceiving unit. From the worst atheist to the greatest theist‚Äîwherever there is conception‚Äîeveryone wants peaceful existence. So, our direct necessity is with Him, ≈örƒ´ K·πõ·π£·πáa, Reality the Beautiful. He is <span class="e3">raso vai Sa·∏•</span>: ecstasy, beauty Himself. We must begin our search for that. Do not lose a moment.`},{class:`b44`,text:` Don‚Äôt waste a minute of your time in wild goose-chasing. Give up everything. <span class="e3">Sarva-dharmƒÅn parityajya</span>. Leave it behind. Give up all phases of duty that you are so busily engaged in. It is all worthless. Begin the search for that divine principle who is the creator, the master of everything, and the fulfilment of everything. Search for Him directly. Give up all your so-called obligations and duties in your relative position. They are misconceived, misunderstood, from your present defective position. Do not rely on them. Make a direct search for the prime cause from which everything is coming as a miracle. He is the fulfilment of our lives. He is the fulfilment of every atomic existence in all worlds.`},{class:`b51`,text:` We must try to march towards K·πõ·π£·πáa with His blessings upon our heads. And His agents will give us important help in that direction. Others can do nothing to help us in our inner search; we must take shelter of the saints. We must take shelter of His divine Name; it is inseparable from His existence. The sound aspect of divinity can help us a great deal on the way back to Godhead. His Holy Name is our slogan, our war cry. ‚ÄúHare K·πõ·π£·πáa!‚Äù With that slogan, we shall march on with His genuine agents. We must follow them and withdraw ourselves from all other possibilities and promises, all so-called prospects of life. They are nothing; they are of no value.`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Student:</span> There are many inequities in the world; there is a lot of unfairness, is there not? How can we account for that?`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">≈örƒ´la ≈örƒ´dhar MahƒÅrƒÅj:</span> Fair and unfair are both false. They are just like a dream. One may have a good dream or a bad dream. In either case, it is only dreaming. So, one should not waste energy to remove the unfair and to increase the fairness. Fair, unfair‚Äîit is all false, completely false. In the <span class="e3">Chaitanya-charitƒÅm·πõta</span> (Antya-lƒ´lƒÅ, 4.176), it is written:`},{class:`b60`,text:` ‚Äòdvaite‚Äô bhadrƒÅbhadra-j√±ƒÅna, saba‚Äî‚Äòmanodharma‚Äô<br />‚Äòei bhƒÅla, ei manda‚Äô,‚Äîei saba ‚Äòbhrama‚Äô`},{class:`b43`,text:` ‚ÄúIn the material world, conceptions of good and bad are all mental concoctions. Therefore, saying, ‚ÄòThis is good, this is bad,‚Äô is a mistake.‚Äù The basis of this calculation is false. Our real interest is not there. It is a false scent we are pursuing. Our fulfilment is not to be found in that direction at all.`},{class:`b51`,text:` In this material world, there is very little distinction between fairness and unfairness. Everything in this world is based on cheating. Everyone is cheating. There may be cheating of different kinds, but all are cheating. Any fairness or unfairness is an illusion. One may have a good, hopeful dream, or a disastrous dream. But both are dreams. Both are false. And fairness within this world is also false; it is a mental concoction. And what is apparently evil within the relative conception of evil is also false. Why allow ourselves to waste time in a wild goose chase? After all, these relative conceptions of fair and unfair, good and evil, are all false. Whether there is a good hope or a bad hope, all hope within the plane of misconception is based on mental concoction.`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Student:</span> But there are so many people that are starving in the world. It seems unfair.`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">≈örƒ´la ≈örƒ´dhar MahƒÅrƒÅj:</span> What to speak of starving, we are in a cave, imprisoned in a cage. That is not desirable for the soul at all. The whole world‚Äîsuns, stars, moons, oceans, mountains‚Äîall are vanishing, and again coming and going. You may be the lord of all you survey, but you are a lord in the cremation ground‚Äîa master of the cremation ground, only to deplore, ‚ÄúOh, everything is passing away. Every second everything is passing away!‚Äù In Gray‚Äôs elegy, he wrote,`},{class:`b99`,text:` The boast of heraldry, the pomp of power,<br />And all that beauty, all that wealth e‚Äôer gave,<br />Awaits alike the inevitable hour;<br />The path of glory leads but to the grave.`},{class:`b50`,text:` Everything here leads only to the grave and will be finished.`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Student:</span> I guess what I want to ask is how we can account for these inequities. I know that you are saying that there is no distinction. But why is there suffering?`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">≈örƒ´la ≈örƒ´dhar MahƒÅrƒÅj:</span> The cause is the misuse of the free will of the jƒ´va-soul. The misuse of the wealth given to you.`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Student:</span> Given by the Supreme Power?`},{class:`b55`,text:` <span class="e2">≈örƒ´la ≈örƒ´dhar MahƒÅrƒÅj:</span> By the Supreme Power. As a part of a particular potency, you have free will eternally existing within you. And by misuse of your freedom, you have selected to become a king in the mortal world, just as Satan is portrayed in Milton‚Äôs <span class="e3">Paradise Lost</span>. He wanted to reign in hell rather than to serve in heaven. The free will‚Äîthe weak, vulnerable, childlike free will‚Äîmisused. We came here to be a monarch of all we survey: to reign in hell. Inherent adaptability is an innate feature of the soul. We could have selected service in heaven. Then, our desires would have been fulfilled. But we have selected the wrong thing. We have moved in the wrong way. We wanted to be monarch. We could not select slavery in the higher realm. We selected monarchy in hell. This material world is hell, the soil of affliction. And here we face affliction in variegated ways. These are mainly classified as birth, death, infirmity, and disease. These undesirable things must be there in hell. There is the subtle difference. If you are to live in heaven, then you must live there as a surrendered soul. That is a much higher soil than this. And ultimately we see that to serve in heaven is infinitely better than to reign in hell.`}]},{title:`Spiritual Evolution`,paragraphs:[{class:`b46`,text:`\r`},{class:`b47`,text:` Spiritual Evolution`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Question: </span>I want to know more about the position of women in your tradition. Are women allowed to participate in the process of practising, praying, and showing their devotion?`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">≈örƒ´la ≈örƒ´dhar MahƒÅrƒÅj:</span> Who is a woman here may not be a woman there in that higher realm; who is a man here may not be a man there. The body is only a dress. The soul has its mental dress, and according to that, we wear this physical dress, the flesh dress. Sexual identity means the flesh and the mind. In the soul, who will represent which type of sexual identity there, is uncertain at present here in this plane. But women there in the higher realm have a higher prospect‚Äîa brighter prospect‚Äîin the spiritual world. In the spiritual realm, those souls that are female‚Äîwho have attained that formation of the soul‚Äôs realisation‚Äîhold a better and higher position than men. Here in the plane of exploitation, men hold the better position. But there, in the plane of submission and surrender, the female form of mind is more rewarding than the male‚Äôs form of mind. The negative aspect of submission is more valuable in connection with K·πõ·π£·πáa. The supreme positive is K·πõ·π£·πáa Himself. And His potency is of a negative nature. We belong to the negative-potency group, not the master group. The Lord Himself is the possessor of the potency.`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Question: </span>You refer to K·πõ·π£·πáa as Him. Does that mean that K·πõ·π£·πáa is manifested as a male figure?`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">≈örƒ´la ≈örƒ´dhar MahƒÅrƒÅj:</span> Yes, male. That is, He is the predominating moiety, predominating half of the Absolute. And others are to be predominated by Him. There are two halves of the Absolute Truth: the male half, or predominating moiety, and the female half, or predominated moiety. Positive and negative. It is similar to the concept of the proton and electron, the positive and the negative. The proton is in the centre and the electron and innumerable other subatomic particles are like so many planets moving about the centre.`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Question: </span>Do you believe in the general concept of equality?`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">≈örƒ´la ≈örƒ´dhar MahƒÅrƒÅj:</span> No two things are ever equal, in this world or in the spiritual world. No two things can ever be the same or equal. Everything has its specific characteristic. One atom is different from another atom, one electron is different from another electron. It cannot but be. Everything has its particular differentiated character.`},{class:`b50`,text:` <span class="e2">Question: </span>How can you determine whether one thing is superior to another?`},{class:`b43`,text:` <span class="e2">≈örƒ´la ≈örƒ´dhar MahƒÅrƒÅj:</span> We must judge a thing from the universal standpoint. If we are to judge a thing, we must judge its quality on the basis of its connection with the Centre. That measurement may be made according to the standard of ecstasy, rasam, just as gold is the standard for measuring the value of different monetary papers. There may be many currencies‚Äîthe pound, the ruble, the dollar, the rupee, the yen‚Äîbut the common standard for determining their value is gold. In the same way, there may be different types of calculation of one‚Äôs relationship with the Absolute on the basis of rasa, ecstasy or divine mellow. Rasa is also scientifically divided. Rasa is classified in five groups: ≈õƒÅnta, passive, dƒÅsya, servitude, sakhya, friendship, vƒÅtsalya, parenthood, and madhura, consorthood. And then again these groups are classified according to the degree or intensity of rasa in each group. Ultimately rasam, ƒÅnandam, happiness, is the common standard by which to judge which religion is higher or lower.`},{class:`b44`,text:` If we want to establish the value of a thing, we must do so by seeing how much of the common requirement it provides. For example, food is a common requirement. We cannot eat dollars in a time of famine. But one who is in possession of food is in a good position. We cannot avoid food. We may not always require dollars, but we must have food. A nation cannot stand without food. That is an indispensable necessity for everyone. In the same way, joy is the innate requirement of every soul, every living thing. And so the position of a particular religious conception may be judged according to the development of rasa that may be traced there.`},{class:`b44`,text:` There are different proposals in the religious conceptions of different peoples. There are Christians, Buddhists, Muslims, and Jews. Amongst those who follow the Vedic doctrines, there are Vai·π£·πáavas, ≈öa·πÖkarites, and so many others. But if we are to judge the value of different religious conceptions in a comparative study, we must judge their value by three things: sat, chit, and ƒÅnandam. This means we must judge how far a religion is durable, eternal; what is the quality of what is conceived, how far can we conceive of it within the plane of knowledge; and what is its development of rasa, ƒÅnandam. These three things must be there: existence, consciousness, and the food of consciousness‚Äîecstasy, happiness. We are to compare religion on the basis of these three things.`},{class:`b44`,text:` In this way we may ask, ‚ÄúWhat is the proposal of Islam, Christianity, Judaism, or Buddhism regarding existence, knowledge, and ecstasy, which is the goal of all religion.‚Äù Christianity, Islam, Vai·π£·πáavism‚Äîso many religious faiths exist. We are to compare them and then accept what is best. Different adjustments are made by each faith. The different religions of the world are not to be cast away, but there are those for whom each will be‚Äîfor the present‚Äîuseful and relevant.`},{class:`b44`,text:` But according to our understanding, K·πõ·π£·πáa is the personification of ecstasy and beauty. And so the highest religious process for achieving complete ecstasy will be the search for ≈örƒ´ K·πõ·π£·πáa, Reality the Beautiful. But how should we search? Through devotion. And what is that? Dedication. What is dedication? Surrender, self-sacrifice‚Äîdie to live. And what is living? To live in love, K·πõ·π£·πáa-prema, love divine. The whole picture can be described in two words, K·πõ·π£·πáa-prema. The search for ≈örƒ´ K·πõ·π£·πáa is sambandha-j√±ƒÅn or understanding our relationship with the object of our fulfilment. Then what is that search, and what is the end of the search? In a few words, in a nutshell, we have described all these things on the title page of our book, <span class="e3">The Search for ≈örƒ´ K·πõ·π£·πáa, Reality the Beautiful</span>.`},{class:`b44`,text:` And this may be understood through the help of ≈örƒ´ Guru and his grace. It may be explained that the necessity of Guru is there; it is universal. To err is human, but not to err is also an inner tendency. ≈örƒ´ Gurudev comes to give us relief from our internal trouble. In this way the conception of Guru may be developed. The necessity for Guru can be inferred from the universal basis of nature which is present around us.`},{class:`b44`,text:` And from there it will gradually move to the Absolute. Ultimately, the conception of Guru will come to K·πõ·π£·πáa. In this highest sense, K·πõ·π£·πáa is Guru. Who can remove all our doubts and satisfy all our enquiries? It is K·πõ·π£·πáa alone. Gradually, our faith will develop and take us to the one who can clear all our doubts. We may have doubts upon doubts. One doubt may go and thousands of doubts may come, but Guru is one who can clear all our doubts‚Äî<span class="e3">bhidyate h·πõdaya-granthi≈õ chhidyante sarva-sa·πÅ≈õayƒÅ·∏•</span> (<span class="e3">SB:</span> 1.2.21)‚Äîwho can do away with all the suspicions in our mind; it is he who is full. In this way we must progress. The birth of our faith may be in intellectualism, but its goal is transcendental. The birth of our search and its destination will come to meet together. The birth of faith is from the potency of K·πõ·π£·πáa, and after moving through the whole of the Infinite, it will come again to the potency where we will take our eternal position.`},{class:`b44`,text:` K·πõ·π£·πáa consciousness means the Infinite in the finite: the affectionate connection of the finite with the Infinite helps him to live in infinity. The finite backed by the Infinite may become infinitely resourceful. Our Guru MahƒÅrƒÅj gave the example that if a poor girl marries a prince, although she may have nothing, by her affectionate relationship with the prince, she turns into a princess. So, one who has nothing, only a friendly relationship, gets command over everything. This is the nature of K·πõ·π£·πáa consciousness.`},{class:`b44`,text:` One‚Äôs resources may increase in that way. Intrinsically, a jƒ´va-soul is insignificant. It is an infinitesimal point of a point of a point, but by coming in affectionate connection with the Absolute, he gets the facility of all the advantages of a life with the Absolute. Then, he or she is in possession of the Whole. We cannot really ascertain anyone‚Äôs potency or power without considering his relationship with others. Israel is a small country. Russia could conquer it in five minutes, but‚ÄîAmerica is there. So, relationships, connections, and friends must be taken into consideration when understanding the power of a thing.`},{class:`b52`,text:` There is a fable that shows how a small bird was able to disturb and even control the whole ocean. Once, a small bird laid her eggs by the ocean‚Äôs shore, but the ocean carried the eggs away. When the ocean stole her eggs, the bird became angry and asked for them back, but the ocean would not return them. The bird went to her master, that bird went to his master, and in this way they finally went to Garu·∏ça, the master of all birds. Garu·∏ça is the servant bird carrier of Vi·π£·πáu. And Garu·∏ça came to the aid of that small bird. He threatened the ocean, ‚ÄúIf you don‚Äôt return this little bird‚Äôs eggs immediately, I shall drink you to the last drop.‚Äù The ocean had to submit. In this way the unlimited ocean was conquered by a small bird. As the moral of this story, Pa·πá·∏çit Vi·π£·πáu ≈öarma gives this conclusion: ‚ÄúWhen examining a person, we must consider his friends and the friends of his friends. Without such considerations, we should not try to estimate the power of a particular thing.‚Äù Because of friendly association, the ocean was conquered. In the same way, by making friendship with the Infinite, one can conquer the Infinite.`}]},{title:`Pure Devotion`,paragraphs:[{class:`b46`,text:`\r`},{class:`b47`,text:` Pure Devotion`},{class:`b50`,text:` Once, Bhakti Vinod ·π¨hƒÅkur had a dream in which he was wandering in the sky chanting the Holy Name. He came upon the court of YamarƒÅj, where YamarƒÅj himself was sitting with BrahmƒÅ, NƒÅrad, and others discussing a point from a verse in <span class="e3">Bhagavad-gƒ´tƒÅ</span> (9.30):`},{class:`b60`,text:` api chet sudurƒÅcƒÅro bhajate mƒÅm ananya-bhƒÅk<br />sƒÅdhur eva sa mantavya·∏• samyag vyavasito hi sa·∏•`},{class:`b43`,text:` The generally accepted meaning of this verse is: ‚ÄúEven if one commits the most abominable action, if he is an ananya-bhƒÅk devotee who worships Me alone in devotional service which is free from karma and j√±ƒÅn, he is to be considered saintly because his endeavors are completely on My behalf and his determination is fixed.‚Äù`},{class:`b44`,text:` Here, K·πõ·π£·πáa says, ‚ÄúWhatever he has done, if he is exclusively given to Myself, he should be considered as My devotee. <span class="e3">Samyag vyavasito hi sa·∏•</span>. And whatever he is doing is cent per cent right.‚Äù But then the next passage says, ‚Äú<span class="e3">K·π£ipra·πÅ bhavati dharmƒÅtmƒÅ</span>: very soon he will be a man of righteousness; he will become dharmƒÅtmƒÅ‚Äîdutiful.‚Äù`},{class:`b51`,text:` As YamarƒÅj, BrahmƒÅ, and NƒÅrad discussed this point, a question came up. K·πõ·π£·πáa says, ‚Äú<span class="e3">Bhajate MƒÅm ananya-bhƒÅk</span>: one who is My exclusive devotee.‚Äù The question arises, ‚ÄúWhat is exclusive devotion or ananya-bhajan?‚Äù K·πõ·π£·πáa says, ‚ÄúGive up all other religious conceptions and surrender to Me alone: <span class="e3">sarva-dharmƒÅn parityajya MƒÅm eka·πÅ ≈õara·πáa·πÅ vraja</span>.‚Äù That is exclusive devotion. But if one is practising exclusive devotion, then he is already dharmƒÅtmƒÅ; he is already righteous. How is it then that in the very next verse, K·πõ·π£·πáa says, ‚ÄúSoon he becomes dharmƒÅtmƒÅ‚Äù? How are we to adjust this? K·πõ·π£·πáa says:`},{class:`b60`,text:` k·π£ipra·πÅ bhavati dharmƒÅtmƒÅ ≈õa≈õvach-chhƒÅnti·πÅ nigachchhati<br />kaunteya pratijƒÅnƒ´hi na me bhakta·∏• pra·πáa≈õyati`},{class:`b43`,text:` ‚ÄúHe soon becomes righteous (dharmƒÅtmƒÅ) and attains lasting peace. O son of Kuntƒ´, declare it boldly that My devotee never perishes.‚Äù This is the general meaning of this verse. K·πõ·π£·πáa tells Arjuna, ‚ÄúHe soon becomes dharmƒÅtmƒÅ. My devotee is never ruined. Go and declare this to the public.‚Äù K·πõ·π£·πáa says that after the devotee became ananya-bhƒÅk‚Äîthat is, he gave up all sorts of duties and surrendered to K·πõ·π£·πáa‚Äîthen again he will be a dutiful man.`},{class:`b44`,text:` As BrahmƒÅ, NƒÅrad, and YamarƒÅj discussed this point, they saw Bhakti Vinod ·π¨hƒÅkur walking in the sky and taking the Holy Name. Then one of them suggested, ‚ÄúThere is a pure devotee. He should be able to give the real meaning.‚Äù Then Bhakti Vinod ·π¨hƒÅkur was invited in their midst and was asked, ‚ÄúHow shall we adjust these points? K·πõ·π£·πáa has said that this person is an exclusive devotee, that he has renounced all sorts of duties and surrendered to K·πõ·π£·πáa. And yet, in no time it will be seen that he is very dutiful. How can we understand this?‚Äù`},{class:`b44`,text:` Bhakti Vinod ·π¨hƒÅkur explained that ‚Äúhe quickly becomes righteous‚Äù refers not to the exclusive devotee, but to one who considers the exclusive devotee pure in all circumstances. ‚ÄúEven if he performs some abominable acts, he is really a sƒÅdhu, a saint.‚Äù One who can think of an exclusive devotee in that way will soon become dharmƒÅtmƒÅ. This was Bhakti Vinod ·π¨hƒÅkur‚Äôs explanation.`},{class:`b44`,text:` In this way, in my commentary on <span class="e3">Bhagavad-gƒ´tƒÅ</span>, I have followed Bhakti Vinod ·π¨hƒÅkur‚Äôs explanation. I also saw that it was redundant to say that an ananya-bhƒÅk devotee becomes dharmƒÅtmƒÅ. K·πõ·π£·πáa says that an exclusive devotee should be thought of as a sƒÅdhu, an honest man. One who says that an exclusive devotee, a surrendered soul to K·πõ·π£·πáa, should be thought of as pure whatever be his external practices‚Äîthe man who is making this remark‚Äîhe becomes righteous. This is the proper conclusion. What he says is cent per cent truth. And the next thing K·πõ·π£·πáa says is that he who can remark in such a way will be purified very soon.`},{class:`b44`,text:` K·πõ·π£·πáa says that by such appreciation of the exclusive devotee, a person will soon come to his eternal duty and attain eternal peace. ‚ÄúSo I ask you, O son of Kuntƒ´, Arjuna, to go and promise in public that My exclusive devotee will never be lost (<span class="e3">Kaunteya pratijƒÅnƒ´hi na Me bhakta·∏• pra·πáa≈õyati</span>).‚Äù Then you will get the benefit of the man whose remark improves his life.`},{class:`b44`,text:` Otherwise, why should K·πõ·π£·πáa tell Arjuna, ‚ÄúMake a public announcement that My devotee is never ruined.‚Äù What effect will there be for Arjuna? But one who declares: ‚ÄúAn exclusive devotee of K·πõ·π£·πáa is saintly no matter what he does‚Äù, soon becomes righteous. If Arjuna declares this, he will become dharmƒÅtmƒÅ. He will get the benefit. So, K·πõ·π£·πáa tells him, ‚ÄúYou make this remark. Take a bold step; take a risk and make this remark. Then you will also get that benefit I have described.‚Äù`},{class:`b44`,text:` Of course, Arjuna is a pƒÅr·π£ad, an eternal associate of K·πõ·π£·πáa, but using him as an example, K·πõ·π£·πáa tells him, ‚ÄúYou do it.‚Äù Arjuna has taken the position of an enquirer independent of his pƒÅr·π£ad character.`},{class:`b44`,text:` When I was publishing my commentary on <span class="e3">Bhagavad-gƒ´tƒÅ</span>, a godbrother once told me, ‚ÄúIf you give such an explanation, then in the name of ananya-bhƒÅk-bhakti, exclusive devotion, less advanced devotees will take advantage of this. What you are revealing here is a very hidden meaning. It is not meant for the public. It is a confidential point. <span class="e3">Api chet sudurƒÅchƒÅro bhajate MƒÅm ananya-bhƒÅk, sƒÅdhur eva</span>: ‚ÄòHe may be the worst debauchee in his outer life. But if he is ananya-bhƒÅk, a surrendered soul, he should be considered a really honest man.‚Äô If you explain things according to your interpretation, everyone will say, ‚ÄòOh, I am an ananya-bhƒÅk devotee‚Äô, and they will go on with their debauchery. So please, don‚Äôt express this interpretation of yours so explicitly.‚Äù`},{class:`b44`,text:` But I published my commentary over this objection because the principle underlying this verse is an important one. One who has surrendered to K·πõ·π£·πáa is accepted as His own. And just as K·πõ·π£·πáa has rights over everything and is never a trespasser, so His own man should never be considered a trespasser at any time. This is confirmed elsewhere in the <span class="e3">≈örƒ´mad BhƒÅgavatam</span>, ‚Äú<span class="e3">ƒÄtmƒÅ bh≈´yƒÅya cha kalpate:</span> My devotee belongs to Me.‚Äù So, one who works by inspiration from K·πõ·π£·πáa should never be considered a trespasser. He can enjoy anything on K·πõ·π£·πáa‚Äôs behalf if he is really a surrendered soul. He should be considered as K·πõ·π£·πáa‚Äôs. He has free access to everything that belongs to K·πõ·π£·πáa. But some objected, saying, ‚ÄúDon‚Äôt be so broad in your interpretation. If you do so, then the people at large will do abominable things in the name of pure devotion. They will say, ‚ÄòOh, I am Vai·π£·πáava. I am achyuta-gotra, I am one of K·πõ·π£·πáa‚Äôs own men. What is His property is mine. I can enjoy everything.‚Äô‚Äù`},{class:`b44`,text:` Then of course the question comes, ‚ÄúHow do we recognise ananya-bhƒÅk-bhakti, exclusive devotion?‚Äù The real trouble is here. Merely professing that I am a pure devotee won‚Äôt do. Rather, a real devotee will think, ‚ÄúI am not a real devotee.‚Äù That will be his understanding, his inner feeling. Exclusive devotion is not a small thing. A genuine devotee thinks, ‚ÄúI can‚Äôt be an ananya-bhƒÅk-bhakta. I have not attained that stage. It is very difficult. Rather, I am going away from that.‚Äù That will be the general tenor of his attitude.`},{class:`b44`,text:` What to speak of lesser devotees, ≈örƒ´matƒ´ RƒÅdhƒÅrƒÅ·πáƒ´ Herself says, ‚ÄúPeople associate me with K·πõ·π£·πáa. They say that I have an illicit connection with K·πõ·π£·πáa. But what they say is all false. My grief is that I could not give My entire heart to K·πõ·π£·πáa. I cannot say that I am completely His. My internal trouble is that I could not become wholly His, and they falsely think that I am. I have no objection to becoming fully His, even to having an illicit connection with Him, but that I can‚Äôt become so. This is My great fault.‚Äù That will be the general attitude of a real ananya-bhƒÅk-bhakta.`},{class:`b44`,text:` Just the opposite tendency will come. The fact is that one who has accepted K·πõ·π£·πáa exclusively has no taste for any other thing, so really he is not durƒÅchƒÅra; he is not capable of acting in an abominable way. Internally, he is always connected with K·πõ·π£·πáa. In external life, he is indifferent. So, what he is doing is not done by him. One who acts in that plane of reality may destroy thousands of universes but does not do anything (<span class="e3">hatvƒÅpi sa imƒÅÃên lokƒÅn na hanti na nibadhyate</span>). He is acting in the transcendental plane, the nirgu·πáa plane. He is not to be seen in terms of what is good or bad in the calculation of this world. He is absent here.`},{class:`b44`,text:` What is in connection with K·πõ·π£·πáa is all good; it is nirgu·πáa, transcendental, without material qualities. In this world, truth is a relative thing. ‚ÄúThis is true, this is not true, this is mine, this is yours‚Äù‚Äîwhat value do these things have? If a devotee steals a flower for K·πõ·π£·πáa, you may say, ‚ÄúOh, why are you stealing my flower?‚Äù But what is the guarantee that the flower belongs to you? These are different stages of bogus conceptions of reality. A man who has possession of some land declares himself the owner. Then a big landowner comes and says, ‚ÄúYou are not the owner. I have real possession of this land. I have allowed you only to use it.‚Äù But beyond the landowner a king may come and say, ‚ÄúOh no, this is my land. Your ownership is only relative. I am the ruler of this land. It belongs to me.‚Äù In this way, one relative conception of truth fights with another. And morality stands only on this conception: ‚ÄúThis is mine, this is yours.‚Äù`},{class:`b51`,text:` All these conceptions of ownership are false. All these transactions of morality are false, because they are not in connection with the Supreme Truth. So, the devotee‚Äôs apparent misbehaviour is quite the contrary in reality.`},{class:`b59`,text:` ‚Äòdvaite‚Äô bhadrƒÅbhadra-j√±ƒÅna, saba‚Äî‚Äòmanodharma‚Äô<br />‚Äòei bhƒÅla, ei manda‚Äô,‚Äîei saba ‚Äòbhrama‚Äô`},{class:`b54`,text:` (≈örƒ´ Chaitanya-charitƒÅm·πõta: Antya-lƒ´lƒÅ, 4.176)`},{class:`b43`,text:` ‚ÄúIn the material world, conceptions of good and bad or right and wrong are all mental concoctions. Therefore, saying, ‚ÄòThis is good and this is bad‚Äô is all a mistake.‚Äù So, in the deepest plane of reality, the deepest wave of K·πõ·π£·πáa consciousness is moving, and there so many jƒ´va-souls are dancing. And that dance is the absolute dance wherein everything surrenders to K·πõ·π£·πáa in the mood of V·πõndƒÅvan: <span class="e3">sarva-dharmƒÅn parityajya MƒÅm eka·πÅ</span>. Everything belongs to K·πõ·π£·πáa, and for His satisfaction anything and everything can be done. This is the only principle followed by the exclusive devotees without caring for the many relative demands and strictures of this false plane. That is nirgu·πáa, transcendental. In that plane, the calculation of false ownership can‚Äôt be applied. All claims of ownership have no value in K·πõ·π£·πáa consciousness.`},{class:`b44`,text:` There is another point that may also be considered in this verse. Once, ParƒÅ≈õar Muni was crossing a river. A young lady was piloting the boat. As the boat reached the middle of the river, ParƒÅ≈õar suddenly became charmed by that young lady. He proposed that they unite, and they did. As a result of their union, VedavyƒÅs was born. ParƒÅ≈õar was already a man of higher sense control. But the time had come for the birth of VyƒÅs, and this created a necessity at a particular stage in him. Suddenly, he was overwhelmed by lust and united with that lady. From their union came VyƒÅsadev, the compiler of all the Vedic scriptures. So, this was the determination of the universal will. ParƒÅ≈õar is not to be accused or condemned. He is not a party to that. He is an instrument of the universal will. We should not consider this an event of lustfulness and criticise ParƒÅ≈õar for his immoral action. He was inspired by some inner will and overpowered by the divine force of the nirgu·πáa will of K·πõ·π£·πáa. Only then did these things take place.`},{class:`b44`,text:` Therefore, K·πõ·π£·πáa says in the <span class="e3">Bhagavad-gƒ´tƒÅ</span> that it is not the action, but the background of the action that is to be considered. That is to be examined, not the action alone. The motive underlying the action, not the karma, but the purpose‚Äîthat is the culprit. Draupadƒ´ had five husbands, but not of her own accord. She had to accept the trouble as her duty; she did not do so for the sake of pleasure. So, Draupadƒ´ should not be held responsible for this; it cannot be said that she is unchaste. She cannot be held responsible for having many husbands. It is said in the ≈õƒÅstra that Draupadƒ´ or Kuntƒ´ may seem to be unchaste, but if you chant their names, you will be purified. So, the internal meaning of an act, its purpose, should be considered‚Äînot the external action.`},{class:`b51`,text:` The higher principle is served not by following ordinary law, but by following some higher law. In that case, the ordinary law is surpassed. One might think a devotee a culprit from the consideration of ordinary law, but from the consideration of a higher law, K·πõ·π£·πáa has said that if you can appreciate their law-breaking, you will be uplifted.`},{class:`b59`,text:` ƒÅj√±ƒÅyaiva·πÅ gu·πáƒÅn do·π£ƒÅn mayƒÅdi·π£·π≠ƒÅn api svakƒÅn<br />dharmƒÅn santyajya ya·∏• sarvƒÅn mƒÅ·πÅ bhajeta sa tu sattama·∏•`},{class:`b54`,text:` (≈örƒ´mad BhƒÅgavatam: 11.11.32)`},{class:`b43`,text:` K·πõ·π£·πáa says, ‚ÄúThe rules of the scriptures come from My direction, My order. But if anyone breaks those rules to satisfy Me, he should be considered a better devotee.‚Äù Sometimes it may be necessary to show even greater loyalty to the king by crossing over the laws of the king. So here, God is above law. When we consider the nature of divinity, we must conclude that K·πõ·π£·πáa is above law. Law is for us. But law may not be applied in His case. He is absolute. When one has actually come in connection with the Absolute, he cannot but ignore the laws meant for ordinary people. Of course, this means in a higher sense. It is not that devotees shall not observe the ordinary laws governing society in the name of devotion. But in the higher sense we have to understand that K·πõ·π£·πáa is all-in-all. He is the creator of law, and He Himself sometimes breaks the law and especially likes those who are ready to break the law for Him. They are His favourite who are ready to take risks for His service, who are ready to bear the consequence of breaking the law.`},{class:`b51`,text:` This is the nature of K·πõ·π£·πáa‚Äôs entire Vraja-lƒ´lƒÅ. In V·πõndƒÅvan, all considerations of individual and local interest are sacrificed. In V·πõndƒÅvan, there is the highest self-sacrifice, to the degree that everyone‚Äôs own particular interest or consideration is sacrificed into fire. Only when you come to that stage of self-sacrifice can you take birth in V·πõndƒÅvan, not before. This is the conclusion of <span class="e3">Bhagavad-gƒ´tƒÅ</span>:`},{class:`b60`,text:` sarva-dharmƒÅn parityajya mƒÅm eka·πÅ ≈õara·πáa·πÅ vraja<br />aha·πÅ tvƒÅ·πÅ sarva-pƒÅpebhyo mok·π£ayi·π£yƒÅmi mƒÅ ≈õucha·∏•`},{class:`b55`,text:` K·πõ·π£·πáa says, ‚ÄúYou must risk all your prospects, you must risk everything, with no prospects other than Myself. I cannot tolerate the presence of any second entity in your heart. I cannot tolerate that you will come to Me with some consideration. My relation with you must be unconditional. I can‚Äôt tolerate any other interest in the heart of My devotee. Only one interest, and that is Me. Sacrifice all your so-called interests, all your prospects, everything. Then you can come to meet Me in V·πõndƒÅvan.‚Äù`}]},{title:`The Subjective Bhagavad-gƒ´tƒÅ`,paragraphs:[{class:`b46`,text:`\r`},{class:`b47`,text:` The Subjective Bhagavad-gƒ´tƒÅ`},{class:`b43`,text:` Both Vi≈õvanƒÅth Chakravartƒ´ ·π¨hƒÅkur and Baladev VidyƒÅbh≈´·π£a·πá have commented on <span class="e3">Bhagavad-gƒ´tƒÅ</span>, and Jƒ´va GoswƒÅmƒ´ has also given his explanation of different verses. Bhakti Vinod ·π¨hƒÅkur has given his own explanation, and he has included both Baladev‚Äôs and Vi≈õvanƒÅth Chakravartƒ´‚Äôs commentaries in his Bengali translation on <span class="e3">Bhagavad-gƒ´tƒÅ</span>. ≈örƒ´dhar SwƒÅmƒ´‚Äôs commentary was the original one, and ≈örƒ´ Chaitanya MahƒÅprabhu had great appreciation for his commentary on <span class="e3">≈örƒ´mad BhƒÅgavatam</span> and <span class="e3">Bhagavad-gƒ´tƒÅ</span>.`},{class:`b44`,text:` I have attempted to shed some new light on some verses in <span class="e3">Bhagavad-gƒ´tƒÅ</span>. On the basis of what the previous commentators have said, I have shown the further development of madhura-rasa in <span class="e3">Bhagavad-gƒ´tƒÅ</span>, and even the paramour relation of parakƒ´ya-rasa. When I discussed my explanation with BhaktivedƒÅnta SwƒÅmƒ´ MahƒÅrƒÅj, I asked him, ‚ÄúIn this place in <span class="e3">Bhagavad-gƒ´tƒÅ</span>, I have given my interpretation to include madhura-rasa. What do you think?‚Äù He told me, ‚ÄúWhat more can be said? Your interpretation is perfectly correct.‚Äù`},{class:`b44`,text:` Still, it was a new conception I had given there. I found parakƒ´ya, the paramour devotion of the gopƒ´s for K·πõ·π£·πáa, represented in the verse: <span class="e3">te·π£ƒÅm satata yuktƒÅnƒÅ·πÅ ‚Ä¶ yena MƒÅm upayƒÅnti te</span>. Just as <span class="e3">≈örƒ´mad BhƒÅgavatam</span> has four essential verses, there are four essential verses in <span class="e3">Bhagavad-gƒ´tƒÅ</span> which contain the very gist, the very substance of the whole ontological conception of <span class="e3">Bhagavad-gƒ´tƒÅ</span>.`},{class:`b51`,text:` In <span class="e3">Bhagavad-gƒ´tƒÅ</span> (10.8), the first of the four nutshell verses is as follows:`},{class:`b60`,text:` aha·πÅ sarvasya prabhavo matta·∏• sarva·πÅ pravartate<br />iti matvƒÅ bhajante mƒÅ·πÅ budhƒÅ bhƒÅva-samanvitƒÅ·∏•`},{class:`b43`,text:` ‚ÄúI am the origin of everything. Everything emanates from Me (including all conceptions of the Absolute Truth and even My own worship). The wise who know this fully worship Me with bhƒÅva, deep devotional ecstasy.‚Äù`},{class:`b44`,text:` Here, K·πõ·π£·πáa says, ‚Äú<span class="e3">Aha·πÅ sarvasya prabhavo Matta·∏• sarva·πÅ pravartate</span>: everything emanates from Me, including all conceptions of the Absolute Truth.‚Äù In <span class="e3">BhƒÅgavatam</span>, the three main conceptions of the Absolute are given: Brahma, ParamƒÅtmƒÅ, and BhagavƒÅn. Brahma means the all-comprehensive aspect of the Absolute. ParamƒÅtmƒÅ means the all-permeating aspect of the Absolute, and BhagavƒÅn means the personal conception of the Absolute.`},{class:`b44`,text:` In his <span class="e3">Bhakti-sandarbha</span>, Jƒ´va GoswƒÅmƒ´ has given the real meaning of BhagavƒÅn, the Personality of Godhead. The general meaning of BhagavƒÅn is ‚Äúone who commands all sorts of potencies.‚Äù All sorts of potencies are controlled by Him personally. That is the conception of BhagavƒÅn found in NƒÅrƒÅya·πá of Vaiku·πá·π≠ha. But Jƒ´va GoswƒÅmƒ´ has given a particularly fine interpretation of BhagavƒÅn. He says that BhagavƒÅn means <span class="e3">bhajanƒ´ya-sarva-sad-gu·πáa-vi≈õi·π£·π≠a</span>: the nature of BhagavƒÅn is such that whatever comes in contact with Him feels a natural serving tendency towards His charming personality. He is endowed with such qualities that everyone is drawn to worship Him, to love Him. He attracts the love of everyone. Everyone wants to serve Him‚Äîthis is BhagavƒÅn. He is endowed with qualities that attract everyone to serve Him.`},{class:`b44`,text:` I have included this special interpretation of Jƒ´va GoswƒÅmƒ´ in my commentary on the above <span class="e3">Bhagavad-gƒ´tƒÅ</span> verse. In the <span class="e3">≈örƒ´mad BhƒÅgavatam</span>, three phases of the Absolute Truth have been described (all-comprehensive Brahma, all-pervading ParamƒÅtmƒÅ, and the all-attractive, absolute person, BhagavƒÅn). I have explained in my commentary that K·πõ·π£·πáa‚Äôs statement here (<span class="e3">Aha·πÅ sarvasya prabhavo</span>) means: ‚ÄúI am Svayam BhagavƒÅn, the Original Personality of Godhead. I am at the root of all these three conceptions of the Absolute. And I am the origin not only of Brahma, the all-comprehensive Absolute, and ParamƒÅtmƒÅ, the all-permeating Absolute, but also of NƒÅrƒÅya·πá, the master of all potencies who commands the respect of everyone. I am the origin of all of them: I am Svayam BhagavƒÅn.‚Äù`},{class:`b44`,text:` In this way, I have interpreted the meaning of <span class="e3">Aha·πÅ sarvasya prabhavo</span>. And in the next line, when K·πõ·π£·πáa says <span class="e3">Matta·∏• sarva·πÅ pravartate</span>, here we must concentrate more finely. K·πõ·π£·πáa says, ‚Äú<span class="e3">Sarva·πÅ pravartate</span>: everything comes from Me.‚Äù With this, K·πõ·π£·πáa is saying, ‚ÄúEven worship of Me comes from Me. I reveal it first. I Myself worship Myself. I do this as Guru, as My finer potency. This potency is nothing but Myself. And My finest potency is RƒÅdhƒÅrƒÅ·πáƒ´. Through My potency, I worship Myself. Every movement begins from Me; even My own worship. My own service is begun by Me, in My role as Guru. I reveal that to the public so that you will properly worship Me. For this reason, Guru is called BhagavƒÅn, for he is nondifferent from Me (<span class="e3">ƒÄchƒÅrya·πÅ MƒÅ·πÅ vijƒÅnƒ´yƒÅn</span>).‚Äù`},{class:`b44`,text:` The finest potency of BhagavƒÅn is RƒÅdhƒÅrƒÅ·πáƒ´. So, Guru in the highest sense, as well as service in the highest sense, is represented in ≈örƒ´matƒ´ RƒÅdhƒÅrƒÅ·πáƒ´. Next, K·πõ·π£·πáa says, ‚ÄúThose who know this will worship Me (<span class="e3">iti matvƒÅ bhajante MƒÅ·πÅ</span>).‚Äù Those who understand this conception, that RƒÅdhƒÅrƒÅ·πáƒ´ serves Him in the highest way, will serve K·πõ·π£·πáa in subjugation to Her. That is RƒÅdhƒÅ-dƒÅsyam, the divine service of ≈örƒ´ RƒÅdhƒÅ. And it is with this understanding that a worshiper will come to worship K·πõ·π£·πáa.`},{class:`b44`,text:` In my interpretation, I have taken it that this is K·πõ·π£·πáa‚Äôs intent when He says, ‚Äú<span class="e3">Iti matvƒÅ bhajante MƒÅ·πÅ</span>: knowing this, they worship Me.‚Äù He means, ‚ÄúThose who know that My worship comes from Me, and that My finest potency worships Me best, will worship Me under the direction of My finest potency.‚Äù Here we find the importance of RƒÅdhƒÅ-dƒÅsyam, the service of ≈örƒ´ RƒÅdhƒÅ, the highest goal of the followers of R≈´pa GoswƒÅmƒ´, the R≈´pƒÅnuga‚ÄìGau·∏çƒ´ya sampradƒÅya. Here, K·πõ·π£·πáa is saying, ‚ÄúKnowing that it is My finest potency that worships Me best, one will worship Me under the direction of My first-class worshiper (≈örƒ´ RƒÅdhƒÅ). With this idea, one will always worship Me under the guidance of My finest ≈õakti, ≈örƒ´matƒ´ RƒÅdhƒÅrƒÅ·πáƒ´, or Her representation, ≈örƒ´ Gurudev. In this way, they will always worship Me under their direction, and never as a direct worshiper.‚Äù This is the meaning of <span class="e3">iti matvƒÅ bhajante MƒÅ·πÅ</span>.`},{class:`b51`,text:` Then, K·πõ·π£·πáa says <span class="e3">budhƒÅ bhƒÅva-samanvitƒÅ·∏•</span>. Here, <span class="e3">budhƒÅ</span> means those of fine theistic intellect (sumedhasa·∏•). In <span class="e3">BhƒÅgavatam</span>, it is said that those of fine theistic intellect will be able to appreciate this (<span class="e3">yajanti hi sumedhasa·∏•</span>). Fine theistic intelligence is the outcome of good fortune which comes from above (suk·πõti); it is not self-acquired. That fine intellectual inner direction and guidance can only come from the nirgu·πáa or transcendental plane. <span class="e3">BudhƒÅ</span> here means ‚Äúone who has a direct connection with the nirgu·πáa or transcendental plane.‚Äù His intelligence doesn‚Äôt come from this mƒÅyic quarter; rather, it springs from the spiritual platform. Only such a person can appreciate these subtle points. This is said in <span class="e3">BhƒÅgavatam</span>:`},{class:`b60`,text:` k·πõ·π£·πáa-var·πáa·πÅ tvi·π£ƒÅk·πõ·π£·πáa·πÅ sƒÅ·πÖgopƒÅ·πÖgƒÅstra-pƒÅr·π£adam<br />yaj√±ai·∏• sa·πÖkƒ´rtana-prƒÅyair yajanti hi sumedhasa·∏•`},{class:`b43`,text:` ‚ÄúThose who are of fine theistic intellect (sumedhasa·∏•) will worship ≈örƒ´ Chaitanya MahƒÅprabhu in sa·πÖkƒ´rtan, not others.‚Äù`},{class:`b44`,text:` So, this verse from <span class="e3">Bhagavad-gƒ´tƒÅ</span> means, ‚ÄúOne whose devotion is the product of the nirgu·πáa wave, whose faith is not collected from this world of misunderstanding, shall worship me through RƒÅdhƒÅ-dƒÅsyam.‚Äù Here <span class="e3">bhƒÅva-samanvita·∏•</span> means <span class="e3">rƒÅga-samanvita·∏•</span>‚Äîthat is, they worship K·πõ·π£·πáa with anurƒÅga, love. Their affinity for K·πõ·π£·πáa, their devotion to Him, is not governed by rules; it does not spring from strictly following the scriptural rules, but from bhƒÅva, inner inspiration. This worship is called rƒÅga-mƒÅrg, the path of spontaneous attraction.`},{class:`b44`,text:` Scriptural rules involve calculations of loss and gain. But worship which is <span class="e3">bhƒÅva-samanvita·∏•</span> is not drawn from any consideration of loss and gain; it flows naturally through love and attraction for K·πõ·π£·πáa. It is j√±ƒÅna-≈õ≈´nyƒÅ-bhakti, free from calculation, free from profit and loss: <span class="e3">j√±ƒÅna-karmƒÅdy-anƒÅv·πõtam</span>.`},{class:`b51`,text:` The next of the four essential verses which contain the entire message of <span class="e3">Bhagavad-gƒ´tƒÅ</span> is as follows (10.9):`},{class:`b60`,text:` mach-chittƒÅ mad-gata-prƒÅ·πáƒÅ bodhayanta·∏• parasparam<br />kathayanta≈õ cha mƒÅ·πÅ nitya·πÅ tu·π£yanti cha ramanti cha`},{class:`b43`,text:` ‚ÄúThe hearts and minds of My devotees are always filled with Me, and they are forever experiencing pleasure and ecstasy in talking about Me.‚Äù`},{class:`b44`,text:` Here, K·πõ·π£·πáa says, ‚ÄúI am in their hearts, in their thinking (<span class="e3">Mach-chittƒÅ Mad-gata-prƒÅ·πáƒÅ</span>). Their whole life, their entire energy, is spent for Me, utilised for Me. Their prƒÅ·πáƒÅ-≈õakti, their life-energy, is also fully devoted for My cause. Internally, they are always thinking about Me and devoting their whole energy for Me, and externally they talk about Me to enhance their mutual understanding (<span class="e3">bodhayanta·∏• parasparam</span>). They love to talk about Me with one another; they talk about nothing else. In private life, and in public life also, they love to talk about Me, and nothing else. I am the only subject of their discussions (<span class="e3">kathayanta≈õ cha MƒÅ·πÅ nitya·πÅ</span>). Whatever they do, wherever they are‚Äîeverywhere‚ÄîI am the subject of their talk.‚Äù`},{class:`b44`,text:` And next K·πõ·π£·πáa says, ‚ÄúIn this they find great satisfaction (<span class="e3">tu·π£yanti cha ramanti cha</span>).‚Äù The internal meaning of <span class="e3">tu·π£yanti cha ramanti cha</span> is as follows. Here two levels of devotees are described. Up to vƒÅtsalya-rasa, or the parental mellow of devotion, K·πõ·π£·πáa‚Äôs devotees are feeling great satisfaction (<span class="e3">tu·π£yanti</span>). And above this is the higher kind of satisfaction (<span class="e3">ramanti</span>) experienced in the madhura-rasa. Just as a wife and husband enjoy a particular kind of connection, K·πõ·π£·πáa‚Äôs devotees feel ecstasy (<span class="e3">ramanti</span>) in His connection, simply by talking about Him. Here the ƒÄchƒÅryas have agreed that the word <span class="e3">ramanti</span> indicates consorthood, and that devotees in consorthood can experience the very deep connection of husband and wife in relation to K·πõ·π£·πáa. In the company of K·πõ·π£·πáa, they feel the ecstasy of consorthood, <span class="e3">ramanti cha</span>. They also feel that ecstasy even when they are only talking about K·πõ·π£·πáa. This meaning of the word <span class="e3">ramanti</span> has been explained in different places by Vi≈õvanƒÅth, Baladev, Bhakti Vinod ·π¨hƒÅkur, and is also admitted even by ≈öa·πÖkar ƒÄchƒÅrya, who agrees that the word <span class="e3">ramanti</span> indicates consorthood.`},{class:`b51`,text:` Then there is the next nutshell verse of <span class="e3">Bhagavad-gƒ´tƒÅ</span> (10.10):`},{class:`b60`,text:` te·π£ƒÅ·πÅ satata-yuktƒÅnƒÅ·πÅ bhajatƒÅ·πÅ prƒ´ti-p≈´rvakam<br />dadƒÅmi buddhi-yoga·πÅ ta·πÅ yena mƒÅm upayƒÅnti te`},{class:`b43`,text:` ‚ÄúTo those who constantly worship Me with devotion, I give the intelligence by which they can come to Me.‚Äù`},{class:`b44`,text:` This is the ordinary meaning of this verse, but there is a deeper meaning. Here, K·πõ·π£·πáa says, ‚ÄúThose persons who are continuously engaged in Me without interruption (<span class="e3">satata-yuktƒÅnƒÅ·πÅ</span>), who are always in Me, who are connected with Me, who serve Me with great love and respect with their heart‚Äî<span class="e3">dadƒÅmi buddhi-yoga·πÅ ta·πÅ</span>‚ÄîI inspire them with the intelligence by which they will come to Me. They will come to Me in a closer connection.‚Äù But I found that this is redundant. K·πõ·π£·πáa has already said <span class="e3">satata-yuktƒÅnƒÅ·πÅ</span>: ‚ÄúTheir devotion is continuous; they are always there in My connection.‚Äù If they are already in connection with K·πõ·π£·πáa, then we must ask why He would again say, ‚ÄúThey will come to Me.‚Äù`},{class:`b44`,text:` K·πõ·π£·πáa has already said that these devotees talk only of Him, think only of Him, take pleasure in Him, and are always engaged in His service. He says, ‚ÄúThey are always connected with Me without interruption, and they are serving Me with heartfelt love.‚Äù They are already serving with heartfelt love, and then K·πõ·π£·πáa says, ‚ÄúI shall give them the inspiration by which they will come to Me (<span class="e3">MƒÅm upayƒÅnti te</span>).‚Äù This is redundant. It has already been said that they are connected to K·πõ·π£·πáa; how is it that again they will ‚Äúcome to Him‚Äù? How is K·πõ·π£·πáa‚Äôs statement ‚Äúthey come to Me‚Äù to be harmonised? So, I found a deeper meaning to the words <span class="e3">MƒÅm upayƒÅnti te</span>. I took here the word <span class="e3">upayƒÅnti</span>, which ordinarily means ‚Äúthey come‚Äù, to indicate <span class="e3">upapati</span>, or ‚Äúparamour‚Äù. So, <span class="e3">upayƒÅnti</span>, ‚Äúthey come to Me‚Äù, means they consider K·πõ·π£·πáa as <span class="e3">upapati</span>, as a paramour.`},{class:`b44`,text:` In society, there is the lawful husband, or pati, and there is the paramour, or upapati. In V·πõndƒÅvan, K·πõ·π£·πáa is not considered by the gopƒ´s as their lawfully married husband, but as master, as the Lord, of their hearts.`},{class:`b44`,text:` Here K·πõ·π£·πáa says, ‚ÄúI inspire those who are constantly engaged in devotional service to come to Me.‚Äù Which devotees does K·πõ·π£·πáa here inspire? Those who are <span class="e3">ramanti</span>, the highest group of devotees, those who are related to him in consorthood, in full rasa‚Äîmukhya-rasa. K·πõ·π£·πáa says here, ‚ÄúI inspire them to come to Me, considering Me as paramour, upapati.‚Äù Here K·πõ·π£·πáa says <span class="e3">bhajatƒÅ·πÅ prƒ´ti p≈´rvakam</span>: this means <span class="e3">prema</span>, which is generally found in madhura-rasa, consorthood. So, the real meaning of this verse is that K·πõ·π£·πáa inspires those who are in consorthood to come to Him, seeing Him as paramour, upapati. And how do they come to Him? He inspires them to come to Him without any consideration of social and scriptural demands. And so, inspired by Him from within, crossing the line of scriptural and social regulations, and even deceiving their own husbands, the gopƒ´s are united with K·πõ·π£·πáa in paramour consorthood (parakƒ´ya).`},{class:`b44`,text:` K·πõ·π£·πáa‚Äôs position is absolute, and He relishes more the devotion of those who can cross everything for Him. And He inspires His devotees from within with this message: ‚ÄúExternally you have to fulfil social and scriptural demands, but My position is over and above the scriptures. My position is above whatever the social laws and scriptural laws tell you to do. I am above the Vedas and everything else. The Vedas are My instructions for the ordinary people. Their instructions are meant for those who are deviated from Me. Society is also under the guidance of those instructions which were given to the fallen. But My connection with everything is intrinsic; it is independent of the laws of scripture and society. I do not require recognition from anyone. My connection with everything is the constant in all equations. It can never be avoided. So, you must neglect all the demands from your previous life‚Äôs connections and come to Me. You have no freedom to do anything else. When your devotional nature will come to demand you to come to Me, you are not free. Your heart must come towards Me.‚Äù`},{class:`b44`,text:` That is upapati, paramour devotion. The devotion of V·πõndƒÅvan. V·πõndƒÅvan-bhajan means paramour devotion: <span class="e3">yena MƒÅm upayƒÅnti te</span>. So here, K·πõ·π£·πáa says that to those who are <span class="e3">ramanti</span>, who are already inclined to come in connection with Him in consorthood as husband and wife, He gives some special feeling and inspiration within their hearts, and they shall come to Him as upapati, as paramours. Here K·πõ·π£·πáa is saying, in effect, ‚ÄúThis paramour devotion is so great that it crosses the rules of both society and scripture. It is independent of everything. Connection with Me is independent of everything that you can conceive. It is most innate and natural. It does not require any scriptural or any social sanction. You may live in society showing formal respect to scriptural and social convention, but from your inner heart of hearts you are Mine. That is <span class="e3">yena MƒÅm upayƒÅnti te</span>, the special instruction or nature or insight I give to these devotees.‚Äù`},{class:`b51`,text:` In other words, these devotees do not allow a second pati or husband to come between them and K·πõ·π£·πáa. They cannot tolerate the interpolation of any second thing, even if it involves social laws or scriptural regulations. Their devotion is so high that all the Vedas are searching after this idea, this divine position:`},{class:`b59`,text:` ƒÅsƒÅm aho chara·πáa-re·πáu-ju·π£ƒÅm aha·πÅ syƒÅ·πÅ<br />v·πõndƒÅvane kim api gulma-latau·π£adhƒ´nƒÅm<br />yƒÅ dustyaja·πÅ sva-janam ƒÅrya-patha√± cha hitvƒÅ<br />bhejur mukunda-padavƒ´·πÅ ≈õrutibhir vim·πõgyƒÅm`},{class:`b54`,text:` (≈örƒ´mad BhƒÅgavatam: 10.47.61)`},{class:`b43`,text:` ‚ÄúAlthough the most exalted devotion of the gopƒ´s is only hinted at in the Vedas, I can now understand their most exalted position. O when shall I take birth as a creeper in V·πõndƒÅvan, so that I can take the dust of the lotus feet of the gopƒ´s upon my head? Those great souls gave up society, friendship, love, their relatives‚Äîand even the Vedic principles‚Äîto take shelter of the holy lotus feet of K·πõ·π£·πáa.‚Äù`},{class:`b44`,text:` Here, one thing should be mentioned: <span class="e3">parakƒ´ya-bhƒÅva</span> has a broader application. It does not only mean paramour devotion. This feeling of crossing scriptural and social rules for an ‚Äòunsanctioned‚Äô relationship is found not only in madhura-rasa or consorthood. <span class="e3">Parakƒ´ya</span> literally means ‚Äúbelonging to another‚Äù. VƒÅtsalya-rasa, parental affection, and sakhya-rasa, friendship, are also infused with the sentiments of parakƒ´ya. This is the method of love for those who follow rƒÅga-mƒÅrg.`},{class:`b44`,text:` In the case of Ya≈õodƒÅ, parakƒ´ya takes the following form: Ya≈õodƒÅ says, ‚ÄúSome people say that K·πõ·π£·πáa is not my son. They say that he is Devakƒ´‚Äôs son!‚Äù This feeling enhances her heart‚Äôs affection towards K·πõ·π£·πáa, for then she thinks, ‚ÄúI could lose Him at any moment.‚Äù This idea draws more intense affection towards K·πõ·π£·πáa. It increases the affection of her service.`},{class:`b44`,text:` In sakhya-rasa, the sentiments of parakƒ´ya are also found. ‚ÄúSome say K·πõ·π£·πáa has come from MathurƒÅ and He may again go to MathurƒÅ. He does not belong to us; he is not exclusively our friend.‚Äù This apprehension also fills the minds of the cowherd boys, and they become anxious, thinking, ‚ÄúWe may lose Him at any time.‚Äù So, that sentiment makes friendly service towards Him more intense. In this way, the whole sentiment in V·πõndƒÅvan is parakƒ´ya.`},{class:`b44`,text:` In the mood of servanthood, or dƒÅsya-rasa, also there is some sentiment like that. Devotees feel, ‚ÄúSome say that K·πõ·π£·πáa comes from MathurƒÅ, that He is the son of Vasudev. He is here only for a while; He is not an ordinary man like us.‚Äù This idea is more or less current in V·πõndƒÅvan. So, parakƒ´ya is not only found in madhura-rasa; K·πõ·π£·πáa may capture all with that sentiment.`},{class:`b44`,text:` Parakƒ´ya is a very special thing in madhura-rasa. Its speciality is that in madhura-rasa it is more objectionable both to the scriptures and to society. But for the gopƒ´s it is not objectionable. In madhura-rasa, they have to cross over the directions of both the Vedas and society‚Äîthey must take that great risk. In other rasas, there is only the fear that ‚ÄúWe may not have K·πõ·π£·πáa permanently, He may go away, He does not belong among us ‚Ä¶‚Äù This suspicion increases the intensity of their service, but in madhura-rasa, they must cross the positive directions of the Veda and society. They must go against these authorities, as if to take the risk of committing sin. This is the special feature of parakƒ´ya in madhura-rasa, so there the intensity of devotion is in its highest condition. So, the inspiration towards parakƒ´ya (<span class="e3">yena MƒÅm upayƒÅnti te</span>) that K·πõ·π£·πáa discusses here with special reference to those who are <span class="e3">ramanti</span>, who are connected to Him in consorthood, is also present in all the servitors in V·πõndƒÅvan.`},{class:`b51`,text:` Finally, we come to the last of the four nutshell verses of <span class="e3">Bhagavad-gƒ´tƒÅ</span> (10.11):`},{class:`b60`,text:` te·π£ƒÅm evƒÅnukampƒÅrtham aham aj√±ƒÅnaja·πÅ tama·∏•<br />na≈õayƒÅmy ƒÅtma-bhƒÅva-stho j√±ƒÅna-dƒ´pena bhƒÅsvatƒÅ`},{class:`b43`,text:` K·πõ·π£·πáa says: ‚ÄúTo show them special mercy, I enter their hearts and destroy their ignorance with the lamp of knowledge.‚Äù`},{class:`b51`,text:` The inner meaning of this verse is more difficult to draw out. The words <span class="e3">te·π£ƒÅm evƒÅnukampƒÅrtham</span> may be interpreted in two ways. The external interpretation is that K·πõ·π£·πáa favours His devotees, and the internal explanation is that K·πõ·π£·πáa is saying, ‚ÄúI want their favour. I aspire after the favour of the devotees of the highest order.‚Äù As in <span class="e3">BhƒÅgavatam</span> (10.82.44), K·πõ·π£·πáa says:`},{class:`b60`,text:` mayi bhaktir hi bh≈´tƒÅnƒÅm am·πõtatvƒÅya kalpate<br />di·π£·π≠yƒÅ yad ƒÅsƒ´n mat-sneho bhavatƒ´nƒÅ·πÅ mad-ƒÅpana·∏•`},{class:`b43`,text:` ‚ÄúMy dear gopƒ´s, everyone considers themselves fortunate if they possess devotion for Me, and by that they achieve an eternal life of nectar. But I must admit that I consider Myself most fortunate because I have come in touch with the wonderful affection found in your hearts.‚Äù`},{class:`b44`,text:` Still the paradox is that K·πõ·π£·πáa seems to say that after such grief and continued engagement with K·πõ·π£·πáa, then He gives these higher devotees pure knowledge, and by that knowledge they get salvation by attaining Brahma. That is the point of argument made by the followers of ≈öa·πÖkar ƒÄchƒÅrya. But I have taken it in another direction.`},{class:`b44`,text:` <span class="e3">J√±ƒÅna-dƒ´pena</span> is a troublesome expression‚Äî‚ÄúI enlighten them with knowledge‚Äù‚Äîso I have given another interpretation: when the pangs of separation felt by K·πõ·π£·πáa‚Äôs devotees comes to its extreme stage, K·πõ·π£·πáa suddenly comes and shows Himself. For example, ≈öachƒ´ Devƒ´ feels extreme separation when she cooks for NimƒÅi, and then by His mercy she can see clearly that NimƒÅi has come and taken prasƒÅdam. Similarly in V·πõndƒÅvan, when the pangs of separation reach their highest degree, then suddenly the devotees can see that ‚ÄúK·πõ·π£·πáa is here in our company.‚Äù So, when K·πõ·π£·πáa says that out of His mercy He appears and removes their ignorance, their <span class="e3">aj√±ƒÅna</span>, He means that when the devotees are experiencing separation from Him, He appears before them and removes the darkness they feel from separation. Out of His mercy, He gives them sustenance. And when that sort of medicine has been applied, they can go on further. In V·πõndƒÅvan, when His devotees felt separation, sometimes He had to come and to show His friends, ‚ÄúI am amongst you. I have not left you.‚Äù This is what is meant by dispelling darkness with the light of divine knowledge: <span class="e3">j√±ƒÅna-dƒ´pena bhƒÅsvatƒÅ</span>. Here the word ignorance or <span class="e3">aj√±ƒÅna</span> means j√±ƒÅna-≈õ≈´nyƒÅ-bhakti, knowledge-free devotion. Devotees do not think that they are part and parcel of the lƒ´lƒÅ, the Pastimes of the Supreme God. No, their devotion is free from such calculation. It is j√±ƒÅna-≈õ≈´nyƒÅ-bhakti: most innocent.`},{class:`b44`,text:` Here K·πõ·π£·πáa is saying, ‚ÄúI can‚Äôt tolerate the pangs of separation felt by My devotees. I must run towards them and show them, ‚ÄòI am here, My mother. You see? I am here taking food.‚Äô‚Äù Sometimes ≈öachƒ´ Devƒ´ prepares food for the Deity, and after offering it, she sees that it is all gone. At that time, she thinks, ‚ÄúWas this a dream? I saw NimƒÅi. He was taking prasƒÅd, and of course nothing was left in the pot. But NimƒÅi has gone long ago. But then who has taken this prasƒÅd? What was it I saw? Was it a dream, or has some dog taken the food? Or is it that I forgot? Have I not cooked today? Perhaps I did not give the bhoga to the BƒÅla GopƒÅl Deity. What did I do?‚Äù`},{class:`b44`,text:` In this way, ≈öachƒ´ is confused. This may be seen as her aj√±ƒÅna, her ‚Äòignorance‚Äô. Then, ≈örƒ´ Chaitanya sends some devotee to her, saying, ‚ÄúYou tell all this to my mother: on those days when such things occur I actually go there; I take food from her hand. It is not a dream. Remind My mother of this and console her. Tell her that I come to her and I take her cooked prasƒÅdam. Remind her that this has occurred.‚Äù`},{class:`b51`,text:` So, this is the meaning of the fourth nutshell verse from <span class="e3">Bhagavad-gƒ´tƒÅ</span>: by His mercy K·πõ·π£·πáa removes the darkness of separation from His devotees. And those that remind us of K·πõ·π£·πáa, and thus remove the darkness born of separation from Him, are the real humanitarians. They are distributing the highest cure. The gopƒ´s tell K·πõ·π£·πáa, ‚ÄúWe are suffering from this pang that is created by You. But the messages about Your Pastimes give us life and sustenance. We are eager to hear this, and then we may feel that we are getting our life back. There is no other medicine but Your assurance and consolation: that alone can save us from these pangs of the burning heart.‚Äù This is their statement in <span class="e3">≈örƒ´mad BhƒÅgavatam</span> (10.31.9):`},{class:`b60`,text:` tava kathƒÅm·πõta·πÅ tapta-jƒ´vana·πÅ<br />kavibhir ƒ´·∏çita·πÅ kalma·π£ƒÅpaham<br />≈õrava·πáa-ma·πÖgala·πÅ ≈õrƒ´mad-ƒÅtata·πÅ<br />bhuvi g·πõ·πáanti ye bh≈´ridƒÅ janƒÅ·∏•`},{class:`b55`,text:` ‚ÄúO K·πõ·π£·πáa, we are always suffering in this world, but just hearing the nectar of Your words and Pastimes gives us life and as a by-product it removes all of our sinful reactions. This sort of hearing is all-auspicious and fills us with spiritual wealth. Those who deliver this message of Godhead are doing the highest relief work for human society and are actually the greatest humanitarians.‚Äù`}]},{title:`The GƒÅyatrƒ´ Mantra`,paragraphs:[{class:`b46`,text:`\r`},{class:`b47`,text:` The GƒÅyatrƒ´ Mantra`},{class:`b43`,text:` The meaning of the Brahma-gƒÅyatrƒ´ must bring us to the conclusion of <span class="e3">≈örƒ´mad BhƒÅgavatam</span>. The gƒÅyatrƒ´-mantra and the <span class="e3">≈örƒ´mad BhƒÅgavatam</span> are one and the same. It is the very gist of the <span class="e3">VedƒÅnta-s≈´tra</span>. <span class="e3">≈örƒ´mad BhƒÅgavatam</span> is the elaborate commentary of gƒÅyatrƒ´:`},{class:`b59`,text:` artho ‚Äôya·πÅ brahma-s≈´trƒÅ·πáƒÅ·πÅ bhƒÅratƒÅrtha-vinir·πáaya·∏•<br />gƒÅyatrƒ´-bhƒÅ·π£ya-rupo ‚Äôsau vedƒÅrtha-parib·πõ·πÅhita·∏•`},{class:`b54`,text:` (Garu·∏ça-purƒÅ·πáa)`},{class:`b43`,text:` The meaning of the gƒÅyatrƒ´-mantra must be in the line of <span class="e3">≈örƒ´mad BhƒÅgavatam</span>. If we analyse how this is possible, we shall uncover the steps leading the gƒÅyatrƒ´-mantra to the <span class="e3">≈örƒ´mad BhƒÅgavatam</span>.`},{class:`b44`,text:` What is the meaning of <span class="e3">gƒÅyatrƒ´</span>? The word <span class="e3">gƒÅyatrƒ´</span> is a combination of two Sanskrit words: <span class="e3">gƒÅnat</span> (what is sung) and <span class="e3">trƒÅyate</span> (gives deliverance). This means, ‚ÄúA kind of song by which we can get our salvation, relief, emancipation.‚Äù GƒÅyatrƒ´ is known as Veda-mƒÅtƒÅ, the mother of the Vedas. And GƒÅyatrƒ´ has produced the whole Veda. If we examine the Vedic conclusion from its most condensed aphorism to its most extensive expression, we shall find that it begins with <span class="e3">O·πÅkƒÅr</span>: the Vedic syllable <span class="e3">Om</span>. That truth is expressed as the gƒÅyatrƒ´-mantra, then it appears in the form of the Vedas, and then as the <span class="e3">VedƒÅnta-s≈´tra</span>. Finally, the Vedic conclusion is given its fullest expression in the <span class="e3">≈örƒ´mad BhƒÅgavatam</span>. Since the meaning, the purpose of Vedic knowledge progresses in this line, the gƒÅyatrƒ´-mantra must contain within it the meaning of <span class="e3">≈örƒ´mad BhƒÅgavatam</span>‚Äîthat is, that the K·πõ·π£·πáa conception of Godhead is the highest.`},{class:`b44`,text:` This must be the meaning of the gƒÅyatrƒ´-mantra, but the problem is how to extract <span class="e3">≈örƒ´mad BhƒÅgavatam</span>‚Äîthe K·πõ·π£·πáa conception‚Äîfrom within the womb of gƒÅyatrƒ´. I heard that Jƒ´va GoswƒÅmƒ´ has given such an interpretation, but I could not find where it is written. I heard that he has given the meaning of gƒÅyatrƒ´ leading to K·πõ·π£·πáa consciousness. Anyhow, the tendency awakened in me to draw the meaning to the K·πõ·π£·πáa conception.`},{class:`b44`,text:` The general meaning of gƒÅyatrƒ´ is ‚Äúthat song which grants liberation‚Äù. Liberation must have some positive meaning. Liberation means not freedom from the negative side, but positive attainment. This is the definition given in <span class="e3">≈örƒ´mad BhƒÅgavatam</span>: <span class="e3">muktir hitvƒÅnyathƒÅ r≈´pa·πÅ svar≈´pe·πáa vyavasthiti·∏•</span>‚Äîunless and until we attain the highest possible positive position, real mukti, real salvation, has not been effected. Mere withdrawal from the negative plane cannot be called liberation. Hegel has said that the object of our life is self-determination. We must determine our normal function in the organic whole‚Äînot mere emancipation from the negative side but participation in a positive function in the domain of service. This is considered to be the highest attainment of life. This is the real meaning of gƒÅyatrƒ´.`},{class:`b44`,text:` The word <span class="e3">gƒÅyatrƒ´</span> comes from two Sanskrit roots: <span class="e3">gƒÅnat</span> and <span class="e3">trƒÅyate</span>. <span class="e3">TrƒÅyate</span> means positive attainment to the final stage (<span class="e3">svar≈´pena vyavasthiti·∏•</span>). And <span class="e3">gƒÅnat</span> means not mere sound, but musical sound. That musical sound which grants us the highest positive deliverance indicates the sa·πÖkƒ´rtan of ≈örƒ´ Chaitanya MahƒÅprabhu and the flute-song of ≈örƒ´ K·πõ·π£·πáa.`},{class:`b44`,text:` The purport of the Brahma-gƒÅyatrƒ´-mantra is as follows: The first word is <span class="e3">Om</span>. <span class="e3">Om</span> is the seed mantra which contains everything within it. The next word is <span class="e3">bh≈´r</span>. Bh≈´r is where we are, Bh≈´loka, the world of our experience. The next word is <span class="e3">bhuva·∏•</span>. Bhuvaloka is the world of mental acquisition. It is the support, the background of our experience. Our present position of experience is the effect of our mental acquisition. That we are here in the world of experience is not an accident; we have acquired this position by our previous karma. The physical sphere, this present world of experience, is only the product, the outcome of our previous mental impulses. And the subtle world of previous karma, the mental sphere, is known as Bhuvaloka.`},{class:`b44`,text:` The next word in the mantra is <span class="e3">sva·∏•</span>. Above Bhuvaloka is Svaloka. The mental world (Bhuvaloka) means acceptance and rejection: what to do and what not to do‚Äî‚ÄúI like this, I don‚Äôt like that.‚Äù Svaloka, however, is the plane of decision, the world of intelligence (Buddhiloka). Our intelligence tells us, ‚ÄúYou may like this, but don‚Äôt do that, for then you will be the loser.‚Äù That plane, the plane of reason, is known as Svaloka. In this way, this material world is composed of three general layers, Bh≈´, the physical world, Bhuva, the mental world, and Sva, the intellectual world.`},{class:`b44`,text:` Of course, a more detailed analysis will reveal seven layers: Bh≈´, Bhuva, Sva, Maha, Jana, Tapa, and Satyaloka. This has been dealt with in detail by SanƒÅtan GoswƒÅmƒ´ in his <span class="e3">B·πõhad-bhƒÅgavatƒÅm·πõtam</span>. Here, these seven strata have been summarised in three planes of existence: physical, mental, and intellectual. And these three planes of experience have been summarised in a word, <span class="e3">tat</span>.`},{class:`b44`,text:` The next word in the brahma-gƒÅyatrƒ´ is <span class="e3">savitur</span>. <span class="e3">Savitur</span> generally means s≈´rya, the sun. And the sun means, figuratively, that which shows or illuminates; that by which we can see. The three gross and subtle strata within this world are shown to us by a particular thing, <span class="e3">savitur</span>. What is that? The soul. Actually, the world is not shown to us by the sun, but by the soul. What really gives us perception and allows us to see gross things? It is not actually the sun that helps us see; we see with the help of the soul. This is found in <span class="e3">Bhagavad-gƒ´tƒÅ</span> (<span class="e3">yathƒÅ prakƒÅ≈õayaty eka·∏• k·πõtsna·πÅ lokam ima·πÅ ravi·∏•</span>). The soul reveals this world to us just as the sun does. The sun can show colour to our eyes, the ear can reveal the sound world, and the hand can reveal the touch world. But really in the centre is the soul. It is the soul who gives light to this world, who gives us an understanding of the environment, the world of perception. All perception is possible only because of the soul. Here, the word <span class="e3">savitur</span>, which generally means sun, can only mean soul, for the soul, like the sun, shows us everything.`},{class:`b44`,text:` All seven strata of our existence‚Äîrepresented by Bh≈´, the physical plane, Bhuva, the mental plane, and Sva, the intellectual plane‚Äîhave here been reduced to one entity: <span class="e3">tat</span>‚Äî‚Äúthat‚Äù. ‚ÄúThat‚Äù is shown by the sun which in this context indicates the soul. Here soul means individual soul. The individual soul is the cause of his world. Not that the mind is in the world, but the world is in the mind. Berkeley has said that the world is in the mind. Here it is being expressed that everything is seen with the help of the sun. If there is no sun, everything is dark‚Äînothing can be seen. So without light, nothing can be seen. And in a higher sense, light means the soul. The soul is the subject, and the soul‚Äôs object is the seven planes of experience within this world.`},{class:`b44`,text:` The next word in the gƒÅyatrƒ´-mantra is <span class="e3">vare·πáya·πÅ</span>. <span class="e3">Vare·πáya·πÅ</span> means p≈´ja: worshippable, venerable. This indicates that although within this plane‚Äîthe objective world‚Äîthe soul is the subject, there is another domain which is to be venerated and worshipped by the soul. That is the Supersoul area.`},{class:`b44`,text:` That worshippable plane of transcendental existence is known as <span class="e3">bhargo</span>. <span class="e3">Bhargo</span> means the supersubjective area, the area of the Supersoul. This is mentioned in the first verse of <span class="e3">≈örƒ´mad BhƒÅgavatam</span>: <span class="e3">dhƒÅmnƒÅ svena sadƒÅ nirasta-kuhaka·πÅ satya·πÅ para·πÅ dhƒ´mahi</span>. ≈örƒ´la VyƒÅsadev says that here he is going to deal with another world whose pristine glory is so great that by its own ray, all misconceptions are brushed aside. The subject is the soul, and its object is all these worlds of experience. And the supersubject is the venerable area which is superior to the subject, the soul‚Äîthat is the supersubjective area.`},{class:`b44`,text:` The word <span class="e3">bhargo</span> means ‚Äúmore subtle than the soul‚Äù and ‚Äúholding a more important position than the soul‚Äù. So this means the Supersoul, the ParamƒÅtmƒÅ. In general, of course, the word <span class="e3">bhargo</span> ordinarily means light. Just as an X-ray can show us what the ordinary eye cannot see, <span class="e3">bhargo</span> is svar≈´p-≈õakti: higher, more powerful light that can reveal the soul. And that energy‚Äî<span class="e3">bhargo</span>‚Äîbelongs to whom? It belongs to Deva. What is the meaning of the word <span class="e3">deva</span>? <span class="e3">Deva</span> means ‚Äúwho is beautiful and playful‚Äù, that is, ≈örƒ´ K·πõ·π£·πáa: Reality the Beautiful. He is not a nondifferentiated substance but is full of lƒ´lƒÅ, Pastimes. <span class="e3">Deva</span> means Pastimes and beauty combined, and this means K·πõ·π£·πáa.`},{class:`b44`,text:` His domain is <span class="e3">bhargo</span>, brilliant, and it is <span class="e3">vare·πáya·πÅ</span>, to be venerated by the jƒ´va-soul. What is the nature of the svar≈´p-≈õakti? It is the vaibhava, the extension of ≈örƒ´matƒ´ RƒÅdhƒÅrƒÅ·πáƒ´. She holds the full service responsibility and the energy to serve K·πõ·π£·πáa. <span class="e3">Bhargo</span> is no less than the vaibhava, the extended body of ≈örƒ´matƒ´ RƒÅdhƒÅrƒÅ·πáƒ´, which contains everything for the service of K·πõ·π£·πáa. <span class="e3">Bhargo</span> represents MahƒÅbhƒÅva, the predominated moiety, and Deva, K·πõ·π£·πáa, is RasarƒÅj, the predominating moiety.`},{class:`b44`,text:` In the gƒÅyatrƒ´-mantra, we are requested, ‚Äú<span class="e3">Bhargo devasya dhƒ´mahi</span>: come meditate.‚Äù What sort of meditation is possible in that plane of dedication? Not abstract meditation, but service cultivation, K·πõ·π£·πáƒÅnu≈õƒ´lanam. <span class="e3">Dhƒ´mahi</span> means ‚Äúto participate in the spontaneous flow, the current of devotion in V·πõndƒÅvan‚Äù. And what will be the result? <span class="e3">Dhiyo yo na·∏• prachodayƒÅt</span>: the capacity of our cultivation will be increased. As we serve, a greater capacity and willingness to serve will be given to us in remuneration‚Äîjust as interest is added to capital in the bank (<span class="e3">dƒÅsa kari‚Äô vetana more deha prema-dhana</span>). In this way, our dedicating principle will be increased again and again. <span class="e3">Dhƒ´mahi</span> means ƒÅrƒÅdhana, worship. It cannot but be explained in terms of ƒÅrƒÅdhana, p≈´jƒÅ, sevƒÅ‚Äîworship, adoration, loving service. The word <span class="e3">dhƒ´</span> is derived from the word <span class="e3">buddhi</span>, which generally means ‚Äúthat which we cultivate with the help of our intelligence‚Äù. But here, <span class="e3">dhƒ´</span> is a reference to that venerable intelligence which descends into this plane to help us cultivate service. So, <span class="e3">dhƒ´mahi</span> does not mean abstract meditation, but devotional service. This is the underlying meaning of the gƒÅyatrƒ´-mantra.`},{class:`b44`,text:` GƒÅyatrƒ´, the song for deliverance, also means sa·πÖkƒ´rtan. Kƒ´rtan is also sung, and it also improves us towards the highest goal. The sa·πÖkƒ´rtan of ≈örƒ´ Chaitanya MahƒÅprabhu also reinstates us in our highest serving position. So, Brahma-gƒÅyatrƒ´ in connection with MahƒÅprabhu comes to mean K·πõ·π£·πáa-kƒ´rtan. Then it reaches V·πõndƒÅvan and the flute-kƒ´rtan. And when we enter V·πõndƒÅvan, we shall find that the sweet sound of K·πõ·π£·πáa‚Äôs flute helps to engage all the Lord‚Äôs servants in their respective duties. When the flute is sounded, the gopƒ´s and others are adjusted in their respective duties. At night, the gopƒ´s, hearing the sound of the flute, will run to the YamunƒÅ, thinking, ‚ÄúOh, K·πõ·π£·πáa is there.‚Äù And when Ya≈õodƒÅ hears the song of K·πõ·π£·πáa‚Äôs flute, she thinks, ‚ÄúMy son is there. He is coming home soon.‚Äù In this way, the sound of the flute engages all the servants of the Lord in their respective positions and inspires them to be mindful of their service.`},{class:`b44`,text:` In my Sanskrit commentary on the gƒÅyatrƒ´-mantra, I have written, ‚Äú<span class="e3">Dhƒ´r ƒÅrƒÅdhanam eva nƒÅnyad iti tad RƒÅdhƒÅ-pada·πÅ dhƒ´mahi</span>: all other services are represented fully in RƒÅdhikƒÅ.‚Äù Like branches they are all part of Her. Madhura-rasa is the chief or mukhya-rasa, the combination of all rasas.`},{class:`b44`,text:` ≈örƒ´matƒ´ RƒÅdhƒÅrƒÅ·πáƒ´ is MahƒÅbhƒÅva‚ÄîShe represents the entire serving attitude.`},{class:`b44`,text:` The flute-song of ≈örƒ´ K·πõ·π£·πáa, expressed as the gƒÅyatrƒ´-mantra, is reminding us and engaging us in our service. And what is our service? Our service must be to surrender ourselves in the service of ≈örƒ´matƒ´ RƒÅdhƒÅrƒÅ·πáƒ´‚Äîto accept the suggestion of RƒÅdhƒÅrƒÅ·πáƒ´. The gƒÅyatrƒ´-mantra will excite us to be mindful about ≈örƒ´matƒ´ RƒÅdhƒÅrƒÅ·πáƒ´‚Äôs lotus feet, to obey Her orders. She is mainly representing the whole serving area. So, to try to engage ourselves in Her service, under Her order‚Äîto accept Her direction and to obey Her‚Äîthat is the service of ≈örƒ´ RƒÅdhƒÅ. In this way, the meaning of the gƒÅyatrƒ´-mantra has been drawn to rƒÅdhƒÅ-dƒÅsyam, self-determination (<span class="e3">svar≈´pe·πáa vyavasthiti·∏•</span>).`},{class:`b44`,text:` In the meantime, the partial representations in vƒÅtsalya and sakhya-rasa are also part and parcel of the original mellow of conjugal love, madhura-rasa. The vƒÅtsalya-rasa devotee will serve Nanda and Ya≈õodƒÅ, the sakhya-rasa devotee will serve ≈örƒ´dƒÅmƒÅ and SudƒÅmƒÅ, but ultimately, the whole system in one conception is included in RƒÅdhƒÅrƒÅ·πáƒ´.`},{class:`b44`,text:` RƒÅdhƒÅ-dƒÅsyam, the service of ≈örƒ´matƒ´ RƒÅdhƒÅrƒÅ·πáƒ´, is the ultimate meaning to be extracted from the gƒÅyatrƒ´-mantra. That is the supreme end of our life. It cannot but be so. <span class="e3">≈örƒ´mad BhƒÅgavatam</span> is the ultimate or full-fledged theism to be extracted from the Vedas, Upani·π£ads, and so many scriptures. All the revealed truth rises to its acme, to its highest position, in the conception given by <span class="e3">≈örƒ´mad BhƒÅgavatam</span>. And <span class="e3">≈örƒ´mad BhƒÅgavatam</span> teaches us that the highest realisation, self-determination, is to be found in the service of ≈örƒ´matƒ´ RƒÅdhƒÅrƒÅ·πáƒ´‚Äîthat under Her guidance we may serve ≈örƒ´ K·πõ·π£·πáa. We aspire for a direct connection with Her service.`},{class:`b44`,text:` What, then, is the inner meaning and purport of the word <span class="e3">bhargo</span>? <span class="e3">Bhargo vai v·πõ·π£abhƒÅnujƒÅtmƒÅ-vibhavaika-ƒÅrƒÅdhana-≈õrƒ´-puram</span>. <span class="e3">BhƒÅnu</span> means the sun, or ‚Äúwho shows us by light‚Äù. RƒÅdhƒÅrƒÅ·πáƒ´ is the daughter of V·πõ·π£abhƒÅnu. So, I selected the word <span class="e3">bhƒÅnu</span>. To represent Her personal extended self, I have given the word <span class="e3">vaibhava</span>. <span class="e3">Vaibhava</span> means, ‚Äúwhat comes out‚Äù or ‚Äúextended self‚Äù. PrƒÅbhava is the central representation and vaibhava is the outer extension. The very gist of svar≈´p-≈õakti is ≈örƒ´matƒ´ RƒÅdhƒÅrƒÅ·πáƒ´, and the whole svar≈´p-≈õakti is Her extended self. The town of Her beautiful service, that is, the country, the abode of Her beautiful service ,is the whole svar≈´p-≈õakti.`},{class:`b44`,text:` Just as rays of light extend from the sun, the whole internal potency is an extension of MahƒÅbhƒÅva, ≈örƒ´ RƒÅdhikƒÅ. She has developed Herself into such a beautiful area of brilliance, of internal energy, and thereby She serves Her Lord. All these necessary things have sprung from Her. To help Her in serving Her Lord, they all come out. When the entire internal energy is condensed in a concise form, it is MahƒÅbhƒÅva, RƒÅdhƒÅrƒÅ·πáƒ´. And when RƒÅdhƒÅrƒÅ·πáƒ´ wants to serve, She extends Herself in limitless different ways. And with some contribution from Baladev and YogamƒÅyƒÅ, the whole spiritual world, including V·πõndƒÅvan, MathurƒÅ, and Vaiku·πá·π≠ha, evolves to assist ≈örƒ´matƒ´ RƒÅdhƒÅrƒÅ·πáƒ´ in the service of ≈örƒ´ K·πõ·π£·πáa.`},{class:`b44`,text:` In this way, I have drawn out RƒÅdhƒÅ-dƒÅsyam, the service of ≈örƒ´matƒ´ RƒÅdhƒÅrƒÅ·πáƒ´, as the meaning of the gƒÅyatrƒ´-mantra and have tried to represent it in Sanskrit verse.`},{class:`b52`,text:` Gauraharibol!`}]},{title:`About The Author`,paragraphs:[{class:`b46`,text:`\r`},{class:`b47`,text:` About The Author`},{class:`b43`,text:` His Divine Grace ≈örƒ´la Bhakti Rak·π£ak ≈örƒ´dhar Dev-GoswƒÅmƒ´ MahƒÅrƒÅj was born in Hapaniya, West Bengal, India in 1895. In 1927 he was initiated as a disciple of ≈örƒ´la PrabhupƒÅd Bhakti SiddhƒÅnta Saraswatƒ´ ·π¨hƒÅkur, the Founder-ƒÄchƒÅrya of the Gau·∏çƒ´ya Ma·π≠h and foremost Vai·π£·πáava scholar of the twentieth century. ≈örƒ´la ≈örƒ´dhar MahƒÅrƒÅj‚Äôs scriptural genius, penetrating realisations, and strict practice of the devotional principles of Gau·∏çƒ´ya‚ÄìVai·π£·πáavism were soon recognised by ≈örƒ´la Bhakti SiddhƒÅnta Saraswatƒ´, who in 1930 awarded him the renounced order of sannyƒÅs. He was named Bhakti Rak·π£ak ≈örƒ´dhar, or ‚Äúguardian of devotion‚Äù after the original <span class="e3">BhƒÅgavatam</span> commentator ≈örƒ´dhar SwƒÅmƒ´pƒÅd.`},{class:`b44`,text:` Bhakti SiddhƒÅnta Saraswatƒ´ saw him as especially fit to protect the Gau·∏çiya‚ÄìVai·π£·πáava line from misrepresentation. After reading one of his Sanskrit compositions glorifying Bhakti Vinod ·π¨hƒÅkur, Bhakti SiddhƒÅnta Saraswatƒ´ remarked, ‚ÄúNow I am satisfied that, after I leave, there will be at least one man who can represent my conclusions (bhakti-siddhƒÅnta).‚Äù`},{class:`b44`,text:` After the passing of ≈örƒ´la Bhakti SiddhƒÅnta Saraswatƒ´, ≈örƒ´la ≈örƒ´dhar MahƒÅrƒÅj established his own temple, ≈örƒ´ Chaitanya SƒÅraswat Ma·π≠h, on the banks of the sacred Ganges in Nabadwƒ´p DhƒÅm, the holy land of ≈örƒ´ Chaitanya MahƒÅprabhu. Having deeply assimilated the teachings of ≈örƒ´ Chaitanya, he began composing original texts. His first work, <span class="e3">≈örƒ´ ≈örƒ´ Prapanna-jƒ´vanƒÅm·πõtam</span>, was a comprehensive scriptural study of surrender. His Divine Grace composed numerous songs, prayers, and commentaries. Among these important works are his commentary on Bhakti Vinod ·π¨hƒÅkur‚Äôs <span class="e3">≈öara·πáƒÅgati</span>, Bengali translations of <span class="e3">Bhagavad-gƒ´tƒÅ</span> and <span class="e3">Bhakti-rasƒÅm·πõta-sindhu</span>, and his own original Sanskrit poem summarising Chaitanya-lƒ´lƒÅ, <span class="e3">Prema-dhƒÅma-deva-stotram</span>. An outstanding contribution to the R≈´pƒÅnuga‚ÄìGau·∏çƒ´ya sampradƒÅya is his commentary on the gƒÅyatrƒ´-mantra in the line of <span class="e3">≈örƒ´mad BhƒÅgavatam</span>.`},{class:`b44`,text:` Original works in English translation include: <span class="e3">The Hidden Treasure of the Sweet Absolute</span> (<span class="e3">Bhagavad-gƒ´tƒÅ</span>) and<span class="e3"> Life-Nectar of the Surrendered Souls: Positive and Progressive Immortality</span> (<span class="e3">≈örƒ´ ≈örƒ´ Prapanna-jƒ´vanƒÅm·πõtam</span>).`},{class:`b44`,text:` At an advanced age in his fully matured stage of realisation, ≈örƒ´la ≈örƒ´dhar MahƒÅrƒÅj spoke extensively on the teachings of ≈örƒ´la Saraswatƒ´ ·π¨hƒÅkur, Bhakti Vinod ·π¨hƒÅkur, and the great predecessor ƒÄchƒÅryas. Some of his English language publications are: <span class="e3">The Search for ≈örƒ´ K·πõ·π£·πáa: Reality the Beautiful</span>, <span class="e3">≈örƒ´ Guru and His Grace</span>, <span class="e3">The Golden Volcano of Divine Love</span>, <span class="e3">Loving Search for the Lost Servant</span>, <span class="e3">Subjective Evolution of Consciousness: The Play of the Sweet Absolute</span>, <span class="e3">≈örƒ´ ≈örƒ´ Prapanna-jivanƒÅm·πõtam: Life Nectar of the Surrendered Souls</span>, <span class="e3">Heart and Halo</span>, <span class="e3">Holy Engagement</span>, <span class="e3">The Golden Staircase</span>, <span class="e3">Home Comfort</span>, <span class="e3">Inner Fulfilment</span> and <span class="e3">Sermons of The Guardian of Devotion I‚ÄîIV</span>.`},{class:`b52`,text:` After his passing in 1988, he was succeeded by his dearmost beloved disciple and appointed successor, ≈örƒ´la Bhakti Sundar Govinda Dev-GoswƒÅmƒ´ MahƒÅrƒÅj.`}]}],r={title:e,code:t,chapters:n};export{n as chapters,t as code,r as default,e as title};